<HEAD>Married Couple New Co-Editors At U.S. News</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A husband-wife team is taking over as
co-editors of U.S. News &amp; World Report, a spokeswoman for the
magazine said Friday.
   Michael Ruby and Merrill McLoughlin will take over the post Oct.
23, replacing Roger Rosenblatt, who resigned on Thursday night,
said Kathy Bushkin.
   Before their promotions Ms. McLoughlin, 44, was a senior editor
at the magazine and Ruby, 47, was executive editor.
   Rosenblatt is resigning because the commute between the
magazine's headquarters in Washington and his home in New York was
disrupting his family life, Ms. Bushkin said.
   However, The Washington Post reported in its Saturday editions
that Rosenblatt was quitting because of a conflict with the
magazine's publisher, Mortimer Zuckerman.
</TEXT>
