<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Syria     10-13 0663</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Syria,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian Says He Flew `Into the Unknown' In Search of Freedom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Syrian pilot who landed his plane in
Israel said today he defected because he wanted to live in a
democracy and would refuse any offer by the Red Cross to return him
to Syria.
   Syria has denied the pilot was a defector and asked the Red
Cross to intervene.
   Maj. Mohammed Bassam Adel refused to answer most political
questions at a news conference arranged by the Israeli army, but he
said Syrian pilots considered Israel's air force superior to their
own.
   He recounted how he flew across the border at high speed and as
low as 30 yards off the ground, ``going into the unknown'' in
search of freedom and a place to land.
   He said he made the decision to defect on his own for personal
reasons and had no contact with anyone in Israel before he piloted
his Soviet-built MiG-23 over the Golan Heights from Syria on
Wednesday.
   ``I decided to cross the border in electronic silence,'' he
said. ``I was not in contact with anyone. Nobody was expecting me.
   ``It was a difficult mission. I didn't know where I was going to
land. I didn't know if I would find a facility to land. I was going
into the unknown,'' the 34-year-old flier told Israeli and foreign
reporters.
   Much has been made in Israel over how Adel crossed the border
without being intercepted, although he reporedly was in Israeli air
space for seven minutes before landing.
   ``The section I was crossing was spread all over with
missiles,'' the short, wiry pilot said. ``I crossed at very low
altitude and very high speed.''
   When asked to be specific, Adel said he flew at 700 to 750 mph
and ``below 50 meters (yards), sometimes 30 meters, sometimes 40.''
   Adel, who was dressed in an olive green flight suit, spoke in
Arabic and his words were translated into English by Israeli
officers. The news conference was held at a military base near Tel
Aviv.
   The pilot said he defected in search of freedom.
   ``I wanted to live in a democracy where people can express their
views with freedom,'' he explained.
   Asked to comment on Syrian politics, he repeated his desire for
freedom and added that ``by implication you can presume my thoughts
about the political system in Syria.''
   Adel was asked whether he would see a representative of the
International Committee of the Red Cross, as Syria has requested.
   ``If the Red Cross wants to meet me and take me back to Syria, I
would refuse this,'' he said.
   Asked if he hoped to remain in Israel, he said, ``I said I
wanted to live in a democracy ... so you might conclude I want to
live here.''
   However, he said he had made no definite decisions about his
future.
   Adel would say little about the MiG-23 he piloted across the
Golan Heights to a civilian airstrip near Megiddo, 57 miles north
of Jerusalem in northern Israel. Nor would he compare it to other
Syrian air force planes.
   He also refused to discuss his family and whether he was
discriminated against because of his Sunni Moslem religion in a
country where the president, Hafez Assad, and many military leaders
belong to the minority Alawite sect.
   Adel said he received ``gentle'' treatment from the Israelis,
was asked mainly about his reasons for defecting and had not yet
been questioned about the Syrian air force.
   When asked if Syrian pilots felt they had gained superiority
over Israel, he replied: ``No one in the Syrian air force feels
that they could defeat Israel, that they are superior to Israel.''
   Adel said he was born in the Syrian town of Aleppo and was a
graduate of Syria's Air Force Academy. He said he decided ``a long
time ago'' to defect and had been planning it seriously for three
to four months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
