<FIRST>r i PM-Norway     10-13 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Norway,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brundtland Steps Down as Norway's Prime Minister</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG MELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland
resigned today, yielding the government to a three-party
non-socialist coalition after 3{ tough years of minority rule.
   Conservative Party Chairman Jan P. Syse, 58, will become prime
minister on Monday. Mrs. Brundtland remains until then as caretaker.
   Mrs. Brundtland's resignation followed a loss by her Labor Party
of eight parliament seats in the Sept. 11 election. The party fell
to 63 seats in the expanded 165-member Storting.
   The 50-year-old prime minister helped topple the same
Conservative-led alliance in 1986, and some analysts predict her
return to power within a year.
   Mrs. Brundtland presented her resignation to King Olav V today
and referred the monarch to Syse about a new government.
   Syse, an attorney, will polish his coalition of the
Conservative, Christian Democratic and Center Parties and assign
Cabinet posts this weekend.
   ``I can assure you the government will be ready at the right
time,'' Syse said after seeing the king.
   The new coalition controls 62 seats. It had the support of the
extreme right 22-seat Party of Progress in its threat to evict
Labor in a no-confidence vote unless Mrs. Brundtland stepped down.
   Labor's ally, the Socialist Left, has 17 seats and there is one
independent.
   Mrs. Brundtland is best known abroad as head of the U.N.
Commission on the Environment and Developement. In opposition, she
is expected to chair parliament's Foreign Affairs Committee.
   The coalition's position is tenuous. The anti-tax Progress Party
has said it won't guarantee support, since the coalition refused to
make it a partner.
   ``They won't last more than a year,'' predicted William
Lafferty, an American political scientist who has lived in Norway
for 22 years.
   Gunnar Vogt of the Institute for Social Research said Syse may
even turn to Labor to support some of his programs to avoid being
held to ransom by the extremist parties.
   ``It's anyone's guess'' whether the coalition can last until
elections in 1993, Vogt said in an interview.
   Norway has no mechanism for early elections, and if Syse can't
hold his partnership together, Mrs. Brundtland probably would move
back into the prime minister's office.
   Mrs. Brundtland was credited for helping to cut inflation in
half, turn a trade deficit into a surplus and slow consumer
spending. But she left the country with postwar record unemployment
of 5 percent.
</TEXT>
