<FIRST>r w PM-Trost-Soviets 1stLd-Writethru a0447 10-13 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trost-Soviets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0447,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Navy Chief: Soviet Arms Control Proposals Present Undue Restrictions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS first name in penultimate graf to Sergei sted Moisev</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. chief of naval operations says Soviet
arms control proposals would place undue restrictions on the Navy's
ability to protect American interests and ``deter aggression.''
   Adm. Carlisle Trost, the first chief of a U.S. military service
to visit the Soviet Union, made the comments Thursday in a speech
to the Leningrad Naval School. A text of his remarks was made
available to The Associated Press.
   The Navy's top man noted with some amusement that he was
spending today, the 214th anniversary of the founding of the U.S.
Navy, ``here in the Soviet Union, visiting ships in your fleet ...
meeting officers and men in your Navy.
   ``I think that my being here marks a milestone in the progress
that our two countries have made in just the past few years toward
improving bilateral relations and easing some of the tension that
has characterized our dialogue for the past four decades,'' Trost
said.
   But the admiral had few kind words to say about Soviet proposals
to limit U.S. naval power around the world.
   Trost mentioned proposals from the Warsaw Pact and others that
would exclude anti-submarine forces from certain security zones;
exclude all naval force activity from certain strategic straits and
high density shipping lanes; limit naval exercises; or place
restrictions on the movement of ships with nuclear-capable weapons.
   ``Any one of these would result in the inability of my Navy to
protect the global interests of the United States or to deter
aggression. Navy forces must be free to operate when and where
deterrent presence is required, and operate unimpeded by
restrictive sanctions,'' Trost said.
   Trost said he also opposed any restrictions on the use of
sea-launched cruise missiles, calling compliance with any such
limitations ``unverifiable without unacceptably intrusive
inspections.''
   The admiral contended the United States is dependent upon
overseas trade for its economic well-being, whereas ``seaborne
trade for the Soviet Union is not a matter of national survival.''
   ``When viewed from this perspective, I strongly feel that my
country's reluctance to enter into naval arms reductions is
justified by the facts and is a prudent and rational position,''
the admiral said.
   Trost also dismissed Soviet calls for limits on the 14 U.S.
aircraft carriers that ply the high seas, calling them the
``backbone'' of the Navy and a useful tool for deterring ``would-be
aggressors.''
   Trost noted that when former Soviet military chief Sergei
Akhromeyev visited the United States, he said the U.S. Navy and its
bases ``threaten the security of the Soviet Union.''
   But Trost said, ``The U.S. strategy is not intended to threaten
anyone.'' U.S. military forces ``are only a threat to someone who
would intend to threaten our interests or those of our allies,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
