<DOCNO> AP891013-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 1103EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Academy-Blacks     10-13 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Academy-Blacks,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Board Members, Athletes Quit Over Private School Racial Issue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two school board members resigned and seven
athletes quit an all-white private school's football team after it
forfeited a game with a school that is fielding a black player.
   ``I just felt it was time I didn't serve on (the board)
anymore,'' said Henry McClellan, a vice president at Holmes
Community College who has been a board member of the East Holmes
Academy for two years. He did not elaborate.
   The resignations and walkout by the players followed
confirmation by East Holmes Headmaster Frank Drake that the school
would not play Columbus Heritage Academy, which has the first black
player in North Central AA Conference history.
   Drake, one of the school's founders, said earlier this week that
race had nothing to do with the decision. He said the action
involved something ``private'' that he could not discuss.
   But several questioned his decision.
   ``It's a racial thing, no question about it,'' said Steve Frank,
whose son was a starting tackle and linebacker before quitting the
team Wednesday.
   Drake refused Thursday to answer additional questions about the
decision.
   A broadcaster also said Thursday in Jackson that former National
Football League player Glen Collins was banned from broadcasting a
game at East Holmes because he is black.
   Lee Adams said he and Collins were scheduled to broadcast the
Jackson Academy-East Holmes game on television on Aug. 25. Collins,
an ex-Mississippi State standout, was told he should not come,
Adams said Thursday.
   Drake denied Adams' charge. ``That was not the case,'' he said.
   Frank Janous, another East Holmes school board member, said he
sent a letter of resignation last Friday after serving on the
governing panel for more than 10 years.
   Asked why he resigned, Janous said: ``I don't want to say ... I
think you probably know.''
   Among the seven atheletes who quit were four starters in
tonight's game against Grenada Kirk Academy. East Holmes has 17
players remaining on its roster.
   ``How do you function?'' asked East Holmes coach Riley Myers.
</TEXT>
