<FIRST>r i PM-Pope     10-13 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Celebrates Final Mass of Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEDAN, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pope today celebrated the final Mass
of his Indonesian tour and urged Catholics here to be bold in
proclaiming Christian values in this predominantly Moslem nation.
   The pontiff stressed themes of family and social teaching at his
final stops but also acknowledged difficulties facing the church in
Indonesia.
   Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro gave a positive summation of
the trip, saying no obstacles had been placed before the pope and
that he spoke with ``absolute freedom.''
   But the pontiff again used guarded language when referring to
potential conflicts with the government or Moslem community.
   His last Mass here was attended by 100,000 people amid lush
coffee and palm oil plantations in North Sumatra.
   In a speech to the country's 42 bishops later in Jakarta, John
Paul urged Catholics to be bold in proclaiming their Christian
values. He acknowledged ``occasional difficulties'' facing his 5
million-member flock but reminded them that religious freedom is
protected by the constitution.
   There are 157 million Moslems in Indonesia.
   ``Do not be afraid to encourage the Catholic people to (be) an
ever more public witness to the truths and values of their faith,
in keeping with their rightful place in the society of which they
are worthy citizens,'' he told the bishops.
   Raising another delicate issue, the pope said ``You are
sometimes painfully aware that certain traditional practices and
other contemporary social influences bring about an obscuring of
fundamental principles regarding family life and the responsible
transmission of life.''
   He did not elaborate but was apparently referring to polygamy
and the government's aggressive birth control program. The church
bars artificial birth control.
   The church as well as the government here is concerned about
increasing pressure from Moslem extremists.
   The Moslem influence is reflected in two proposed laws before
parliament. One would make Islamic religious teaching mandatory in
all schools, including Catholic ones, and the other would set up
Islamic courts for marriages, wills and inheritances.
   The only trouble during the pope's stay occurred Thursday in
East Timor, when youths opposed to Indonesian rule of the former
Portuguese colony clashed with police at the end of the papal mass.
They held up banners greeting the pope in the name of an
anti-Indonesian guerrilla group.
   Navarro said John Paul watched the incident calmly and made no
mention of it afterward.
   The pope is scheduled to leave Saturday for the Indian Ocean
island nation of Mauritius. He returns to Rome on Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
