<DOCNO> AP891013-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 1127EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-GMBiasSuit     10-13 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GM Bias Suit,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeal of GM Racial Discrimination Lawsuit Filed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several black General Motors Corp. workers are
challenging a settlement of a racial descrimination lawsuit against
the company, saying the payout is too small.
   Attorneys said the settlement could cost GM $3 million
immediately and up to $40 million over the next five years.
   An appeal filed Thursday with the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Cincinnati says the case was poorly handled and the
settlement too small.
   Last month, U.S. District Judge John Feikens approved a
settlement of the lawsuit originally filed by four employees in
1983. It became a class action suit three years later involving
10,000 black GM workers in Michigan, Indiana and Ohio.
   The black workers claimed an employee appraisal system, dropped
by the automaker after the suit was filed, resulted in lower pay
and fewer promotions for blacks between 1982 and 1986.
   GM issued a statement Thursday saying the settlement was fair.
   Godfrey Dillard, an attorney who represents a group of black GM
employees challenging the settlement, said the appeal will stop
implementation of the settlement.
   Dennis James, an attorney who negotiated the settlement for the
plaintiffs, said the appeal would cost about $1 million a year in
attorneys' fees.
</TEXT>
