<FIRST>r a PM-Wedtech-Garcia     10-13 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wedtech-Garcia,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Begins Deliberations In Wedtech Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury began deliberating today whether
Rep. Robert Garcia and his wife extorted payoffs from the Wedtech
Corp., a defunct defense contractor.
   U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand, who instructed the jurors
Thursday afternoon, told them to begin their discussions at 10:30
a.m.
   Also Thursday, the panel heard closing arguments from Garcia's
lawyer, who said the prosecution did not prove the couple's guilt.
   ``No one was paying off Bobby Garcia,'' Robert Morvillo said.
Garcia helped Wedtech get government contracts because he was a
good public official, he said.
   The lawyer described Garcia as a dedicated and honest politician
who rose from the ghetto to represent his neighborhood in
Washington.
   ``Bobby Garcia wants nothing more than to go back to the South
Bronx and serve his constituents,'' he said.
   Morvillo said the $76,000 that the government contends was
funneled by Wedtech to Mrs. Garcia's consulting firm to pay for
Garcia's political influence was for work unrelated to Wedtech.
   A $20,000 loan Garcia received from the company was ``a loan
among friends,'' he said.
   He claimed Garcia asked Mario Moreno, the former Wedtech vice
chairman, to make the loan to the congressman's sister, who passed
the money on to Mrs. Garcia, because he knew it wouldn't look right
to take a loan from a constituent.
   Congress members are not required to report loans from family
members on their financial disclosure forms, Morvillo said. He
noted that the loan was promptly repaid.
   Garcia, a 56-year-old Democrat, and his wife, Jane Lee Garcia,
are accused of conspiring to obtain $185,000 in checks and
interest-free loans, and a diamond and emerald necklace for Mrs.
Garcia, from officials of the now-defunct Wedtech Corp.
   The couple was charged in a seven-count indictment with
conspiracy, extortion, bribery and receipt of illegal gratuities.
If convicted of extortion, they face up to 20 years in prison.
   Their trial is the last of several to stem from the scandal at
Wedtech, the small South Bronx machine shop that grew into a
multimillion-dollar defense contractor through various bribe
schemes. The company collapsed in 1986 amid allegations of
corruption.
   Morvillo attacked the credibility of Moreno, the government's
key witness.
   ``Did Mario Moreno lie in this case? Yes,'' Morvillo said. ``He
lied about everything that would incriminate these people.''
   Moreno pleaded guilty to theft- and bribe-related charges in
1987 and testified at other Wedtech trials.
   In the prosecution's rebuttal which followed Morvillo's
arguments, Assistant U.S. Attorney Edward Little denied the
defense's argument that the prosecution presented a one-witness
case.
   He said 27 other witnesses and 500 documents corroborated
Moreno's testimony.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
