<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 1139EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Conservatives     10-13 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Conservatives,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Urges Continued Military Might as Conservatives End Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLACKPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher today
said it has been ``a fantastic year for freedom'' but told her
Conservative Party that despite this, military might must not be
allowed to lag.
   She also scorned the opposition Labor Party for abandoning its
policy of unilateral disarmament, calling it a desperate move to
win votes.
   In a speech to the final session of the Conservative Party's
four-day conference, Mrs. Thatcher also gave strong support to the
Chancellor of the Exchequer, Nigel Lawson, whose recent decision to
boost interest rates has caused discontent within party ranks.
   ``The torch of freedom we lit in Britain all those years ago,
the symbol of our party, has shed its light across the Iron Curtain
into Eastern Europe,'' she said.
   ``What a fantastic year this has been for freedom _ 1989 will be
remembered for decades to come as the year when the people of half
our continent began to throw off their chains.''
   The prime minister turned 64 today, and as she entered the
conference hall, an organist played ``When I'm 64.''
   Despite the changes in the communist world, Mrs. Thatcher said
the potential for conflict lurked around the world.
   ``Yes, we are ready to negotiate to reduce the levels of weapons
on both sides, but only so long as it can be done without
jeopardizing our security,'' she said.
   The opposition Labor Party's call for a 25 percent cut in
defense spending, she said, would endanger that security, and she
scorned Labor's new commitment to multilateral instead of
unilateral disarmament.
   ``Labor's supposed conversion to multilateralism is no more than
a confidence trick to try to make Labor electable,'' she said.
   Turning to economics, Mrs. Thatcher said she understood that
higher interest rates worried home owners, farmers and small
businesses. ``But when the choice is between high rates now, or
persistent higher inflation later, with all the damage that would
do, the choice is clear.
   ``Inflation will come down through the use of high interest
rates as it has in the past,'' she said, and commended Lawson and
his predecessor, Sir Geoffrey Howe, as ``the two finest chancellors
of the exchequer since the war.''
   Interest rates are now at an eight-year high of 15 percent and
will remain high in an effort to curb the 7.3 percent inflation
rate, Lawson said Thursday.
   Despite fears of an economic crisis and persistently poor poll
ratings, the traditionally loyal and well-discplined party
activists have cheered some uncompromising messages from Cabinet
ministers during the conference.
   But outside the conference hall, there have been expressions of
unease.
   ``Many people are feeling rather let down,'' delegate Peter
Brown said Thursday after Lawson announced the continued high
interest rates.
   ``They are rather upset that after 10 years of Conservative rule
we should have got into these rather difficult times,'' Brown said.
   At fringe meetings, there also were signals the Conservatives
need to find a new agenda after dominating the decade with
right-wing policies based on tight money, curbing unions, selling
off nationalized industries and building up Britain's nuclear
arsenal.
   Howe warned that the party needed to ensure that ``people
recognize us as a listening party, just as much as a crusading
one.''
   The interest rates, hitting homeowners and businesses, have
exacerbated the Conservatives' problems, midway through Mrs.
Thatcher's third term. She has been in office 11 years.
   Polls show widespread opposition to key sections of her current
political program _ a shakeup of the National Health Service, plans
to sell off to private enterprise the water and electric utilities,
and a new property tax.
   Meanwhile, the socialist Labor Party has adopted a new, more
moderate platform and is presenting the Conservatives with their
most serious challenge since 1979, when Mrs. Thatcher ousted Prime
Minister James Callaghan's Labor government.
   Labor has been in the lead in poll ratings for the past four
months and now has an average 7-point edge.
</TEXT>
