<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 1225EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Chapman     10-13 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chapman,0335</SECOND>
<UNK>Giant Foot in Flowers for Monty Python Star's Funeral</UNK>
<DATELINE>MAIDSTONE, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The surviving members of Monty
Python's Flying Circus sent flowers in the shape of a giant foot to
Friday's funeral for comedian Graham Chapman.
   ``To Graham from the other five Pythons with all our love. P.S.
Stop us if we're getting too silly,'' said a note attached to the
flowers, modeled on the foot that dropped down with a rude noise to
end the group's television shows.
   The message recalled Chapman's appearances as a stiff-backed
colonel who barged in to end sketches that had become ``too silly.''
   Services for Chapman, who died Oct. 4 at age 48, were held at
Vinters Park crematorium, with close friends and family attending.
   ``Not many of us take the opportunity to express our convictions
in the way that Graham did and he specialized in a brand of humor
which satirized pomposity,'' said the Rev. Tony Porter, chaplain at
Maidstone Hospital where Chapman died.
   Chapman's last words to Porter were: ``The events of this last
year have renewed my faith in human nature.''
   The minister said, ``Through these words we catch a glimpse of
Graham who though vulnerable, overcame many fears.''
   Mourners at the service included Chapman's companion for many
years, David Sherlock, and his adopted son, John Tomiczek.
   Sherlock had planned to stay away from the funeral but had a
last-minute change of mind.
   ``Both Graham and I believed in caring for the living, and not
mourning after the dead. He would have understood why at first I
wasn't going to go.
   ``But I thought about it, and felt it was only right that I
should be there for his very last moment,'' Sherlock said.
   None of the surviving Pythons _ John Cleese, Terry Gilliam, Eric
Idle, Terry Jones and Michael Palin _ attended, but they are
expected to participate at a memorial service at St. Paul's Church
in Covent Garden in London.
</TEXT>
