<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 1228EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Obit-Franco     10-13 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Franco,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zairean Jazz Great Franco Dead at 51</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zairean jazz guitarist and band leader
Franco, a leading force in African music who made more than 100
albums, has died at the age of 51.
   Franco, whose real name was Lokanga Ladjo Pene Luambo Makiadi,
died Thursday in a Brussels hospital after a long, undisclosed
illness.
   Franco and his brassy-sounding T.P.O.K. Jazz orchestra were best
known for integrating jazz, gospel and African rhythms. To his
millions of fans, Franco was was the king of the ``rhumba
authentique.''
   Through his music, Franco often derided both Africa's former
European rulers and the post-independence ruling classes in many
African nations.
   Franco was considered the father of Zairean jazz, laying the
groundwork for modern Central and West African music. He first
performed on stage when he was 12 and made his first record in 1954.
   President Mobutu Sese Seko declared him Grand Master of Zaire
Music in 1978. Later, however, Zairean authorities jailed him
briefly because of the provocative content of some of his songs.
   Among his most successful songs were ``Independence Cha Cha'' in
1960, about Zairean independence from Belgium, and ``Mario'' in
1985, a litany of accusations addressed to a carefree gigolo by his
rich mistress.
   He later wrote ``Beware of AIDS,'' a hit song on the Central
African pop charts in 1987 that became a battle cry against the
deadly disease.
   He had been living in Belgium since the early 1980s.
   He is survived by 17 children.
   Mobutu ordered a four-day period of mourning in Zaire, with
government flags at half-staff and official radio playing soft
music. Franco's body will be returned on Saturday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891013-0035 </DOCNO>
