<FIRST>r w AM-OctagonRestoration     10-13 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Octagon Restoration,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Historic Washington Home to Be Restored</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Tayloe CQ in penultimate graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Architectural Foundation on
Friday launched a campaign to pay for restoration of a building
known as the Octagon, where President James Madison resided for six
months after British troops burned the White House in 1814.
   The three-story brick building, located on New York Avenue two
blocks west of the White House, also was the site of the signing by
Madison of the treaty that ended the War of 1812.
   The architectural foundation announced a drive to raise at least
$3.5 million between now and the organization's 50th anniversary in
1992. Of this amount, approximately $2.5 million will be devoted to
restoration of the Octagon.
   ``Restoration will be as complete and authentic as allowed by
the intended use of each space,'' said Norman L. Koonce, president
of the foundation. ``Thus, the period rooms and the exterior of the
building will be carefully researched and accurately restored,
while other spaces _ such as our exhibition galleries _ will be
improved appropriately.''
   He said all of the restoration work will be carried out by
specialists skilled in traditonal building crafts.
   The Octagon was designed by William Thornton, the first
architect of the U.S. Capitol, and completed in 1801 as a city
house for Col. John Tayloe III, a Virginia plantation owner and
friend of George Washington.
   The building is considered a premier example of Federal-period
architecture and is one of the last remaining unaltered residences
from the capital's early years.
</TEXT>
