<FIRST>r a PM-HighTides 2ndLd-Writethru a0454 10-13 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-High Tides, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0454,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede WASHINGTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Higher Than Normal Tides Expected for Atlantic, Pacific and Gulf</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with tide reports in areas of South
Carolina affected by hurricane. Deletes dateline and adds byline. Picks
up 4th graf pvs, `On the Pacific ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Higher tides than normal caused by an unusual alignment of the
sun, moon and Earth began lapping South Carolina's
hurricane-ravaged beaches today, but little erosion or flooding was
expected, forecasters said.
   The National Weather Service said high tides on the Atlantic and
Gulf coasts could be up to a foot higher than the highest tides of
the past few years.
   The pre-dawn tide in South Carolina today was 6.6 feet and tides
were expected to rise to 7.3 feet by Monday, or slightly higher if
accompanied by gentle winds, the weather service said. Normally,
tides are 5 feet to 6 feet.
   In Folly Beach, S.C., where at least 23 beachfront structures
were destroyed by Hurricane Hugo and others left teetering on
foundations, today's tides did no damage, said Mayor Bob Linville.
   ``I went down and checked where we were expecting problems,'' he
said. ``I think truthfully if the wind doesn't become a factor we
might come out of this thing.''
   On the Pacific Coast, high tide could equal the highest marks of
recent years, the service said.
   ``The threat of coastal flooding increases if a storm surge
should occur at the same times as the astronomical high tide,'' the
service said.
   Tide tables will show the expected heights. Fishermen, boaters
and residents of flood-prone areas should consult the tables and be
alert to weather forecasts, the service said.
   Higher than normal tides also will occur Nov. 12-13 and Dec.
10-12, the service said.
</TEXT>
