<FIRST>r w AM-CommunityColleges     10-13 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Community Colleges,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Community College Leader Criticizes State Legislatures, Ed Department</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a community college group said
Friday that state legislatures are biased against urban colleges
and that the federal Department of Education takes no interest in
their problems.
   Dale Parnell, president of the American Association of Community
and Junior Colleges, spoke at a news conference called to release a
report on innovative programs at community colleges.
   Alfred A. DelliBovi, under secretary of Housing and Urban
Development, said at the news conference that HUD officials see
community colleges as crucial to economic growth.
   ``We see jobs as the engine of opportunity,'' DelliBovi said.
``We see jobs and payrolls as the way people are going to rebuild
America's cities and we see community colleges as a way to get jobs
or get better jobs.''
   Parnell called that ``a great challenge for community
colleges.'' However, he said, ``they are not going to do it if they
don't have the help from the decision makers.''
   Asked why the Department of Education was not represented at the
news conference, Parnell said: ``They have not taken any interest
in urban education.''
   HUD Secretary Jack Kemp ``has shown more interest in this
subject than anyone else in this Cabinet,'' Parnell said.
   Education Department spokesman Tom Lyon said he had no immediate
comment on Parnell's remarks, but said he would look into it.
   ``I'd say there is a bias in state legislatures against urban
colleges,'' Parnell said. ``I say that respectfully. We have
formulas that do not apply to urban colleges.''
   Parnell also was critical of Congress.
   ``This week Congress put a cap on part-time students in student
financial aid,'' he said. ``Urban colleges are filled with
part-time students. What kind of priority is it to say we are going
to limit the number of part-time students? I don't understand that
kind of priority system.''
   Ronald J. Temple, president of Wayne County Community College in
Detroit and chairman of the association's commission on urban
community colleges, said such colleges need financial support.
   ``We are not necessarily talking about substantial additional
dollars at this point,'' he said. ``I think we are talking about
conceptualizing how we as a nation are going to begin to pull
together current resources to address urban problems.''
   The association's report described projects ranging from a
senior citizens' center at a former dormitory at the Bronx
Community College in New York to a Miami community college center
that serves as a focus of the amnesty program for illegal aliens
and offers almost 200 credit courses taught bilingually.
</TEXT>
