<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 1323EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-RetailSales     10-13 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Retail Sales,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spending Still Strong Despite Slowing Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales rose a moderate 0.5 percent last
month, the government said Friday in a report analysts said shows
consumer spending is still fairly strong despite a slowing economy.
   The Commerce Department said sales rose to a seasonally adjusted
$145.2 billion last month after gaining 0.7 percent in both August
and July. The revised July figure was even stronger than the 0.5
percent first reported.
   ``It shows there's good, solid consumer spending out there,''
said economist John Silvia of Kemper Financial Services in Chicago.
   ``Even excluding automobiles, sales were up 0.4 percent,''
Silvia noted. ``Furniture, department and drug stores, they all
were good sales numbers and I think that's what we want to see. We
don't want to see a recession.''
   Retail sales account for about one-third of the nation's
economic activity and are one of a number of indicators watched by
analysts to determine whether the Federal Reserve Board's
tight-credit policies are threatening to stall out the economy or
just slow it enough to keep inflation in check.
   Retail sales have risen every month since February, except for
June, when they were unchanged. On the other hand, the
manufacturing sector of the economy has grown sluggish, due in
part, Silvia said, to slowing exports.
   Lawrence A. Hunter, deputy chief economist for the U.S. Chamber
of Commerce, said the Fed should not interpret the retail sales
report as a sign of excess demand overheating the economy.
   ``To the contrary, price discounts and `everyday low prices' are
fueling the rise in consumer spending,'' Hunter said.
   He called on the Fed instead to reduce interest rates and thus
induce businesses to invest more to meet growing consumer demand.
   Durable goods sales slowed to a 0.6 percent gain in September,
Commerce said, following a strong 2 percent hike in August that was
boosted in part by a 2.2 percent gain in automobile sales.
   But the early summer sales were driven by end-of-model-year
incentives that are usually offered in September and distorted the
0.5 percent auto sales gain reported in September, analysts said.
   The 0.5 percent gain reflected higher prices in September
because dealers did not discount vehicles as they usually do,
according to economist David Jones of Aubrey G. Lanston &amp; Co. of
New York. Unit sales actually dropped by 400,000 vehicles during
the month, he said.
   Besides automobiles, sales of other durable goods categories
split _ furniture and other home furnishing sales gaining 1.3
percent while building materials fell 1.8 percent.
   Non-durable goods sales rose 0.4 percent, compared with a 0.1
percent drop in August. All categories except apparel gained _
department stores, 1.7 percent; grocery stores, 0.3 percent;
gasoline stations, 0.3 percent; restaurants and bars, 0.2 percent,
and drug stores, 1.4 percent.
   Apparel sales were down 0.5 percent after rising 0.8 percent the
previous month.
   For the three months from July through September, overall retail
sales were up 6.4 percent. Retail sales so far in 1989 were 6.1
percent above those in the first nine months of 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
