<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-TV     10-13 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-TV,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Independent TV Forming, Has Contract for 5,000 U.S. Films</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An independent company has been formed to break
the staid government television's monopoly, and it has gained
rights to show outside programming, including 5,000 U.S. films, a
report said Friday.
   ``There must not be a monopoly, there must be freedom of choice
for both journalists and viewers,'' Nikolai I. Lutsenko, the
president of the Nika TV company, told the weekly newspaper Nedelya.
   The company is working on its own programming in several
provincial cities and hopes to be on the air regularly in about a
year, the report said.
   State-run TV has been one of the chief means through which the
Soviet Union has tried to inculcate officially approved values into
the population.
   It has become freer under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
reforms and some programs have sparked controversy. On one program,
there was a debate on whether Vladimir I. Lenin's body should
remain in its famous mausoleum on Red Square.
   The majority of its programming, however, remains staid.
   Lutsenko told Nedelya that he recently had been to the United
States to pick up the rights to show U.S. films in the Soviet Union.
   ``In Hollywood, I concluded two contracts according to which we
obtained the rights to 5,000 of the best American films,'' he said.
Official TV occasionally shows foreign films, and its coverage of
events and the cultural life of other countries has increased
dramtically in the past several years.
   Another aim of the network is to uncover local talent in the
cities where it is operating, and help them find a place on
national Soviet TV and abroad, he said.
   Nedelya's article was accompanied by a picture of Lutsenko, by
profession a scholar of Asian affairs, interviewing American singer
John Denver in Colorado.
   Nika TV plans to use official television's communications
initially but eventually is seeking its own satellite system.
   Even though it will be independent of official television,
Lutsenko said Nika TV plans will have an oversight board that will
includes parliamentarians, members of the Communist youth league,
the Union of Filmmakers and others.
   ``We are all in the same boat, and Nika TV does not plan to rock
it,'' Lutsenko said. ``We will not be out of control.''
   However, it plans to focus much of its programming on the Soviet
Union's current political and economic difficulties, he said.
   ``The pain and losses of our economy, culture, ecology _ these
are the basic themes of our programs. Ecology is the first
priority,'' he said. But there also will be entertainment, music
and sports.
   The company has branches in Leningrad, Tashkent, Perm, and Alma
Ata, and is organizing in Vladivostok, Odessa, and the Baltic
republics, the report said.
</TEXT>
