<FIRST>u a PM-CoalStrike     10-13 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Secretary Visits Striking Miners, Announces Two Sides Will
Meet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Pres Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARBO, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole met with
striking Pittston Co. coal miners today and announced that the
company chairman and the union president have agreed to meet with
her Saturday.
   Face-to-face negotiations are the only way to settle the
6-month-old walkout, she said.
   ``I feel frustration with the impasse,'' Mrs. Dole said. ``We're
talking about communities being torn apart and in some cases
families torn apart as I've heard talking with miners this
morning.''
   The two sides have held bargaining sessions since the strike
began April 5, but in separate rooms with federal mediators
shuttling messages back and forth. Mrs. Dole said Pittston Co.
Chairman Paul Douglas and United Mine Workers President Richard
Trumka had agreed to meet with her in a Labor Department office.
   About 1,700 miners in Virginia, West Virginia and Kentucky are
on strike against Pittston Coal Group Inc., a subsidiary of
Pittston Co.
   Mrs. Dole, who visited picket lines to listen to miners'
concerns about health benefits and job security, was careful to
point out that she was not taking sides in the strike and planned
to meet with Pittston officials later today in Lebanon, Va.
   ``I'm not a mediator,'' she said. ``I'm not here to say I have
the answer to this complex problem, but I do feel now it is time to
see if we can facilitate the bargaining process.''
   Mrs. Dole spoke to some of the 280 pickets at the entrance to a
coal preparation plant that 98 striking miners invaded and occupied
for four days in September.
   UMW strike captain Fred Wallace of Lebanon said it ``gives us a
shot in the arm to know that the secretary of labor is interested
enough to come for a first-hand view.''
   Miners told Mrs. Dole that the contract Pittston is proposing
would reduce their health benefits, threaten the stability of the
UMW pension fund and eventually break the union.
   ``They trying to destroy our union,'' said Joel Phillips, a
picket captain from Castlewood.
   The company repeatedly has denied it is trying to break the
union.
   Heather Hamilton, the 3-year-old daughter of a striking miner,
gave Mrs. Dole a bouquet of flowers and told her, ``Get a contract
for my daddy.''
</TEXT>
