<FIRST>r w AM-US-Cyprus 370   10-13 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cyprus, 370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Denktash Meeting With Senior Official, but U.S. Insists No Policy
Change</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash met
Friday with Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger, but
both the State Department and the Greek Cypriot government denied
any shift toward recognition of the self-declared state.
   U.S. and Greek Cypriot officials stressed the informal nature of
the meeting, held over lunch in a State Department dining room.
   ``This is simply in keeping with our desire to help resolve the
conflict,'' said one official, who asked not to be named.
   The sensitivity over the meeting is a reflection of the bitter
conflict between the Mediterranean island's Greek majority and
Turkish minority, which has defied resolution for 26 years.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said Eagleburger
has known Denktash for many years and received him as head of the
Turkish Cypriot community, not as leader of the breakaway state.
   ``The U.S. Embassy in Nicosia maintains continuing contact with
Denktash and we believe his meetings in Washington are fully in
keeping with our desire to be of assistance to the intercommunal
negotiating process of Cyprus, through which we hope a lasting
peaceful solution emerges,'' she said.
   It is the first time Denktash has visited the State Department
since he declared a breakaway state in the northern part of Cyprus
six years ago.
   Only Turkey, which has provided 30,000 troops to the Turkish
Cypriots, has recognized the state.
   Denktash and Cypriot President George Vassiliou began talks in
1988 in an attempt to dissolve the partition. But the talks under
U.N. auspices have stalled, with each side blaming the other.
   Vassiliou was received by President Bush at the White House last
week, and Denktash is following in his footsteps to garner support
for the Turkish position.
   ``We feel very strongly that we've been discriminated against
too long, and we want to be heard,'' Denktash told reporters.
   The Turkish Cypriot community, about 30 percent of the island's
population, wants a federation with the Greek part of the island to
be ruled by a central council of ministers. The presidency would
rotate between Greeks and Turks, Denktash said.
</TEXT>
