<FIRST>r a PM-HUD-Plea     10-13 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Plea,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former HUD Official Changes Plea to Guilty, Gets Year in Prison</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-HUD</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BILOXI, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Housing and Urban Development
official has pleaded guilty to conspiracy to defraud the government
and has been sentenced to a year in prison.
   DuBois Gilliam changed his plea Thursday after federal
prosecutors agreed to drop four bribery counts. Together with the
conspiracy charge, conviction on those counts could have brought
him up to 13 years in prison.
   Gilliam was charged with trying to obtain more than $3 million
in HUD grants and loans for a hotel-marina project at Point Cadet
in this Gulf Coast city.
   Former Mayor Gerald Blessey and the city's former economic
development director, Reba Capers, were indicted in April on
conspiracy and mail fraud charges. Prosecutors said they improperly
spent $160,000 of a HUD grant on the waterfront project. Their
trial ended in a mistrial in September, and prosecutors promised to
bring them to trial again.
   Gilliam was a deputy assistant secretary of HUD and close
associate of Samuel Pierce, the HUD secretary during the Reagan
administration.
