<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 1436EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Fashion     10-13 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fashion,0727</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italian Designers Offer Choice in Spring-Summer Shows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIELA PETROFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The woman who dresses Italian style for next
spring and summer can be anything she wants to be.
   The new look offered by more than 40 top Italian designers, who
presented their warm weather wears this week, is both sexy and
demure, sporty and urbane, tailored and languid, colorful and
muted, simple and ornate.
   There is less of a unified message than in past ``moda
Milanese'' seasons, allowing the fashionable woman, as Armani put
it, ``to choose something which seems to be designed for her
alone.''
   Naturally there are trends. The new style concentrates on the
upper body, with the bare midriff the newest look. Bra tops
bandeaus and bustiers, as well as an accent on see-through blouses,
spell bad news for the lingerie industry. The bra as an
undergarment virtually disappears.
   Color is another novelty on the Milan runway. After many a
season of drab shades, the designers have burst out in a bright
palette of Italian fruit ice cream tones: raspberry, kiwi,
watermelon, mango, apricot, peach, banana, blueberry and many more.
In some of the collections these shades are in muted pastels. Black
also plays a big role by night.
   Short skirts no longer make news in Italy, with the young and
old _ stout and slim alike _ showing off their legs. It is no
surprise that short skirts continue to dominate the runway. Next
season's miniskirt is not as hip-hugging as the winter version with
a preference for draping and tie skirts, like the ones worn by
South Sea island natives.
   There is little for city dwellers and working women in the new
collections with the emphasis on holiday attire: shorts, jumpsuits,
gaily printed sun dresses, pajama pants and loose shirt jackets.
   Where detailing is concerned the Milanese designers are on a
fringe binge with long silk threads adorning shawls and scarves, as
well as finding there way onto shirts, jackets, and the hemlines of
skirts.
   Gold and crystal beading dot all the collections especially for
evening. Simple chiffon gowns and camisole tops are richly
embroidered with opulent sequining, all done now in India. Gone are
the famous Italian seamstresses who used to work out of their homes
by candle light to embellish Italian couture.
   Ornate jewelry is back for the summer of 1990, with over-sized
gold bracelets, necklaces and earrings by day and night.
   Face-painting is out next season with a return for the natural
look not only in the make-up but also in the short boyish
hairstyles. Footwear is predominantly casual and flat even for
evening.
   Americans are spending more cautiously, but the Italians are
comforted by a Japanese market, which almost doubled the number of
buyers it sent to Milan.
   Beppe Modenese, the organizational mastermind behind the ``moda
Milanese,'' which swept the fashion world at the beginning of the
1980s, is confident that despite recent defections by Italian
designers to Paris _ Romeo Gigli has joined Valentino in showing
his ready-to-wear collection in Paris and Gianfranco Ferre now
designs for Dior as well as doing his own label out of Milan _
Milan will continue to be a guiding light in the 1990s.
   ``We are still the reference point for all ready to wear.
France, Germany, and even America take their cue from us,''
Modenese said.
   Highlights from the shows:
   Versace _ The sexiest, most theatrical look with super short
skirts and multicolored gold and crystal encrusted bustier tops.
   Ferre _ The most confident look with enormous scarf tie blouses
and a see-through jumpusit made of bands of silk jersey and
skin-color chiffon.
   Krizia _ The award for the longest show _ one hour and 10
minutes _ and the clumpiest shoes, 1940s platform ankle straps.
   Armani _ The longest, loosest jacket in raw silk, and the most
elegant collection.
   Jenny _ The only collection to dress working women.
   Byblos _ The easiest collection to sell, full of young and
pretty clothes.
   Biagiotti _ Always the best where cashmere is concerned.
   Missoni _ Superb quilted and knitted reversible jackets.
   Moschino _ The best sense of humor. He stitches his labels on
the outside, poking fun at himself.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
