<FIRST>u a AM-People     10-13 0947</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0992</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television preacher Billy Graham is getting a
star on Hollywood's Walk of Fame, a concrete honor stuck between
the stars for actress Judy Holliday and Italian opera singer
Beniamino Gigli.
   ``We are all aware of Billy Graham's great evangelistic
successes,'' Walk of Fame Chairman Johnny Grant said Thursday.
``Few realize, however, the tremendous impact he has had on the
world through radio, film and television.''
   Graham's star will be unveiled Sunday and it won't be the first
time a clergyman has been honored with a star, Grant said.
   Rev. James Cleveland, a Grammy-winning gospel singer, composer,
pianist and minister at the Cornerstone Baptist Church in Los
Angeles, received a star in 1981.
   Graham is getting the last available spot in front of the
theater, a popular tourist stop that used to be called Grauman's
Chinese Theater but is now a Mann theater. There are other spots,
however, still available on the sidewalk.
   On Wednesday the evangelist went out to look over the star's
location and sign autographs.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: ``sex, lies and videotape'' lowercase is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steven Soderbergh, the young director of the
surprise hit ``sex, lies and videotape,'' received the first John
Cassavetes award at the opening of the 12th Denver International
Film Festival.
   The festival began Thursday evening with the premiere of Woody
Allen's film ``Crimes and Misdemeanors.'' About 1,000 people turned
out.
   Soderbergh, the 26-year-old director whose film won the top
prize earlier this year at the Cannes Film Festival, was presented
with the first Cassavetes award, given to the individual who has
made the greatest contribution to American independent filmmaking
this year.
   The award is in honor of the late John Cassavetes, one of the
country's most well-known independent directors, who died in
February.
   ``Home Boys,'' a documentary made by Denver director Donna
Dewey, makes its premiere during the festival. The film features
interviews with leaders of the Crips and Bloods youth gangs.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Pat Sajak Show'' will be trimmed to one
hour in an effort to pick up the pace of the late-night gab fest,
CBS officials said Friday.
   Sajak's weeknight series began in January as a 90-minute program
that went head to head with NBC's one-hour ``Tonight Show'' and the
first half hour of ``Late Night With David Letterman.'' It also was
pitted against ABC's half-hour ``Nightline,'' and the syndicated,
one-hour ``Arsenio Hall Show.''
   Sajak's show was shortened ``to strengthen the format and
tighten the flow,'' said Rod Perth, CBS' vice president for
late-night programs, in a statement.
   The hour format was ``much more conducive to a livelier,
faster-paced broadcast,'' he said.
   When the change is made Oct. 30, CBS said, it will air one-hour
action-adventure programs at 12:30 a.m. Mondays through Thursdays,
and the ``CBS Late Movie'' on Fridays.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kitty Dukakis, wife of Massachusetts' Gov.
Michael Dukakis, urged physicians Friday to step up the fight
against drug and alcohol abuse by monitoring patients for hidden
addictions.
   She told delegates at a World Psychiatric Association congress
how her own battle against an addiction to stimulants was dogged by
careless prescriptions.
   ``I'm an alcoholic and a drug addict,'' Mrs. Dukakis said. ``I
have come to this meeting the hard way.
   ``For many years I was able, quite easily, to have prescriptions
filled for the amphetamines to which I was addicted,'' she said.
   Mrs. Dukakis was hospitalized in February for alcoholism
rehabilitation at a private center in Newport, R.I., for 31 days.
   The World Psychiatric Association, the internationally
recognized body for psychiatrists, meets every six years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man will be watching the World Series
with added interest this weekend after making a big bet with talk
show host David Letterman on the games _ his wife of 50 years.
   Maurice Shank got a call Wednesday afternoon from Letterman
during the taping of NBC's ``Late Night with David Letterman.''
   ``I was on the defensive the whole time because I didn't know
what I was getting into,'' said Shank, 76, on Thursday.
   Letterman told Shank he wanted to bet on the World Series, which
starts Saturday. He asked Shank to pick a team, and Shank chose the
Oakland A's.
   Then, Letterman asked, ``If you lose, what are you prepared to
surrender?''
   ``My wife,'' Shank said.
   That wasn't quite what he meant, according to his wife, Darline.
She said her husband was starting a sentence when Letterman cut him
off.
   But the stakes aren't as high as betting his wife forever.
   If the A's beat the San Francisco Giants and Shank wins, the
couple will win a case of J&amp;B Scotch and an electric shoe-shiner.
   If Shank loses, Mrs. Shank will get a free trip to New York to
be on Letterman's show, said officials at NBC.
   ``It's fantastic,'' Mrs. Shank said. ``Our quiet little life of
raking leaves and cleaning windows, and look where we are.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Queen Elizabeth II will
arrive this weekend for a state visit coinciding with the 46-nation
Commonwealth summit, her spokesman said Friday.
   The queen is to arrive Saturday on the royal yacht Brittania at
Port Klang, 18 miles west of Kuala Lumpur, for the visit to this
former British colony, said press secretary Robin Janvrin.
   She will not address the summit, but will tour the site Tuesday,
he said.
   Also next week, the queen plans to meet with leaders at the
summit, hold a banquet for them and have a reception for foreign
ministers, he said.
   The Commonwealth nations, which include Britain and its former
colonies, meet biennially to discuss global issues.
</TEXT>
