<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 1626EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WelfareRegulations     10-13 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Welfare Regulations,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>New State Welfare Regulations Issued</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Friday issued rules states must
follow in setting up required education, job training and work
programs to help welfare recipients become self-sufficient.
   The rules implement the Job Opportunities and Basic Skills
Training program, a $3.7 billion, five-year initiative passed by
Congress last year. It was the first major welfare overhaul in more
than half a century.
   ``This final rule recognizes that parents must work toward
self-sufficiency and government must support their efforts,'' said
Eunice Thomas, acting assistant secretary of the Family Support
Administration at the Department of Health and Human Services.
   All states must have a JOBS program approved by the federal
government no later than Oct. 1, 1990.
   Twenty-five states that have begun their programs must have them
re-approved to assure they comply, said David Siegel, a Family
Support Administration spokesman.
   States, whose progam funding will be matched by the federal
government, initially will have to bring 7 percent of their
caseload in Aid to Families with Dependent Children programs under
the new plan, and by 1994 will be required to have 20 percent in
the program.
   About 3.7 million families receive AFDC, the nation's largest
cash assistance program costing about $8.5 billion a year. HHS
estimates that up to 138,000 families will be able to leave the
welfare rolls over the first five years of the JOBS program.
   The plan requires that one parent in two-parent welfare families
to work at least 16 hours a week as a condition for receiving
benefits.
   Single welfare parents with children 3 years or older must
participate in employment and training programs, and teen-age
parents who have not finished high school will be required to
return to school or work toward an equivalent degree.
   States must guarantee child care for parents who participate in
the education and training programs.
   Kathy Patterson of the American Public Welfare Association,
which represents the state human services agencies that will
implement the programs, said the rules give states more flexibility
than did the government's initial proposal.
   ``We're pleased they listened to some of the comments the states
made,'' she said.
   However, she said the association's evaluation was based only on
a briefing by officials at the department's Family Support
Administration and that some of the regulations present concerns.
One such concern is that the rules may impose an overly stringent
cap on funds for child care.
</TEXT>
