<DOCNO> AP891013-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 1630EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Thatcher     10-13 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thatcher,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Thatcher, Applause &amp; Beatles Music, But Inflation Jumps Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLACKPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
defended her economic strategy Friday, but a jump in inflation to
7.6 percent took some of the gloss off a rousing speech winding up
the Conservative Party's annual conference.
   ``When the choice is between high (interest) rates now or
persistent higher inflation later, with all the damage that would
do, the choice is clear,'' Mrs. Thatcher said. ``Britain's economy
is strong. When inflation is beaten ... Britain will be stronger
still.''
   Mrs. Thatcher, who turned 64 on Friday, received a rapturous
ovation from the 9,000 party activists packed into conference hall
in this north England resort.
   She hailed 1989 ``as the year when the people of half our
continent began to throw off their chains,'' adding, ``We didn't
know it at the time but the torch we lit in Britain, which
transformed our country _ the torch of freedom that is now the
symbol of our party _ became a beacon that has shed its light
across the Iron Curtain into the East.''
   Delegates tapped their feet to the strains of the Beatles'
classic ``When I'm 64,'' and after the keynote speech sang ``Happy
Birthday'' and burst into the favorite Tory anthem, ``Land of Hope
and Glory.''
   They waved huge blue Tory banners and chanted ``10 more years''
as Mrs. Thatcher made her way out of the ballroom.
   Despite the razzmatazz, Mrs. Thatcher, who came to power in 1979
and won a third five-year term in 1987, ended the convention with
her party in trouble.
   Fears of an economic recession have combined with unpopular
plans for a new property tax and privatization of the water and
electricity industries to depress Tory fortunes.
   ``After 10 years in government, Margaret Thatcher is facing her
toughest test,'' commented the respected weekly, The Economist,
which usually supports the Thatcher government.
   Mrs. Thatcher made no direct reference to the Conservatives'
slumping popularity, now an average 7 points behind the socialist
Labor Party.
   But she said inflation was too high and acknowledged that
soaring interest rates _ doubled to 15 percent in the past 16
months _ were hitting businesses and millions of home-buyers.
   In London, the government announced that the annual inflation
rate has risen to 7.6 percent from 7.3 percent, which was already
among the highest in industrialized countries.
   Mrs. Thatcher said the Labor Party, surging ahead on a new, more
moderate platform, was ``seeking power at any price and they'll say
anything to get it.''
   ``Labor's real prescription for Britain is the disease half the
world is struggling to cure,'' she added, referring to reforms in
Poland and Hungary and protests against East Germany's hardline
communist rulers.
   Labor last month ditched its policy of unilateral nuclear
disarmament, and Mrs. Thatcher dismissed the action as ``no more
than a confidence trick.''
   ``It's still unilateral disarmament _ unilateral disarmament by
agreement with the Soviet Union,'' she said. ``That isn't a defense
policy to see Britain through the 1990s. Its a form of words to see
Labor through the next election.''
   She took a few cracks at critics of her rigorous tight-money
brand of conservatism, including academics and some church leaders.
   ``I went to Oxford University, but I've never let it hold me
back,'' she said of the ancient university which in 1985 voted
against giving her an honorary doctorate in protest at cuts state
grants.
   The four-day convention was overshadowed by economic problems.
Inflation, fuelled by a booming credit, began to take off again
last year.
   The government is using high interest rates as the sole means of
trying both to curb inflation and defend the value of the pound.
   Pressure is mounting from right and left _ big business, trade
unions and the Labor Party _ for Mrs. Thatcher to speed up British
entry into the exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary
System. It is links the currencies of most of the 12-member nations
of the European Economic Community.
   The issue has divided Mrs. Thatcher, who has set stringent
conditions for entry, and Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson.
Critics charge that the differences mean the government lacks a
coherent economic strategy.
   During the conference, there were also signs of unease that Mrs.
Thatcher's combative style is not working any more. Some top Tories
say privately they also fear that she will not be able to pull the
economy around before the next election, which must be held by
mid-1992.
</TEXT>
