<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Babies     10-13 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Babies,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Press: Alcoholism, Pollution Hurting Children</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOSB2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mental retardation is rising among Soviet children
because of worsening alcoholism among parents, a newspaper said
Friday in the latest media revelation on how children suffer for
Soviet society's ills.
   One special education school in the southern Russian city of
Oryol has seen the number of retarded children it serves more than
quintuple during a period when the city's population only doubled,
the daily Sovietskaya Rossia reported.
   The newspaper attributed the rising retardation rate to the
intractable alcoholism that drives Soviets to make bootleg liquor
and drink everything from after-shave lotion to insect repellent.
   Other recent Soviet media reports have focused on baldness,
deformities and diseases in children living in polluted areas and
on the terrible toll radiation has taken on babies on the Chukotka
peninsula in the Soviet northeast.
   ``Infant mortality remains high'' in the entire Soviet Union,
Pravda reported Friday, and allergies, cancer and heart disease are
increasing because of pollution.
   More than 90 children were reported to have lost their hair this
year in towns near the shale-oil fields in the Baltic coast of
Estonia due to an ailment apparently caused by the dirty
environment. Other outbreaks of child baldness were reported in the
Ukraine.
   In Chukotka, which lies across the Bering Strait from Alaska,
nuclear tests carried out decades ago have left such a high level
of radiation that the cancer rate there is 2-3 times higher than
the national average and infant mortality can reach up to 100
deaths per 1,000 infants, the Moscow News reported this summer.
   The people of northern Russia are considered to be living in
some of the country's worst conditions, with pollution widespread
and shortages especially extreme.
</TEXT>
