<FIRST>r w AM-Marijuana-Forests     10-13 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marijuana-Forests,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forest Service Says Marijuana Crop Size Will Remain Stable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite a sharp increase in the number of
arrests and plants destroyed, the size of the marijuana crop
growing illegally in national forests will probably remain the same
for the next several years, the U.S. Forest Service said Friday.
   The report also said that ``organized networks'' of growers and
distributors now control more than half of the marijuana crop in
the national forests and the number of clandestine drug labs, most
producing methamphetamines, remains a serious problem.
   The report was released by Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore. and the
successful sponsor of legislation last year giving the Forest
Service increased powers to deal with drug problems in the federal
forests.
   Wyden said he would ask William Bennett, the presidential drug
policy coordinator, next week to form a ``strike force'' to
spearhead the war on the drug networks operating in the national
forests.
   ``In the 1988 drug act, we told the Forest Service `go
get'em,''' Wyden said. ``This report shows how well they've done.
But they're catching the equivalent of serfs and peasants. They
must now catch the lords who direct forest crime.''
   The Forest Service said in the report that it expected to be
``faced with a continuing drug production challenge in the national
forest system for the foreseeable future.''
   The report, recounting figures that had largely been released
previously, said:
   _Almost 415,000 marijuana plants were eradicated in the national
forests in 1988, an 84 percent increase over the 254,950 plants
destroyed in 1987.
   _Law enforcement personel made 543 arrests in 1988, up roughly
300 percent over the 135 arrests in 1987.
   _Areas in the national forests considered ``unsafe'' because of
marijuana crops that could be booby-trapped or armed growers
defending their plants fell about 50 percent, from 772,600 acres in
1987 to 388,800 acres in 1988.
   _Some 116 booby-traps were found in 1988 compared with 83 in
1987; the number of weapons seized grew from 101 to 271, and the
number of drug-related assaults dropped from 19 to 11.
   Preliminary estimates for the first nine months of 1989 suggest
that the number of arrests and plants destroyed this year will
exceed last year's totals, the Forest Service said.
   ``Our analysis of these trends suggest that despite increased
eradication and apprehension effectiveness the total volume of
cannabis produced in the national forest system may remain about
the same for the next several years,'' the Forest Service said.
   Roughly two-thirds of the cannabis sites found and half the
plants eradicated in 1988 were in the national forests of the
South, the report said.
   The Daniel Boone National Forest in Kentucky, because of its
nearness to urban markets in the East and the depressed local
economy, accounted for almost 25 percent of the cannabis eradicated
throughout the national forest system in 1988, the report said.
</TEXT>
