<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica Bjt   10-13 0738</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa, Bjt,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plan Rallies to Celebrate Prisoner Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blacks planned 17 rallies
across the country Saturday to celebrate the imminent release of
eight major anti-apartheid leaders, including seven jailed for a
quarter-century.
   Walter Sisulu, a leader of the African National Congress, and at
least four of his jailed colleagues were flown Friday from their
Cape Town prison to their hometown of Johannesburg, according to
airline personnel.
   The men were immediately taken to Diepkloof Prison outside the
city and near the huge Soweto township, according to various
reports.
   Another prisoner, Raymond Mhlaba, was flown from Cape Town to
his hometown, the southern city of Port Elizabeth.
   The white-run government announced Tuesday that the eight,
ranging in age from 60 to 80, would be freed unconditionally.
Officials have refused to say when or where the men will be
released. Some _ if not all _ were expected to be freed over the
weekend.
   Seven of the men are ranking African National Congress members
and Sisulu, 77, is the most prominent jailed leader of the outlawed
guerrilla movement after Nelson Mandela.
   Mandela's release has not yet been approved but is widely
expected in the next few months.
   The eighth, Jafta Masemola, belongs to a smaller black
nationalist guerrilla movement, the Pan Africanist Congress.
   The decision by President F.W. de Klerk to release the activists
has generally won high praise, both in South Africa and abroad. De
Klerk, who became president in August, says he wants to end racial
discrimination and negotiate a new constitution that will bring the
black majority into the national government.
   However, almost all black political leaders have said they will
not negotiate with de Klerk until the government makes several
concessions, including the release of political prisoners.
   Anti-apartheid leaders applied to magistrates to hold ``victory
marches'' in cities and towns across the country Saturday to
celebrate the releases.
   The New Nation, a militant opposition newspaper, said at least
250,000 people were expected to take part.
   Police Friday lifted restrictions on Sisulu's wife, Albertina,
who had been banned from meetings and making public statements
since February 1988.
   Mrs. Sisulu, a prominent activist in her own right, told
reporters at her Soweto home she would join the planned march in
Johannesburg.
   Journalists and residents waited outside her house for much of
the day, and police used tear gas to disperse a group of youths
dancing in the street Friday evening.
   One young girl was injured and ABC News had one of its video
cassettes confiscated, witnesses said.
   Mrs. Sisulu said she received some political advice from Mandela
on Tuesday, when she and other activists met with him at his prison
quarters near Cape Town.
   ``Now that there are less limitations on my activities, I will
be able to push ahead with the suggestions and advice given to me
by Mandela,'' she said without elaborating.
   Mrs. Sisulu is co-president of the banned United Democratic
Front, a nationwide anti-apartheid coalition.
   Despite her restrictions, Mrs. Sisulu, 71, was issued a
short-term passport by the government this year. She and other
anti-apartheid leaders met President Bush, French President
Francois Mitterrand and officials of other Western governments.
   In addition to Sisulu, four of the other prisoners to be freed
were sentenced to life in prison _ along with Mandela _ at the
Rivonia treason trial in 1964. They are Ahmed Kathrada, 60; Elias
Motsoaledi, 65; Andrew Mlengi, 63; and Mhlaba, 69.
   Also to be freed are African National Congress leaders Oscar
Mpetha, 80, and Wilton Mkwayi, 67, and Masemola, 60.
   All have been imprisoned for 25 years except the ailing Mpetha,
who is nearing the end of a five-year term.
   When they are released, the seven African National Congress
members are expected to seek permission to travel to the group's
headquarters in Lusaka, Zambia.
   A leading official of the guerrilla movement said the release of
the political prisoners shows international pressure is working.
   Thabo Mbeki, the group's secretary for international affairs,
said he did not believe the release was a sign of a new spirit of
conciliation on de Klerk's part.
   ``I think it's a response to pressure,'' he said in an interview
with the BBC. ``I don't think it signifies that this regime of de
Klerk is any different from the regime of P.W. Botha except that
the pressures have become so much that it has to yield ground.''
</TEXT>
