<SECOND>PM-Wall Street, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0647,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dow Industrials Plunge More Than 115 Points in Worst Day of the Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to CORRECT UAL to takeover, sted merger,
add that 115-point drop would be 4th largest.. Picks up 4th graf pvs.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices tumbled today in the most
spectacular drop of the year, battered by fear of higher inflation
and word that the United Airlines takeover bid may have collapsed.
   The speed of the decline spooked traders in a startling reminder
of the worst stock panic ever almost two years ago on Oct. 19.
   By late afternoon, the widely watched Dow Jones average of 30
industrial stocks had plunged 115 points to the 2,645 level, by far
the biggest drop for the index this year. Other stock indices also
fell sharply.
   If the 115-point drop held until closing, it would be the fourth
biggest drop in the Dow industrials on record, in terms of points
lost. The largest was the 508-point drop of Oct. 19, 1987, the
second-largest was a 156.83-point drop a week after that, and the
third largest was a 140.58-point drop on Jan. 8, 1988.
   Brokers said the drop was triggered partly by news that a
labor-management group failed to secure financing for the proposed
$6.75 billion takeover of UAL Corp., parent of United Airlines. UAL
is a component of the Dow Transportation index.
   Others said news from the Labor Department that wholesale prices
rose sharply in September suggested inflation was accelerating,
reducing the likelihood that the Federal Reserve would act to ease
interest rates.
</TEXT>
