<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Kidnap     10-13 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Kidnap,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swiss Flight Attendant Released in North Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KOUBBA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 31-year-old Swiss flight attendant was
released Friday after being held for six days in northern Lebanon,
security sources said.
   Lebanese police said they had no information on the case. ``The
abduction was not reported to us in the first place,'' a spokesman
said.
   Reliable Lebanese security sources said the woman, Astrid
Fischer, was released in the port city of Tripoli.
   One source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Ms. Fischer
left Tripoli after her release and went to the village of Koubba.
The part-time attendant for Swissair has a house in this village in
the Syrian-controlled north.
   The security source said gunmen kidnapped Ms. Fischer in Koubba
Sunday and that she was ``interrogated in connection with her
activities and stay in Lebanon.'' He did not elaborate and refused
to identify the kidnappers.
   Reporters and photographers arriving in Koubba, 31 miles north
of Beirut, were told by unidentified armed guards ringing Ms.
Fischer's house that she did not want to be disturbed.
   The guards, who wore civilian clothes, declined to identify
themselves. They were believed to be either members of the Syrian
intelligence service or militiamen of former Lebanese president
Suleiman Franjieh _ the only paramilitary force allowed to operate
in the region.
   Franjieh, 79, president when Lebanon's civil war broke out in
1975, heads the Marada, or Giants militia, which is allied with
Syria.
   Christian and Moslem radio stations in Beirut said Franjieh was
instrumental in Ms. Fischer's release. They did not elaborate.
   In Bern, Swiss Foreign Ministry official Francois Chappuis said
Ms. Fischer's freedom was gained through contacts by Dino Sciolli,
Switzerland's ambassador to Lebanon based in Cyprus.
   Chappuis told reporters there never was any indication of a
political motive behind Fischer's abduction and no demands were
made. He refused to speculate on the motive.
   Ms. Fischer was the third Swiss national to be abducted in
Lebanon in the last week.
   Red Cross workers Elio Erriquez and Emmanual Christen, both
Swiss, were abducted in the southern provincial capital of Sidon
Oct. 6. No group has claimed responsibility or made demands for
their release.
   Including the Swiss Red Cross workers, 18 foreigners are missing
in Lebanon. They include eight Americans, four Britons, two West
Germans, an Italian and an Irishman.
   Most of the foreign hostages are believed held by pro-Iranian
Shiite Moslem underground factions.
   Held longest is American Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   Police blamed the radical Palestinian Fatah-Revolutionary
Council faction led by terrorist mastermind Abu Nidal for
kidnapping Christen and Erriquez. The group denied involvement.
</TEXT>
