<SECOND>AM-France-Missing General,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Body of Retired French Army General Found in River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PERIGUEUX, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Friday found the body of a
retired French army general who was reported missing after he
failed to return home six days ago.
   The body of Jean Favreau, the 72-year-old former military
commander of Paris, was found about 6:30 p.m. under a bridge on the
Dordogne River at the village of Izon, said a spokesman for the
Gironde prefecture, southwestern France.
   Police had been searching for Favreau since he failed to return
home Saturday after leaving his wife at the railway station in
Libourne, a town 20 miles from Bordeaux.
   Favreau was last seen driving from the station in his
Mercedes-Benz, which was later spotted with two other people
inside. Police, who lost the vehicle after a brief chase, later
found the car _ burned _ about 9 miles away.
   Police speculated Favreau may have been thrown off the bridge,
but no other details were available about the cause or
circumstances of his death.
   An anonymous caller on Wednesday told the regional newspaper
Sud-Ouest that the Direct Action terrorist group had kidnapped
Favreau and demanded the release of all the gang's members in jail.
   The caller offered no proof and police discounted the claim,
saying the alleged kidnapping did not fit with the known facts.
