<FIRST>r w AM-Gingrich-Dickinson 430   10-13 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gingrich-Dickinson, 430</SECOND>
<HEAD>House GOP Whip Says Ethics Committee Should Investigate Dickinson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Bill Dickinson's financial dealings with
an Alabama industrialist should be investigated by the House ethics
committee, House Republican Whip Newt Gingrich said Friday.
   But Gingrich, R-Ga., who led the ethics crusade that forced
Democrat Jim Wright to resign as speaker of the House, said he
won't file an ethics complaint to trigger an investigation of the
Alabama lawmaker, the senior Republican on the House Armed Services
Committee.
   ``Clearly, ... the ethics committee will look at the case and
report back,'' Gingrich said when asked if he thought Dickinson had
violated House rules by accepting a one-third interest in a
$300,000 investment venture funded by Ben Collier of Montgomery,
Ala.
   ``I would be very surprised if they didn't issue some kind of
ruling,'' he said.
   Gingrich is the target of an ethics complaint filed by Rep. Bill
Alexander, D-Ark. The complaint alleges that Gingrich may have
violated campaign finance laws, limits on outside income and a rule
preventing acceptance of gifts from those with a direct interest in
legislation.
   Gingrich has denied any violations.
   While the ethics committee can initiate an investigation on its
own, the filing of a formal complaint by one member of Congress
against another forces the panel of six Democrats and six
Republicans to vote on whether an investigation should be opened.
   Mike Lewis, Dickinson's press secretary, said Dickinson had no
comment on Gingrich's statements.
   Dickinson said in an interview this week that he approached
Collier in 1986 with ``what I thought was a good business
opportunity.''
   He said they formed the Montgomery Investment Club, with Collier
supplying the $300,000 and Dickinson supplying the ``contacts.''
Their agreement provided that any profits or losses would go
one-third to Dickinson and two-thirds to Collier.
   House rules prohibit members from accepting gifts worth more
than $100 from an individual who has a direct interest in
legislation before Congress. Dickinson contends that rule does not
cover Collier, whose companies have done $50 million in government
defense work since 1987.
   Dickinson said he never made any money from the investment
because the $300,000 was turned over to Steven A. Streit of
Huntsville, Ala., who later pleaded guilty to securities fraud
charges and was sentenced to 10 years in prison.
   Streit's assets were frozen in 1987, and Dickinson said the
investment club has received about 90 percent of the $300,000 from
a bankruptcy clerk that is serving Streit's creditors.
</TEXT>
