<FIRST>r a AM-People-McClure     10-13 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-McClure,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jessica McClure is OK Two Years Later, She Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jessica McClure says she's doing OK two
years after her rescue from an abandoned water well.
   ``I'm fine,'' the 3{-year-old said in an extremely brief phone
interview Thursday night.
   Jessica and her parents, Chip and Cissy, are doing nothing to
mark the anniversary of her rescue Oct. 16, when dozens of
volunteers helped her out of a well in her aunt's back yard. The
toddler cried and softly sang a nursery rhyme while she was wedged
22 feet underground for 58 hours.
   Like the McClure family, Midland plans no commemorations _ no
parades, no speeches.
   About the closest thing to a celebration will be the handing out
of the Midland Community Spirit Award to recognize a city that
responded to a person or group in need, Mayor Carroll Thomas said.
   But the award probably won't be given Oct. 16, Thomas said,
because he and about eight other judges are still looking at the
70-odd entries.
   He said the award, which was publicized in August in a ``Dear
Abby'' column, will be given soon, but set no date.
   Meanwhile, Jessica walks just fine, her father said, although
her right little toe and the tip of her right big toe were
amputated after the rescue.
   ``She has no memory of the incident whatsoever,'' he said.
   Jessica gets one or two cards a day, he said.
   When Jessica was hospitalized after the rescue, she was received
truckloads of cards and gifts of stuffed animals. Someone donated
the McClures a phone answering machine, and they were getting 100
to 200 calls a day.
   ``I really appreciated the outpouring of affection,'' said
McClure, who, with his wife, was 18 at the time of the accident.
``But, truthfully, it was a big hassle.''
   Jessica is curious, bright and talks well, McClure said, adding
that she doesn't suffer from nightmares or claustrophobia.
   The McClures seemed overwhelmed by the publicity at first, but
the strain did not threaten to split them apart.
   ``If this did anything, it strengthened our marriage,'' McClure
said.
</TEXT>
