<FIRST>u i AM-Palme     10-13 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Palme,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Assassination Conviction Thrown Out, Drifter Seeks Return to Normalcy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drifter who won an appeal against his
conviction for the murder of Prime Minister Olof Palme said Friday
he doesn't want to change his identity and prefers to return to the
easygoing life he had before his arrest.
   The 10 months of imprisonment for his interrogation, trial and
appeal had left him unchanged, said Christer Pettersson, a day
after his July conviction was thrown out.
   ``I am what I am, and I think I'm going to be the same,'' said
Pettersson, an admitted alcohol and amphetamine abuser who has been
in and out of jail or mental institutions for years.
   Pettersson, 42, said he turned down offers of police protection
and help to change his appearance and identity, saying he did not
feel threatened by people who still believed he was Palme's killer.
   ``I have already started living as before. Police had plans for
me to go away for a few weeks. But I must face the world at some
point anyway,'' he told a crowded news conference in the office of
his attorney, Arne Liljeros.
   ``What can I do? Can I live in some other part of the world? No,
I don't think so,'' he said.
   The appellate court on Thursday found the evidence against
Pettersson insufficient. His release left police with no suspects,
no new witnesses and no apparent leads to unravel the mystery of
Palme's shooting Feb. 28, 1986, while he walked with his wife on a
Stockholm street.
   ``The investigation of the Palme murder will continue,'' said
state prosecutor Axel Morath.
   The small team of detectives still on the case were focusing
efforts on finding the missing murder weapon, a .357-caliber Magnum
pistol, or any other forensic evidence, said a senior police
official.
   Palme dominated Swedish politics for nearly two decades and was
an international figure for socialist causes and nuclear
disarmament. His slaying shocked this nation unaccustomed to street
violence or political assassination.
   Palme was shot from close range while he and his wife, Lisbeth
walked home from a movie.
   Pettersson, who was sentenced by the District Court to life
imprisonment, has maintained his innocence. He spent his first
night of freedom playing cards and drinking with a neighbor.
   Pettersson has received help from the Swedish welfare state
through an ``early retirement'' program, often used to support
drunks or other people considered unemployable.
   Talkative and joking, Pettersson fielded questions in Swedish
and English. He said he held no rancor toward Mrs. Palme, whose
testimony was the key to the prosection's case against him.
   Though he said he would like to meet Mrs. Palme, he admitted it
would be unlikely. ``But if it would happen, I would like to hug
her. I share her loss and do not think she is lying.''
   Mrs. Palme testified that she saw Pettersson when she looked up
from her dying husband and was ``100 percent'' certain he was the
gunman.
   Legal experts said that unequivocal statement would prohibit her
from testifying against anyone else accused of the crime. Another
half-dozen witnesses who claimed to have seen Pettersson stalking
Palme on the night of the crime also would be disqualified in any
future case, they said.
   Mrs. Palme made no immediate public comment on Pettersson's
release.
</TEXT>
