<FIRST>r a AM-MoscowManagers     10-13 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Moscow Managers,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moscow Construction Officials Visit To Learn Capitalist Ways</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CASSANDRA BURRELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-two Moscow managers are in the United
States to pick up a few tips on capitalism in trip that would have
been taboo just three years ago.
   Four senior construction executives said Friday the eight-week
trip is part of their own version of perestroika, a bid to
modernize and restructure Moscow's infrastructure.
   The four are guests of KPMG Peat Marwick, a New York-based
management and consulting firm.
   ``This training is very important,'' said Andrei Stroyev, 42,
head of Mosinzhstroy, the Moscow agency responsible for
infrastructure construction and rehabilitation. It also serves as a
general contractor in Moscow, a city of about 8 million residents.
   ``I'm absolutely sure that this visit is the most important part
of the whole training process,'' Stroyev said Friday during a news
conference here.
   The executives are busy touring construction sites and observing
management and design practices in Pittsburgh, San Francisco,
Atlanta, Miami, New York City and neighboring areas.
   The trip is paid for with money already earned by Perestroika
Joint Venture, a partnership Stroyev formed with the Atlanta-based
Worsham Group Inc., a development firm building office and living
space in Moscow for foreigners.
   Stroyev is chairman of the partnership, which came into
existence after Soviet officials passed a law in 1987 allowing
Soviet agencies to form joint ventures with foreign companies.
   The partnership began four construction projects in Moscow this
year, and has received six year's rent in cash from their clients,
he said.
   ``The reason why we chose this direction is actually there is
really a serious shortage of office space, shortage of hotels and
apartments, in Moscow for foreign communities,'' Stroyev said.
   ``This gives us the possibility to invest some hard currency to
speed up the process of construction and then to get back very good
return on the investments.''
   The joint venture also is hoping to put together deals that
would send Moscow construction crews to work on projects in other
countries, he said.
   The management training program began in June and July with a
two-month series of lectures on U.S. business and culture. The 22
Soviet executives visiting the U.S. this month will be followed by
25 other Mosinzhstroy managers in November.
   About 150 others, lower level managers, will visit the U.S. and
other foreign nations next year.
   The four Pittsburgh visitors _ Yefim Sloutski, 50, Georgy
Sinitzki, 54, Vladimir P. Samoilov, 62, and Valentin G. Lerner, 53,
all of Moscow _ are tunnel experts who supervise departments of
about 2,500 employees each. Mosinzhstroy has about 35,000 employess.
</TEXT>
