<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 1713EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Banks-BradyPlan     10-13 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Banks-Brady Plan,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Citicorp Head Says Banks Feeling Betrayed by Bush Tactics</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Business Outook</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the nation's largest bank
said Friday that some bankers feel betrayed by high-handed tactics
they contend the Bush administration is using to push its Third
World debt-reduction strategy.
   Citicorp Chairman John Reed said the debt initiative unveiled in
March by Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady had generated enormous
tension in the banking industry, in part because banks weren't
consulted before the plan was put in place.
   ``With no warning and no obvious reason, all of a sudden the
banks are being asked to shoulder serious economic burdens,'' Reed
said.
   ``For those (bankers) who are walking around feeling there is an
element of betrayal and high-handed action and lack of consultation
and so forth, there is tons of evidence to support that.''
   Reed, who spoke to reporters at the fall meeting of the Business
Council, did not say that he fully agreed with those feelings.
Instead, he said he preferred a more benign interpretation of the
administration's actions.
   ``Depending on the way you look at the coin, on the one hand you
could feel betrayal and a change of signals and on the other hand
you could look and see what is going on as a necessary
pre-condition to get this (debt crisis) behind us,'' he said.
   There have been reports of shouting matches between bankers and
administration officials, and a senior Treasury official warned
last week that if commercial banks fail to lend more money to
Mexico the consequences for the banks could be ``very painful.''
   The Brady plan calls on banks to forgive part of their Third
World loans and to make new loans.
   Many bankers predict that because the plan envisions substantial
write-offs of old debt, the banks will turn their backs on the
Third World and refuse to provide the new loans needed to keep
developing countries afloat.
   Treasury undersecretary David Mulford, the chief architect of
the administration's debt strategy, briefed the Business Council on
the proposal Friday.
   Afterward, in a session with reporters, Mulford said it was a
``fact of life that the debt strategy is a very difficult problem''
for the banks as well as the debtor countries.
   ``Since not everybody can have everything that they want, then
obviously everybody will have some degree of unhappiness,'' he said.
   Mulford denied that he or others in the administration were
putting pressure on the banks to go along with debt reduction. But
he said that for banks willing to write off a portion of their old
debt, the Brady plan does offer various guarantees through
international lending agencies that the remaining debt will be
repaid.
   Mulford said that negotiations with Mexico, the first country to
benefit from the Brady plan, were ``on track'' for completion later
this year and that talks were also going forward with other
countries, including Venezuela.
   Reed said he believed that the Mexican negotiations would result
in enough banks coming forward with new money to make the plan work
but that it would not be known for sure until Nov. 1, the deadline
for banks to submit their proposals.
</TEXT>
