<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 1713EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Georgia     10-13 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Georgia,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prominent Georgian Dissident Dies in Accident Friends Say Was Suspicious</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merab Kostava, a prominent Soviet Georgian
dissident, was killed in an auto accident early Friday, the
unofficial news agency Express-Khronika reported.
   A fellow activist said Soviet authorities had threatened
Kostava's life.
   Kostava was riding with two other Georgian pro-independence
activists on a deserted wet road when the accident occurred and he
was killed, the news agency said. Tamara Chkheidze, who was
driving, and Zurab Chavchavadze, were hospitalized with serious
injuries, it said.
   No further details were available immediately.
   Zviad Gamsakhurdia, considered the dean of dissidents in the
southern Soviet republic, said Kostava had received death threats
during the summer and last week.
   ``A week ago, we were warned by one KGB man that we shall be
killed in the nearest future, Merab Kostava and I,'' Gamsakhurdia
said in a telephone interview from Tbilisi, capital of the Black
Sea republic.
   Gamsakhurdia said he also was told last summer that all leaders
of Georgian independence movement would be killed by Oct. 15.
   The threats came from ``the military staff and the military
intelligence service,'' Gamsakhurdia said, adding that he and other
dissidents were so concerned that they hired private guards for
their homes.
   During the summer, Gamsakhurdia said a grenade exploded outside
his home.
   News of Kostava's death came after business hours and Soviet
officials could not be reached for comment.
   Nationalist fervor has run high in Georgia since spring, when 20
people were killed by Soviet soldiers sent in to halt the unrest. A
recent report by a Georgian commission implicated Defense Minister
Dmitri T. Yazov and former KGB chief Victor M. Chebrikov in the
plan to send the soldiers.
   Gamsakhurdia said an impromptu gathering Friday night in
downtown Tbilisi was turning into a memorial for Kostava.
   Kostava, aged 59 or 60, was first arrested on political charges
in 1956, according to a brief obituary carried by Express-Khronika.
   He served several terms in prison camps and internal exile for
political activities, and ``even in the camps he continued his
human rights work,'' the obituary said. Kostava was released in
spring 1987 in a widespread amnesty for political prisoners.
   ``Until his last days, Merab Kostava remained one of the leaders
of the Georgian human rights movement,'' said Express-Khronika, a
former underground network now permitted to operate openly.
   Kostava was a member of the Georgian Helsinki Watch group and a
leader of the Holy Ilya Society, a religious-nationalist group
prominent in the agitation for Georgian independence.
   Georgia, a sunny, mountainous republic in the Caucasus region,
became part of the Soviet Union in 1920. Only a handful of
pro-independence dissidents were active a year ago, but the
movement has gained strength since spring.
   Thousands gathered in Tbilisi on Wednesday night to call for
independence, protest the military draft and urge an election
boycott.
