<FIRST>u w AM-US-Mideast     10-13 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Seeks To Bar PLO Members And Limit Pre-Negotiations Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel is trying to exclude PLO members from
Mideast negotiations and to limit any talks with Palestinians to
the mechanics of conducting elections on the West Bank and Gaza,
diplomatic sources said Friday.
   The sources commented as Secretary of State James A. Baker III
pressed an effort to arrange a three-way meeting in Washington. Its
main purpose would be to select Palestinians for talks with Israel
about elections in the territories.
   Baker talked by telephone again on Thursday with Egyptian
Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid and has had several
conversations with Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Arens. The U.S.
campaign was put on hold, at least so far as Jerusalem is
concerned, for the Sabbath and the celebration of the Jewish
holiday of Sukkot, which began Friday evening.
   With Baker making little apparent progress, Margaret D.
Tutwiler, the State Department spokeswoman, insisted he had set no
time limit on his effort. ``There is no date certain, there is no
deadline,'' she told reporters.
   Ms. Tutwiler and other U.S. officials declined to provide any
details of Baker's conversations with Abdel-Meguid and with Arens.
``I am not authorized,'' she said.
   But Baker is known to have presented the foreign ministers a
week ago with a five-point proposal that includes Israel holding
talks with Palestinians only if it is ``satisfied'' with the
composition of the delegation.
   Still, Arens is insisting that all members of the Palestine
Liberation Organization, whose covenant calls for the dismantling
of Israel as a Jewish state, be barred. Palestinians who are
sympathetic to PLO positions would be eligible, however.
   The meeting Baker is promoting is designed to blend Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir's proposal for elections with a 10-point
formula by Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak. This is proving to be
very difficult.
   Mubarak, after consulting with the PLO, wants the delegation to
include two Palestinians who were deported from the West Bank and
Gaza during a 22-month rebellion against Israeli control.
   Shamir and Arens, both members of the Likud coalition, are
opposed to the proposition, as well as to Mubarak's demand that
Israel agree in advance it will surrender territory as part of an
overall settlement.
   Arens is also insisting that Israel's talks with the
Palestinians be limited to making arrangements for the elections
and not serve as a forum for negotiating Palestinian demands.
   Baker, on the other hand, would permit the Palestinians to raise
whatever concerns they might have about the election plan.
   Shamir's proposals provides for the elected Palestinians to
negotiate with Israel arrangements for five years of limited
self-rule to be followed by wider negotiations on an overall
settlement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
