<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Staff     10-13 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Staff,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush denied Friday that he was
angered over internal second-guessing about the failed Panamanian
coup.
   There have been reports the President told his staff to stop
leaking post-mortem criticisms to reporters.
   Bush, saying that he's changed from the days when his
frustrations gave him ulcers, denied any ``gag order,'' saying he
only wanted to avoid any appearance he was criticizing his team.
   ``They all did a good job,'' he said at a news conference.
   But the president immediately indicated there might have been
something that riled him a bit.
   ``Normally I might get a little more tense. I wouldn't blow up,
I don't think. And that's why I had ulcers 20 years ago, because I
didn't, I kept it all inside. But I learned now to get out there
and do your best, get the best information that you can and have
confidence in good people,'' Bush said.
   Many members of Congress criticized Bush for not coming to the
aid of dissident Panamanian military officers who tried to
overthrow Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega on Oct. 3.
   Privately, administration officials have said they were things
that could have been handled differently, and that problems such as
information flow hampered quick decision making. Bush has denied
that was the case, but officials have said that procedures are
under review.
   Other criticisms included statements that a key cable was
garbled regarding whether the insurgents would turn Noriega over to
the United States and that there had been insufficient attention to
communication links with the coup leaders.
   ``There wasn't a gag order ... and I didn't get angry. What I
did say is, I don't want to see any blame coming out of the Oval
Office or attributed to the Oval Office in the face of criticism,''
he told a news conference.
   ``I haven't lost any confidence in our top people that are
handling these matters,'' Bush said.
   Bush had a bleeding ulcer when he was in the oil business in his
early 30s. His doctor told him, ``You try to do too much and you
worry too much,'' Bush wrote in his autobiography, ``Looking
Forward.''
   ``All my life I'd worked at channelling my emotions, trying not
to let anger or frustration influence my thinking. But I'd never
given much thought to channelling my energies. That would change,
however,'' he wrote.
</TEXT>
