<FIRST>b a PM-WallStreet 4thLd-Writethru a0669 10-13 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0669,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dow Industrials Plunge 197 Points in Worst Day Since 1987 Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with figures from composite index,
American Stock Exchange; trading heaviest since January; add that record
set just Monday. Picks up 8th graf pvs, `Brokers said...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices tumbled and the Dow Jones
industrial average plummeted 197 points today in the most
spectacular drop since the 1987 crash, battered by fear of
inflation and word the United Airlines buyout may have collapsed.
   The speed of the Friday the 13th decline, which came just four
days after the Dow set a record high, spooked traders in a
startling reminder of the worst stock panic ever almost two years
ago on Oct. 19.
   At the closing bell, the unofficial tally of the widely watched
Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks had plunged to around
2,562.50, by far the biggest drop for the index this year and
second only to the crash of 1987, in terms of points lost.
Thursday's close was 2,759,84.
   ``It's total emotional and psychological chaos,'' said Eugene
Peroni, an analyst with Janney Montgomery Scott in Philadelphia.
``People are dumping everything. ... A great deal of money is being
lost.''
   When the Dow dropped 508 points on Oct. 19, 1987, closing at
1,738.74, it represented a loss of 22.6 percent of the index's
value in one day. Today's drop was about 7 percent.
   Other stock indices also fell sharply today. The New York Stock
Exchange's composite index tumbled 11.43 to 185.55. At the American
Stock Exchange, the market value index was down 16.56 at 378.45.
Bond prices rose dramatically as investors sought a safe haven for
their money in the credit markets.
   Big Board volume totaled 251.17 million shares, the heaviest
total since 254.87 million were traded Jan. 27.
   Just Monday, the index closed at an all-time high of 2,791.41.
That had been the fifth straight trading day to post a record high
close.
   The second-largest Dow plunge on record, until today, was a
156.83-point drop on Oct. 26, 1987, which brought the average to
1,793,93. The third largest was a 140.58-point drop on Jan. 8,
1988, when the Dow industrials closed at 1,911.31.
   Brokers said today's drop was triggered partly by news that a
labor-management group failed to secure financing for the proposed
$6.75 billion takeover of UAL Corp., parent of United Airlines. UAL
is a component of the Dow Transportation index.
   Others pointed to troubles in the junk bond market, where a
heavy supply of new issues coupled with investor skittishness has
severely crimped investors' appetite for the high-risk issues.
   The UAL news, combined with recent worries about the junk bond
market, ``seemed to trigger a selling panic,'' said Hildegarde
Zagorski, an analyst at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. She said
that program selling accelerated the drop.
   Still others said news from the Labor Department that wholesale
prices rose sharply in September suggested inflation was heating up
again, reducing the likelihood that the Federal Reserve would act
to ease interest rates.
   At 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow was off about 23 points. But an
overwhelming tailspin pushed the key index down an additional 100
points in little more than an hour.
   The drop is eerily reminiscent of a 108-point Dow drop on a
Friday exactly two years ago, which proved to be a harbinger of the
century's second stock market disaster. When trading resumed the
following Monday _ Oct. 19, 1987 _ the Dow plunged a whopping 508
points.
   Zagorski said she did not expect the events of 1987 to be
repeated. ``It's not going to go down too much further from these
levels,'' she said shortly before the market closed.
   The worst drop so far this year occurred on March 17, when the
Dow lost about 48 points.
  
</TEXT>
