<FIRST>r i AM-PompidouMuseum     10-13 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pompidou Museum,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Center Shut By Two-Week Janitors' Strike to Reopen After Cleanup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Georges Pompidou Center, closed for two weeks
because of a janitors' strike, will reopen this weekend but only
after it has been thoroughly cleaned, the museum director said
Friday.
   The cultural complex, a hulking metal structure with giant blue
and white pipes running along its facade, has been forced to turn
away thousands of visitors as mountains of refuse and garbage piled
up inside and out.
   The cleaning personnel, who work for four companies, went on
strike Sept. 30 demanding higher wages and representation by a
single body.
   Museum director Helene Arhweiler said in a statement that the
entire center was to be ``disinfected'' before opening its doors to
the public, but she ``strongly urged'' visitors to help keep it
clean.
   She said the strike was not ``completely settled'' and that the
agreement reached late Thursday with the strikers provided for
``minimum service.''
   She said the decision to disinfect the center was made after the
head of hygiene of the city of Paris called the sanitary conditions
``not at all satisfactory.''
   The center normally draws 25,000 people daily to a wide variety
of activities but was built originally to handle 5,000 visitors
daily.
