<HEAD>Japanese Socialists Deny Pachinko Payoffs</HEAD>
<UNK>By TETSUO JIMBO ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition Socialist Party said on Friday that
no such thing as a pachinko scandal existed.
   Socialist legislators stand accused of accepting bribes from
pinball parlor owners to lighten up on regulations restricting the
light-up industry.
   The governing Liberal Democratic Party raised the allegation in
Parliament Wednesday following reports in the Shukan Bunshun
magazine suggesting that money from Japanese-style pinball, called
pachinko, had infiltrated politics.
   ``I would like to express regret for causing concern among the
people in the so-called pachinko scandal,'' Tsuruo Yamaguchi,
secretary-general of the Socialist Party, told a news conference.
   ``But we would like to clarify that no such thing as the
pachinko scandal exists and it is no more than an illusion created
by Shukan Bunshun.''
   Yamaguchi acknowledged nine party lawmakers received $55,000 in
donations from the pachinko association, but said the donations
were legal and no member tilted toward the industry.
   ``Our investigation found no trace of wrongdoing,'' he added.
   Receiving donations from industry is common and legal in Japan
as long as recipients do no favors in return.
   The Socialist Party said it investigated claims that several of
its legislators used their influence to water down bills regulating
the pachinko business in exchange for donations ranging from $1,400
to $3,500.
   Yamaguchi also said the party is still investigating news
reports that a Socialist legislator received donations from a
pro-North Korea organization called the Association of Korean
Residents in Japan.
   Receiving donations from foreigners and foreign organizations
violates the Political Fund Control Law. Most of the 700,000
Koreans in Japan are not Japanese citizens, and are divided into
associations that favor communist North or capitalist, pro-West
South Korea.
   Koreans are major operators in pachinko, a widely played form of
pinball in which winners receive prizes. About 15,000 pachinko
parlors are strung across Japan, with annual sales estimated at $21
billion, according to industry sources.
   Yamaguchi acknowledged that the National Pachinko Parlor Owners
Association bought $31,000 worth of tickets for a fund-raising
party of Socialist Party Chairwoman Takako Doi, a pachng of Declines
</TEXT>
