<FIRST>r i AM-TerryWaite     10-13 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Terry Waite,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relatives Hope for Waite's Release as 1,000th Day of Captivity Nears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terry Waite's relatives said Friday they still
hold hope the Anglican Church envoy will be freed, and vigils were
held at several cathedrals to mark Sunday, which will be his
1,000th day as a hostage in Lebanon.
   ``I really do think that he is still alive, I feel he is,'' said
Waite's mother, Lena Waite. ``He would hate to be shut up like that
but I am sure he will come through all right.''
   His cousin, John Waite, said that as time goes on it becomes
more difficult to believe Waite is alive.
   However, John Waite added: ``He is such a nice, genuine guy I
cannot imagine even a desperado wanting to do him any harm.''
   The Church Army, the Church of England's evangelical branch,
organized prayer vigils at the cathedrals of Winchester, Bristol,
Liverpool, Rochester and London's Southwark.
   Waite was in Lebanon trying to negotiate freedom for other
Western hostages when he disappeared on Jan. 20, 1987.
   He is among 18 foreigners missing in Lebanon. They include eight
Americans, four Britons, two West Germans, two Swiss and Italian
and an Irishman.
   Most of the foreign hostages are believed held by pro-Iranian
Shiite Moslem underground factions.
   Held longest is American Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, addressing the Conservative
Party conference in Blackpool, recalled the plight of Waite and the
two other British hostages.
   ``We think of Terry Waite, Brian Keenan, John McCarthy and of
their families and friends who endure so much.
   ``Any government which has influence over those who hold
hostages should be ready as a matter of course to use that
influence to bring about their release,'' Mrs. Thatcher said.
   ``A country cannot support terrorism and still expect to be
treated as a member of the international community. To take
hostages is to exclude yourself from the civilized world.''
