<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-US     10-13 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-US,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Arms Negotiator Meets With Solidarity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. arms negotiator Edward L. Rowny
briefed Solidarity lawmakers Friday on disarmament talks with the
Soviet Union and met with Lech Walesa, leader of the independent
union.
   Walesa said he told Rowny after their meeting ``it would be good
for all of us if we changed several tanks to bread.''
   Discussions of East-West weapons levels, the U.S. approach to
talks with the Soviets and other defense topics were an added sign
change in Poland, the only Warsaw Pact nation with a non-Communist
government.
   ``We feel it very important that people understand our points of
view and ... that we seek their support,'' Rowny said.
   The American arms negotiator, whose father was born in Poland,
arrived Tuesday for official meetings and a lecture at Jagellonian
University in Krakow, where he studied in 1936.
   Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki, a Solidarity activist, has
promised allegiance to the Soviet-led military alliance, but Rowny
envisaged a growing role for Poland in the Warsaw Pact as a ``voice
in changes and reductions to come.''
   ``We see a greater influence in the Warsaw Pact of the Poles
than there used to be and we think that's good and encourage that,
and look for even more progress in the future,'' he said.
   ``We think that the government is playing a very prudent role
and is able to have a voice ... is able to do things within the
Warsaw Pact that it didn't think it could in the past, and has
enough freedom of action.''
   Rowny said the Soviets accept U.S. efforts to aid political and
economic reform in Poland.
   ``There is certainly no prohibition or inhibition that we can
see to U.S. assistance to Poland, politically or economically,'' he
said. ``There is no increase in tensions between ourselves and the
Soviets because of our frank and candid announcements that we are
going to help the Poles.''
