<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 1811EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HUDProbe     10-13 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Probe,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Reagan Administration Official Won HUD Grant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Reagan administration official won
approval of a multimillion-dollar project _ a month before the
application was filed _ after appealing directly to HUD Secretary
Samuel Pierce, a House subcommittee was told Friday.
   Former General Services Administrator Gerald Carmen said that
since its approval in early 1987, the Arlington, Texas, project has
returned $800,000 in profits to him through up-front tax credits
without risking any of his own money.
   ``I'm a little surprised at the way it went and I find myself a
little uncomfortable at the position I'm in now,'' Carmen told the
employment and housing panel of the House Government Operations
Committee.
   ``Frankly, it embarasses me.''
   Carmen said he saw the 316-unit Pebble Creek Moderate
Rehabilitation Program project as an opportunity to both ``make
money and do some good'' by providing rent-subsidized housing for
poor people.
   The onetime Manchester, N.H., businessman, Carmen got to know
Pierce during the transition between the Carter and Reagan
administrations in late 1980 and early 1981.
   Carmen was a member of Reagan's transition team for the
Department of Housing and Urban Development, and Pierce
subsequently was named to head the agency.
   Carmen was appointed by Reagan to head the General Services
Administration, which is responsible for building or leasing most
government offices and acting as a supply officer for much of the
federal bureaucracy.
   He held the GSA post until 1984, when Reagan named him U.S.
ambassador to United Nations agencies in Geneva, Switzerland. About
six months after resigning in 1986, Carmen said he learned of the
Texas project.
   Carmen said Arlington housing officials were unaware of the
potential for a rehabilitation grant until after he tried to
persuade them to submit an application.
   ``I made it plain at that discussion there were no guarantees at
all,'' he said.
   Carmen said he met with Pierce in Pierce's office for about 15
minutes in late January 1987, telling him that the city of
Arlington would be submitting an application and that he hoped it
would get proper consideration.
   ``I recall that I did not ask him for a decision and he did not
give me one,'' he said, adding that he talked with no one else in
Pierce's office about the project.
   Carmen said he didn't know of the project's approval by HUD
until late April, when the Arlington Public Housing Authority was
notified.
   The subcommittee, however, revealed a March 4 memo from
then-Federal Housing Administrator Thomas Demery to Deborah Gore
Dean, Pierce's executive assistant, on funding decisions that
included a handwritten message adding the 316 Pebble Creek units.
   ``This is the first time I've seen this,'' Carmen told the
subcommittee's chairman, Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif.
   Carmen declined to agree with an assertion by Rep. Ted Weiss,
D-N.Y., that his meeting with Pierce was the sole factor behind the
favorable action on Pebble Creek.
   ``I don't want to concede that, although I do concede that's the
way it looks,'' Carmen said. ``That's what thousands of people do
in Washington ... making sure that things don't slip between the
cracks.''
   Lantos then unveiled a memo from Ms. Dean to Pierce dated April
7 _ two weeks before the city submitted a formal application _
stating ``... and Carmen are set.''
   Lantos said the combination of the memos and Carmen's testimony
contradicts an assertion by Pierce before the subcommittee last
spring that he took no part in HUD funding decisions.
   The subcommittee has subpoenaed Pierce to testify before the
panel again later this month and in November. In his last
appearance in September, Pierce took his Fifth Amendment rights on
self-incrimination and refused to answer questions.
   Pebble Creek was developed as a limited partnership between
Carmen and Joshua Muss, a law partner of Carmen's daughter.
   Carmen and Muss used HUD guaranteed mortgages to borrow $8.2
million _ $4 million for buying a run-down apartment complex and $4
million to upgrade it _ and sharing in $2.4 million in up-front tax
credits plus $1.8 million in annual HUD rent subsidies.
   The project surfaced in an audit by HUD's inspector general in
April as an example of underwriters escalating the value of
projects in co-insuring their mortgages with FHA.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
