<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riding a parade float has its price _
even if you're Miss Nevada. In this town it'll cost at least $20.
   Nevada Day parade organizers told Miss Nevada, Brenda Anne
Linscott, that she would have to pay $20 to appear on the Lions
Club parade float _ just like other crown holders and people
participating in the 125th birthday celebration.
   But Ed Blanchard, the Nevada Day Committee parade chairman, said
Thursday there is a list of bigwigs who don't have to fork over $20
and Miss Linscott apparently isn't on the list.
   Linda Roberto, business manager for Miss Nevada, insisted Miss
Linscott should be on that dignitary list because she's the state's
official hostess.
   But Blanchard and the Nevada Day parade organizers refused to
budge.
   ``She's not getting anything free,'' said Blanchard.
   That's when the Gov. Bob Miller stepped in.
   Larry Henry, Miller's spokesman, said the governor would pay the
$20 fee for Miss Linscott.
   Miss Linscott said she wasn't aware of the dispute and prefers
to let her business manager handle money matters.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SPARKS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four-time International Whistle-Off Grand
Champion Roy Thoreson thinks he blew it this year.
   The Canadian whistling wonder and the only person to win the
contest more than once was coaxed into being on the judge's
committee for this weekend's 12th annual event.
   ``They'd just as soon I didn't compete,'' Thoreson, 58, said of
contest organizers. ``I agreed to it, but I kind of wish I was
competing.
   ``I guess they want to make way for some other people to win.
But I'll be back. I'll take a couple of years off and come back in
1991.''
   Thoreson, who began blowing melodic tunes along with his mother
and with radio shows when he was six years old, is among hundreds
of dedicated whistlers who can't imagine not putting lips together
to make music.
   ``I practiced for 40 years, from the time I was six until I was
46, before I entered my first contest,'' said Thoreson of Calgary,
Alberta. ``With all that work behind me, I'm not going to quit
now.''
   The railroad brakeman, who whistles contemporary and classical
tunes, is among 60 competitors, performers and judges scheduled to
attend this weekend's whistle-off.
   ``It's great for the voice and lungs,'' said organizer Dana
Andrus. ``And besides, you can't be unhappy if you're whistling.''
   Ms. Andrus said whistling is enjoying a resurgence after its
heyday in the 1940s when the networks had staff whistlers and
entertainers such as Bing Crosby often puckered up before the
microphone.
   Sponsored by the International Association of Whistlers, this
year's contest has six categories and also will name a Grand
Champion whistler by adding up the best scores in events entered.
