<FIRST>r w AM-NewTelescope     10-13 0146</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Telescope,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Science Board Approves $4.41 Million For Design Of New Telescope</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Science Board approved a $4.41
million award Friday for the design of a radio telescope that is to
be ``the most advanced'' in the world.
   The award for design work was granted to Associated Universities
Inc., an organization that operates the National Radio Astronomy
Observatory at Green Bank, W. Va.
   Expected to cost about $75 million and have a 300-foot dish, the
new telescope ``would be the most advanced radio telescope in the
world,'' the board's announcement said. It will replace a
25-year-old instrument that collapsed last November at Green Bank.
   Design studies for the new instrument are expected to take about
a year and the telescope is expected to become operational about
1995.
   The National Science Board is the policy-making body of the
National Science Foundation.
</TEXT>
