<FIRST>r i AM-Budd     10-13 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budd,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspect Says He Killed SAfrican Runner's Father After Sexual Assault</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOEMFONTEIN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 26-year-old man arrested in
the slaying of the father of Olympic runner Zola Budd told a
magistrate he did so after Frank Budd tried to sexually assault
him. He was denied bail Friday.
   Chris Barnard, arrested hours after Budd's body was found Sept.
22, acknowledged the shooting to Magistrate H. Ladman during
cross-examination Thursday when he sought bail, the independent
South Africa Press Association and other local news media said.
   Barnard, however, has yet to enter a formal plea. SAPA said he
was to be tried for murder.
   Barnard, who has admitted to 11 previous convictions on various
charges, said he had moved into Budd's farm near Bloemfontein two
days before the shooting to do construction work.
   Ms. Budd, 23, had been estranged from her 59-year-old father for
several years and did not attend his funeral in accordance with a
directive in his will.
   She said after his death that her father was a homosexual and
that this was a factor in her parents' separation in 1984 and
subsequent divorce.
   Because of her father's British ancestry, Ms. Budd was able to
obtain a British passport and compete in 1984 Summer Olympics in
Los Angeles. South Africans are barred from the Olympics and most
international competition because of the government's racial
segregation policies.
   In the 3,000-meter run in Los Angeles, Ms. Budd collided with
U.S. star Mary Decker, and the American was unable to continue.
Budd finished seventh to a chorus of boos.
   She later set several world distance records while living and
training in Britain, but returned to South Africa in May 1988,
complaining of mental exhaustion because of harassment from
anti-apartheid activists. She says she will race in South Africa
but make no attempt to return to international competition.
</TEXT>
