<HEAD>Kidnapped Girl Found Murdered, Suspect Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 27-year-old man was arrested Friday on suspicion
of kidnapping and murdering a girl in central Japan, police said.
   Police officials identified the man as Yuji Urayama, a former
owner of a coffee shop.
   Police said 8-year-old Misako Kobayashi was kidnapped Wednesday
near the town of Nagoya. She was found dead Friday on a hill near a
road where Urayama was arrested Thursday on charges of violating a
traffic law, police said.
   Misako, the daughter of Sei Kobayashi, 41, a carpenter,
disappeared Wednesday afternoon while heading home from a nearby
shop.
   Two hours later, a man telephoned and demanded $69,500 in
ransom, police officials said. In more than a dozen phone calls,
the man agreed that $34,750 would be enough and designated places
to receive the ransom from the father, the officials said. However,
the man did not appear.
   Police detained Urayama Thursday after chasing his car, which
ran a red light, the officials said.
   According to police figures, there have been 166 kidnap cases
involving ransom since the end of World War II, and the girl was
the 31st known victim to be killed in such a case.
   Most recently, Tsutomu Miyazaki, a 26-year-old print shop
worker, was arrested in August on charges of kidnapping and killing
four girls, ages 4 to 7, over the past year in a Tokyo suburb.
