<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-13 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tropical Storm Jerry Threatens Gulf Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical storm Jerry and unusually high tides threatened the
Gulf Coast Friday as showers and thunderstorms fell from Florida to
Texas.
   Rain also fell along the northern Pacific Coast, and
high-temperature records up to 76 years old were set or tied in
five cities across the country.
   Jerry, which formed in the southwest Gulf of Mexico, was about
520 miles south-southwest of New Orleans and heading north at 10
mph Friday evening.
   ``At the moment, Louisiana appears to be in the greatest danger,
but the storm could turn over the weekend,'' said hurricane
forecaster Gilbert Clark.
   The storm's possible effect and unusually strong tides prompted
a coastal flood watch for the Texas Gulf Coast.
   Showers and thunderstorms fell over Florida's Atlantic Coast,
and from the Florida Panhandle to the Texas Gulf Coast. Morning
rain was heavy in Florida. In Daytona Beach, 1\ inch of rain fell
in just two hours, causing local flooding.
   High-temperature records for the date were set in Evansville,
Ind., where a 91-degree reading exceeded the old mark made in 1928
by 1 degree, Paducah, Ky. (89 degrees, 88 in 1975), and Greer, S.C.
(85, 84 in 1970). Records were tied in Miami (90, 1986) and North
Platte, Neb. (89, 1913).
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 52
degrees in Bozeman, Mont., to 98 degrees in Gila Bend, Ariz. The
low for the Lower 48 states was 13 degrees in Gunnison, Colo.
</TEXT>
