<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 2138EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Marijuana-Driving     10-13 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marijuana-Driving,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>US-Sponsored Program to Test Driving Under Influence of Marijuana</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Han graf 2 is correct</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAASTRICHT, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Dutch university is recruiting
volunteers for a program commissioned by the U.S. government to
test the skills of drivers under the influence of marijuana, a
researcher said Friday.
   The two-year Limburg University project will be conducted on a
closed-off section of highway and will be the first to involve the
actual use of automobiles by drivers who have smoked the drug,
researcher Han de Gier said.
   He said the purpose of the research, commissioned by the U.S.
Department of Transportation, is to determine as realistically as
possible how marijuana affects a driver's skill and behavior.
   Marijuana is not believed to be addictive but has been blamed
for loss of concentration, lower reaction speed and even brain
damage and hallucinations in some users.
   Its effects on drivers have been investigated only under
laboratory conditions, De Gier said in an interview.
   De Gier said most of those tests had shown a negative effect on
performance.
   Motorists who smoke marijuana often drink alcohol as well,
making it difficult to pinpoint the specific cause of an accident,
he said.
   No figures on drug-related auto accidents were available from
the Dutch government.
   Volunteers in the program, to be supervised by health
authorities and the prosecutor's office, will be closely screened
and known drug dealers will be barred, the university said.
   ``We'll need to be sure subjects use marijuana regularly, at
least once a month,'' an announcement said. ``A certain amount of
driving experience will also be required.''
   De Gier denied the choice of Holland as a site was related to
the country's liberal attitudes toward drug use.
   Possession of up to 50 grams (1.75 ounces) of hashish or
marijuana is a minor offense in Holland, punishable by a
seldom-imposed maximum fine of 50 guilders ($18). Both drigs are
available in hundreds of coffee houses in Amsterdam alone.
   Dutch law forbids driving under the influence of any substance
that could impair a driver's skills, but specifically mentions only
alcohol.
   According to Limburg University figures, 10 to 15 percent of all
citizens under age 18 have smoked marijuana at least once and 5
percent are regular users.
   In the United States, up to one-fourth of high school and
college students smoke marijuana regularly, the university
announcement said.
   Marijuana is derived from the cannabis plant. Hashish, which
contains the same active chemicals in a more concentrated form, is
made from cannabis resin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891013-0102 </DOCNO>
