<FIRST>r i AM-Mozambique-Fighting     10-13 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mozambique-Fighting,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Kill 24 Civilians in Attack on Village, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels made their third major attack
on a civilian target this week, killing 24 people, the national
news agency AIM reported Friday.
   Troops of the leftist government killed three members of the
Mozambique National Resistance during the guerrilla raid Wednesday
on the southern village of Macaretane, AIM said.
   Seven civilians were also wounded during the raid, AIM said,
citing a report on state radio.
   The agency said 35 people were killed Tuesday when rebels set
fire to a bus near Chibuto, about 125 miles north of Maputo, the
capital on the Indian Ocean near the country's southern tip.
   Rebels also killed 13 people in an attack Monday on the village
of Nwachikolwane, about 90 miles north of Maputo, AIM said.
   The rebels, who have been accused of widespread atrocities, have
been fighting since 1977.
   Hit-and-run rebel attacks have devastated the economy of the
southeast African nation, one of the world's poorest. Nearly half
Mozambique's 15 million people need some form of food assistance.
