<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 2117EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Syria     10-13 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Syria,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defecting Syrian Pilot Says He Flew to Freedom</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Syrian pilot who defected to Israel
said Friday he was willing to chance flying his Soviet-built MiG-23
fighter over Israel's border missile batteries for a chance at
freedom.
   Maj. Mohammed Bassam Adel told a news conference arranged by the
Israeli army that he sometimes flew at just under 100 feet as he
crossed into Israel at high speed over the Golan Heights last
Wednesday.
   ``It was a difficult mission. I didn't know where I was going to
land. I didn't know if I would find a facility to land. I was going
into the unknown,'' the 34-year-old flyer said.
   ``The section I was crossing was spread all over with missiles.''
   Adel said he flew at 700 to 750 mph and ``below 50 meters,
sometimes 30 meters, sometimes 40.''
   A meter equals 3.3 feet.
   The dark-haired pilot chain-smoked during the news conference at
a military base near Tel Aviv. He wore an olive-green Syrian flight
suit. Adel spoke in Arabic, with Israeli officers translating his
words into English. No tape recorders or cameras were allowed.
   Much criticism has been expressed in Israel over Adel's ability
to fly into Israel without being intercepted.
   Asked about this, Adel said his own warning system indicated he
was ``observed,'' though he said earlier he switched off his
electronic gear to fly in silence.
   He said the thought of being intercepted ``entered my mind'' but
added: ``I feel that a country which has confidence cannot be
afraid of one single airplane and would take time to evaluate the
meaning of what's going on before taking action.''
   Syria has claimed Adel did not defect but landed in Israel
because his plane had technical problems. It asked the
International Committee of the Red Cross to help return the pilot
and aircraft.
   But Adel said he did not want to return home.
   ``If the Red Cross wants to meet me and take me back to Syria, I
would refuse this,'' he said.
   Adel refused to answer most questions on politics but said
Syria's pilots considered Israel's air force better than their own.
   ``No one in the Syrian air force feels that they could defeat
Israel, that they are superior to Israel,'' he said.
   The pilot said he had no contacts with Israelis before he landed
at Megiddo, 57 miles north of Jerusalem. ``Nobody was expecting
me,'' he said.
   He said he decided to flee Syria because of ``my own personal
feelings.''
   ``I wanted to live in a democracy where people can express their
views with freedom,'' he said. ``I am going to open a new chapter
by coming to Israel.''
   Asked for his views on Syria's politics, he repeated his desire
for freedom and added that ``by implication, you can presume my
thoughts about the political system in Syria.''
   Adel also was asked if he wanted to stay in Israel.
   ``I said I wanted to live in a democracy ... so you might
conclude I want to live here,'' he replied. But he added he was
uncertain what his plans were.
   The pilot said his treatment by Israelis has been ``gentle.'' He
said he was questioned mainly about his reason for defecting and
not yet about Syria's air force.
   Adel said little about his MiG-23 and refused to compare it with
other Syrian aircraft.
   He refused to answer questions about his family, saying only he
was born in Aleppo, northern Syria, and graduated from Syria's air
academy. It has been reported he is a bachelor and a Sunni Moslem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
