<FIRST>u i AM-Israel     10-13 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Palestinians Killed, At Least Four Wounded In Clashes With Troops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers shot and killed two young Palestinians
in separate incidents Friday in the occupied West Bank, the army
reported.
   A third Palestinian was seriously wounded by gunfire when he
drove his car into an Israeli man and a soldier in the occupied
Gaza Strip, the army said.
   At least three other Palestinians were wounded in clashes with
troops in the occupied lands, according to army and Arab reports.
   The confrontations came as Jews in Israel began the week-long
celebration of Sukkot, the Feast of Tabernacles, which marks the
Israelites' wandering in the desert after their biblical exodus
from Egypt. It is celebrated by building huts to symbolize life in
the wilderness.
   The deaths brought to 593 the number of Palestinians killed by
Israeli troops or civilians during the 22-month-old uprising in the
occupied lands. Another 128 Palestinians have been killed by fellow
Arabs, most on suspicion of collaborating with Israel. Forty
Israelis also have died in the violence.
   In the West Bank town of Kalkiya, 30 miles northwest of
Jerusalem, border police fatally shot Azni Ediab, 18, after he
tried to attack them with an ax, the army said. It said police
arrested another youth and placed the town under curfew.
   The second fatal shooting occurred at Beit Jala, six miles south
of Jerusalem, when soldiers encountered masked youths trying to
incite residents to violence, the army said.
   ``The soldiers ordered them to stop and fired into the air when
they tried to escape,'' said an army spokesman, who cannot be
identified under military rules. ``The troops then shot at their
legs and one youth was killed.''
   In the Gaza Strip, an Israeli civilian suffered serious injuries
and a soldier minor injuries when a Palestinian ran them down in
his car, the army spokesman said. Both were taken to hospitals in
Israel, he said.
   The spokesman said an army officer and a soldier who witnessed
the incident in Gaza City fired on the car and wounded the driver,
identified by hospital officials as Jamal Mahmoud Abdel Adi, 23, of
the Shati refugee camp.
   The army would not release the names of the Israeli civilian and
soldier and gave no explanation of why it believed the act was
intentional.
   Also in Gaza City, the army sealed the houses of two youths
detained in July and accused of being members of an underground
``popular committee'' that kidnapped and tortured Gazans to enforce
directives in the Palestinian uprising, Arab journalists said.
   A 3-year-old boy from Shati, Attiyah el-Ghurani, remained in
critical condition at the Tel Hashomer hospital in Israel after
suffering a shattered skull Thursday, the army said.
   Officials at Shifa hospital in Gaza said Thursday the injury was
caused by a rubber bullet fired by Israeli soldiers. An army
spokeswoman said initial investigations indicated troops did not
fire in the area.
</TEXT>
