<FIRST>r w AM-BorderMarines     10-13 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Border Marines,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marines Being Sent To Mexican Border</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service
said Friday that up to to 50 Marines would be deployed along the
U.S.-Mexico border to help the Border Patrol detect illegal alien
trying to enter the country.
   The INS said it had reached an agreement under which the Marines
will provide training in intelligence gathering techniques and help
the Border Patrol operate observation posts that will be equipped
with electronic detection equipment.
   The Marines will not be empowered to pursue or arrest any
illegal aliens, said INS spokesman Duke Austin.
   The Marines lack authority to enter private property, so their
activity will be restricted to federal property. Austin declined to
say where the Marines are being deployed, but it appeared they
would be concentrated in Arizona and California.
   Both states have extensive stretches federal and state land
along the Southern Border. There is little public land along the
Texas and New Mexico portions of the border.
