<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 2143EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PrayerProtest     10-13 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prayer Protest,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Says He Will Not Violate Prayer Order</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Emory Folmar said Friday he will
abide by a judge's order to stop praying at high school football
games at a city-owned stadium, but he promised to fight the
prohibition in court.
   U.S. District Judge Joel Dubina on Thursday imposed a 10-day
restraining order against Folmar and other city officials until a
hearing in a lawsuit filed by a civil liberties group.
   On Aug. 24, Folmar defied an 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
ruling that public prayers before high school football games are
unconstitutional.
   Folmar and Montgomery County Commission Chairman W.F. Joseph Jr.
stood on the 50-yard line at the city's Cramton Bowl and prayed
aloud prior to the prep season's first game as protesters blared
air horns and waved signs against the prayer.
   The mayor, however, said he will not violate Dubina's order,
which came on a lawsuit filed by the Civil Liberties Union of
Alabama against Folmar, Joseph, the city and the Montgomery County
Board of Education. Joseph also is covered by the order.
   But Folmar said he believes the federal appeals court ruling in
January, which affected Georgia, Alabama and Florida, does not
apply when events are held on city property.
   ``This temporary restraining order does apply to me and as a
constitutional officer I will not pray until I can get a new court
order in place,'' Folmar said. He said private funds, not city or
education funds, would be used to battle the lawsuit.
   In May, the U.S. Supreme Court let stand the appeals court
decision. The high court restricted pregame prayers where the
promotion of religion at a school-sanctioned event violates the
constitutional separation of church and state.
   Olivia Turner, executive director of the Civil Liberties Union,
said the August invocation by Folmar and Joseph clearly violated
the appeals court ruling.
   Dubina will schedule a hearing on the civil liberties group's
request for a permanent order against such prayers within 10 days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
