<FIRST>r w AM-Thornburgh-Soviets     10-13 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thornburgh-Soviets,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thonrburgh Taking Six-Day Trip To Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh will discuss
crime fighting tactics with Soviet officials and the American legal
system with law students during a six-day trip to the Soviet Union.
   In what is being billed as the first official visit to the
Soviet Union by a U.S. attorney general, Thornburgh and a group of
aides leave Saturday for Moscow.
   The attorney general said his discussions with Soviet legal
authorities would include ``joint law enforcmeent concerns in the
fields of drugs and organized crime.''
   ``It is my hope that through this visit we can establish a
continuing dialogue between U.S. and Soviet legal officials on
matters of common concern and interest,'' Thornburgh said in a
statement issued on the eve of his departure.
   ``We have been asked to discuss with Soviet officials such
issues as human rights, the role of the judiciary and commercial
and regulatory law, including environmental law,'' said Thornburgh.
   The attorney general also plans to meet at the U.S. Embassy with
Soviet dissidents and human rights activists, said spokesman David
Runkel.
   Soviet emigration is also expected to be a topic of discussion
between Thornburgh and Soviet officials. The department has
expressed a desire to move the processing of Soviet refugees by
Immigration and Naturalization Service officials from Rome to
Moscow.
   Such discussions would be held against the backdrop of increased
emigration and the Bush administration's decision to reduce the
number of Soviet refugees entering this country.
   On Oct. 18, Thornburgh plans to address law students at Moscow
State University about the American legal system, Runkel said. ``He
is going to talk about our basic legal system and the values that
underpin it.''
   Runkel said it was still uncertain whether Thornburgh would meet
with Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev, a graduate of the Moscow
State University law school.
   The attorney general will meet with members of the Supreme
Soviet, which is scheduled this fall to consider criminal-law
reform legislation, Runkel said.
   ``There is a great desire on the part of Soviet officials to
learn about how we deal with certain problems and issues,'' Runkel
said.
   Besides legal reform, the Soviets are interested in discussing
ways of enforcing environmental regulations. The delegation will
include Assistant Attorney General Dick Stewart, head of the
Justice Department division that enforces environmental laws.
</TEXT>
