<FIRST>r i AM-Honduras     10-13 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>International Commission Visits Contra Camps</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Francisc is cq</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos TEG3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international commission to
verify disbanding of the Contra rebels has been told the U.S.
government is ready to help repatriate the fighters to Nicaragua,
commission members said Friday.
   ``The U.S. administration is willing to earmark economic
resources for the Nicaraguan resistance to return to their
country,'' Francisc Vendrell told a news conference after a visit
to the camps of the guerrillas, known as Contras.
   ``The United States is also willing to help the functioning of
the commission.''
   Vendrell represents U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar on the International Commission for Support and
Verification. He said he had been in touch with State Department
representatives.
   The commission was created after Central American presidents
signed an agreement on Aug. 7 calling for voluntary repatriation or
resettlement of the U.S.-supported Contras by Dec. 8 in exchange
for democratization in Nicaragua.
   Enrique Bermudez, the Contras' military leader, said he was
willing to negotiate the voluntary repatriation of rebel fighters
and their families.
   However, Bermudez said he still doesn't trust Nicaragua's
leftist Sandinista government, which offered an amnesty to Contras
who choose to participate in political life there. Campaigning for
Nicaragua's presidential elections next Feb. 25 is getting into
full swing now.
   ``We demand from the Sandinistas all the fundamental human
rights before we return to Nicaragua,'' Bermudez told The
Associated Press in an interview.
   ``We don't believe the promises of the Sandinistas, who have
always misled our people, but we are willing to negotiate our
reincorporation into the political, economic and social life of
Nicaragua.''
   He accompanied the commission on its trip to the camps in
eastern Honduras near the Nicaraguan border, where about 12,000
Contra fighters and 42,000 family members have been living since
the United States halted military support to the Contra movement in
February 1988.
   Congress renewed non-lethal aid to the Contras this year on
condition it be used for disbandment if an agreement could be
reached.
   ``We are involved in a truly pacifying process in Central
America,'' said Hugo De Zela, who represents Secretary-General Joao
Baena Soares of the Organization of American States.
   Vendrell, De Zela and other observers visited the Contra camp at
Yamales, 120 miles east of Tegucigalpa, on Thursday, and met with
the Contra leadership.
   The observers said they could not give details about the
discussions, including a departure date.
   It was the commission members' fourth meeting with the Contras
and their second visit to Honduras. They will also visit the
Miskito Indian resistance based in eastern Honduras and visit
Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
