<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 2004EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-FamilyinFear     10-13 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Family in Fear,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shots Fired at Black Family in South Boston Housing Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Until Wednesday, the 1{-year-long effort to move
minority families into South Boston's tough, predominantly white
housing projects seemed to be on the right track. Just last week,
city officials reached a housing settlement with the NAACP.
   But when nine shots were fired at a black family's apartment in
one of the projects, the optimism surrounding federally mandated
housing desegration in Boston evaporated.
   Police cars converged on the Old Colony housing project, and
officers guarded the apartment of Mary Bullock, 39, and her family.
   For many residents, the incident brought back memories of the
violence that resulted from court-ordered busing in the 1970s. For
city officials, it was an alarming setback.
   In a news conference outside the Bullock apartment Friday, Mayor
Raymond Flynn said everything was being done to find those
responsible for ``this senseless shooting.'' Flynn, a lifelong
South Boston resident, said those responsible ``will pay a heavy
price.''
   No one was hurt in the incident Wednesday evening at the
third-floor apartment shared by Bullock, her husband, four children
and grandson.
   Two bullets pierced the steel door to the apartment. One
narrowly missed her 11-year-old stepson, Warren Honeycutt.
   An hour before the shooting, daughter Crystal Bullock, 17, told
police, she bumped into a white girl at a nearby convenience store.
The white girl made a racial comment and threatened to return with
others, the teen-ager said.
   Five or six teen-agers carrying baseball bats showed up within a
few minutes, and Crystal Bullock and a friend fled, she said.
   She said two other teen-agers on a motorcycle tried to run them
down as they ran to her family's apartment and that someone threw a
brick at the home after they were inside.
   Police Detective William Johnston said Friday that authorities
were close to making an arrest.
   Mary Bullock said Thursday the family would move out of the
project, but Flynn said Friday that they had decided to stay. The
family would not speak to reporters Friday, and asked the police to
keep the press away.
   The Bullocks are one of only 11 black families among 821
families at Old Colony, according to the Boston Housing Authority.
There are 29 black families among 954 families at the neighboring
Mary Ellen McCormack project.
   The shooting came a week after the city settled out of court
with the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
over discrimination in minority housing.
   The agreement will provide about $3 million in damages to around
1,500 minority families who were denied housing or steered away
from the city's mostly white housing projects.
   Flynn told reporters that most South Boston residents were
outraged by the shooting and should not be stereotyped as bigots,
but some Old Colony residents were not as reassuring.
   Richard Noll, an 11-year-old white who lives in the project,
called Warren Honeycutt ``one of my best friends.'' But he said
some of his neighbors feel differently about blacks.
   ``A lot of people hate them,'' Noll said Friday. ``I don't. I
like them.''
   A 16-year-old boy who only gave his name as Matty and said he'd
lived in a project apartment for a year complained that some of the
black families in the project ``can be really loud and make a lot
of noise.''
   ``If white people moved into Roxbury, we'd be dead within a
year,'' he said, referring to the predominantly black neighborhood.
   Another project resident, 42-year-old Nancy Green, was more
sympathetic.
   ``I was surprised,'' she said. ``It was a shooting that
shouldn't have happened.''
</TEXT>
