<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 2013EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-CannibalismConclusion 2ndLd-Writethru   10-13 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cannibalism Conclusion, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0699-a0644,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Packer Verdict: Murder and Butchery, Without a Doubt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf 23: ``The evidence,'' with reason for concluding
Packer guilty. ``ALferd'' CQ.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold prospector Alferd Packer was guilty of
murder and ate his victims, too, an expert concluded in a Friday
the 13th report on the most celebrated instance of cannibalism in
American history.
   ``Packer was as guilty as sin and his sins were all mortal
ones,'' said James E. Starrs, a professor of law and forensic
science who led a summer expedition of archeology, anthropology,
pathology and firearms experts to Lake City, Colo,. to uproot the
scarred remains of Packer's five fellow prospectors.
   They studied the bones for 30 days.
   His purpose, Starrs said at a news conference, was to show how
much can be learned through forensic science, a field he says is
underutilized in criminal investigations.
   But he also did it, he said, because ``I am an iconoclast and
this was a great icon to clast.''
   Over the years, Packer became an icon of folk history.
   At an annual feast of bad taste at the University of Colorado in
Boulder, he is toasted. His bust has been displayed in the state
capitol. In 1901, a lively newspaper campaign led authorities to
parole him 15 years after he was sentenced to 40 years in prison.
   Spreading the Packer legend has been a remark attributed to
Judge Melville Gerry upon sentencing Packer:
   ``They was sivin Dimmicrats in Hinsdale County, and ye eat five
of them, God damn ye!''
   Starrs said his scientific sleuthing established that Gerry
never said it, that the quotation was made up by a bartender.
   Packer, a Union Army veteran, was convicted of murder in 1883
and of five charges of manslaughter three years later when the
first conviction was overturned on a technicality.
   He was accused of killing his fellow prospectors in 1874 and
then staying alive by eating their flesh while stranded in the snow
during a murderous winter in the Colorado Rockies.
   His story was that one of the gold seekers, hunger-crazed
Shannon Wilson Bell, came at him with a hatchet when he returned
empty handed from a five-day sortie in search of wildlife.
   He said Bell had killed and cannibalized the others. He said he
shot Bell in self-defense, finished him off with the hatchet and
then survived the winter on his companions' flesh.
   But the bones showed contradictory evidence, Starrs said.
   ``It is plain as a pikestaff that Packer was the one who was on
the attack, not Bell,'' Starrs said.
   Wounds on the bones of three of the victims ``were caused by a
hatchet-like instrument at a time when these persons were defending
themselves from the attack of an aggressor,'' he said.
   He said the marks suggested the victims had raised their arms to
fend off blows.
   Starrs said the evidence that Packer's story is false, and thus
that Packer is guilty, is that the angle of the blade marks on the
bones from which the flesh had been taken _ including the bones
believed to be Bell's _ indicated that the cuts were all made by
the same person.
   However, Starrs acknowledged that his findings had their limits.
He said, for example, he could not be sure which set of bones was
Bell's.
   Anthropologist Walter H. Birkby of the Arizona State Museum, who
scrutinized the bones for 26 days, said he couldn't share Starrs'
conclusions.
   ``It could possibly be the right scenario, but scientifically we
cannot substantiate it,'' Birkby said.
   Last summer, Birkby went further, saying his study of the
remains actually supported Packer's story.
   Starrs, however, entertained no doubts.
   Packer, he said, ``was having his flesh filets morning, noon and
night'' even though he could have lived by killing rabbits. He said
the fresh evidence ``convicts him beyond any shadow of a doubt.''
   Starrs said Packer was a fiend, ``base ... brutish ...
barbaric.''
   The experts also tried to settle forever the fiendish question
of how Packer spelled his first name.
   ``A-l-f-e-r-d,'' said Duane J. Dillon, a criminal investigator
from Martinez, Calif.
   His evidence was elementary: on court records, military records
and parole papers, the name appears conventionally, ``Alfred,'' but
whenever Packer signed a document he used the spelling, ``Alferd.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
