<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     10-13 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>64 Dead in Guerrilla Attacks A Month Before Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW SCOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wave of leftist rebel attacks and clashes
with security forces in highland and coastal areas this week has
left more than 64 people dead, including three mayors, authorities
said Friday.
   The government says the Maoist Shining Path rebels are
attempting to sabotage municipal elections scheduled for Nov. 12 by
assassinating officials and attacking government facilities.
   This week's attacks coincided with a meeting of the Group of
Eight Latin American presidents, which took place Wednesday and
Thursday in Ica, 185 miles southeast of Lima.
   Rebel attacks left 35 people dead, including 17 guerrillas,
since Thursday, authorities said. With a total of 64 dead, this is
the heaviest week of violence since the army reported killing more
than 200 rebels in a series of encounters in July.
   In the latest incident, the government said in a communique
issued through the official news agency Andina that 14 Shining Path
guerrillas were killed and a policeman was wounded in a battle
Friday near Antauta, 590 miles southeast of Lima.
   The mayor of Tingo Maria, a jungle city 240 miles northeast of
Lima, was fatally shot by guerrillas Thursday as he walked near his
home, according to a government spokesman.
   Rebels also assassinated the mayor of Jauja, 120 miles east of
Lima Thursday. On Tuesday, rebels killed the mayor of Ananea, 610
miles southeast of Lima, in addition to the town's police chief and
nine policemen.
   The assassinations bring to at least 56 the number of mayors
killed in political violence in the last five years. Twenty-seven
of them died this year.
   Police said other Shining Path rebels toppled two power pylons
in the central highlands Thursday night, causing a total blackout
in and around the Huancayo, a city 140 miles east of Lima.
   During the blackout, rebels using dynamite bombs attacked an
army barracks, two police posts, government offices, banks, schools
and the local newspaper El Correo. One child was killed in one of
40 blasts reported by police, and two policemen were attacked and
killed.
   Rebels also blew up seven power pylons near Huaraz, 190 miles
north of Lima in the Andes, knocking out power to a region with
more than 100,000 inhabitants, according to police.
   The Shining Path launched its armed insurgency in 1980 in the
mountains near Ayacucho, 235 miles southeast of Lima, and now
operates in most of the highlands, the coca-producing jungles in
the northeast and in some areas of Peru's coastline.
   The government says more than 15,000 people have died in the
violence since 1980, including police, soldiers, rebels, government
officials and civilians.
</TEXT>
