<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Cavallaro     10-13 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Cavallaro,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Band Pianist Carmen Cavallaro Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Big Band-era pianist and composer Carmen
Cavallaro, who played the soundtrack for the movie ``The Eddy
Duchin Story'' in 1956, has died of cancer. He was 76.
   Cavallaro died Thursday at Mount Carmel East Hospital, where he
had been hospitalized since Oct. 5, said hospital spokeswoman Betty
Staley.
   John Moore, a former booking agent for Cavallaro, described
Cavallaro as a ``poet of the piano. He had a sheer love of making
people happy with his piano playing.''
   As a youngster, Cavallaro was trained in classical music and
played concerts in the United States and abroad.
   From 1933 to 1937, he was billed simply as Carmen, and he led a
five-piece combo at a St. Louis hotel in 1939.
   In the 1940s, he played in top hotels in Detroit, New York,
Chicago and other cities. A change to a swing band failed in the
mid-40s.
   In the late 1940s, Cavallaro had a Sunday afternoon radio show
called ``The Schaeffer Parade.''
   Cavallaro, who composed such songs as ``Wanda,'' ``While the
Nightwind Sings'' and ``Masquerade Waltz,'' won acclaim for
imitating Eddy Duchin's piano style in the soundtrack of ``The Eddy
Duchin Story.'' Tyrone Power portrayed Duchin.
   Cavallaro had lived in Columbus for the past 15 years, where he
remained active by giving concerts.
   He is survived by his wife, Donna, four sons and two daughters.
</TEXT>
