<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 2250EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FBI-Spy 1stLd-Writethru a0745 10-13 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FBI-Spy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0745,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-FBI Agent Ordered Freed on Bail Pending Espionage Retrial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf with 2 grafs to UPDATE with Miller reaction; picks
up 4th graf, `The appeals ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court ruled Friday that
Richard W. Miller is not a flight risk and ordered a judge to set
bail for the former FBI agent whose 1986 espionage conviction was
overturned this year.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed a detention order
issued by U.S. District Judge David Kenyon after Miller's
conviction was overturned. Miller has been in federal custody since
his 1984 arrest.
   Miller, in a federal prison in Minnesota, reacted with ``very
guarded optimism'' because of past disappointments in the case,
defense attorney Joel Levine said in Los Angeles. ``He's very
anxious to get out,'' Levine said.
   Levine expects Miller to be transferred back to California for a
bail hearing soon now that the case has been returned to federal
court in Los Angeles.
   The appeals court said the government has failed to prove Miller
is a risk to flee. The order returns the case to Kenyon to impose
``appropriate release conditions.''
   Miller is the only FBI agent convicted of espionage. The 20-year
FBI veteran was convicted of delivering secret U.S. documents to
his lover, Svetlana Ogorodnikov, a Russian emigre who pleaded
guilty with her husband, Nikolay, to espionage.
   The Ogorodnikovs are serving federal prison terms.
   A jury deadlocked in Miller's first trial, but a second jury
found him guilty and Kenyon sentenced him to two life prison terms
plus 50 years.
   The appeals court overturned the conviction in April on grounds
that Kenyon erred in admitting lie detector evidence in the second
trial in 1985-86.
   The court ordered a new trial for Miller, and the government
appealed. In July, lawyers for Miller sought to have him freed on
bail pending the appeal, but Kenyon ruled he was a flight risk and
denied bail.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals turned down the government
appeal in August, and prosecutors have not indicated whether they
will appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court or try Miller again.
   During Miller's two trials, the prosecution depicted him as a
bitter man who was reprimanded for ineptitude. They said he was
easily recruited in the summer of 1984 by Mrs. Ogorodnikov and her
husband.
   Miller went into an FBI office on Sept. 27, 1984, and revealed
his relationship with Mrs. Ogorodnikov. He claimed he was trying to
redeem his career by infiltrating the KGB.
   Prosecutors charged that Miller and Mrs. Ogorodnikov planned to
travel to Vienna to meet with Soviet intelligence agents.
   FBI agents grilled Miller for four days as Mrs. Ogorodnikov
frantically called his Lynwood home and FBI offices in Los Angeles
and Santa Ana to try to locate him. Miller arrested Oct. 2, 1984.
</TEXT>
