<FIRST>r i AM-PLO     10-13 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PLO,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Leader Says PLO Rejects Baker Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAURICE GUINDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Palestine Liberation Organization
opposes a reported U.S. plan to bring about Israeli-Palestinian
talks as the first step toward a peace settlement, a senior PLO
official said Friday.
   Yasser Abd-Rabbo, a member of the PLO's 15-man Executive
Committee, said he's against talks that don't include the PLO.
   ``This plan is not acceptable to us at all because it is the PLO
that appoints its own representatives to any negotiations,'' he
told Egypt's state Middle East News Agency.
   U.S. and Israeli proposals ``have only one aim and that is to
waste time,'' Abd-Rabbo said after arriving in Cairo for meetings
with Egyptian officials.
   Israel Radio said the plan proposed by Secretary of State James
A. Baker III would have Egypt consult with the Palestinians on the
composition of their delegation and would have Israel agree to the
dialogue only if it is satisfied with the choice of the Palestinian
negotiators.
   The Israeli plan Abd-Rabbo referred to was in May by Israeli
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir for Palestinian elections in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza sector who would negotiate with
Israel on interim autonomy. Talks on the final status of the
territories would be held later.
   Abd-Rabbo is the chief PLO delegate to PLO talks with the United
States in Tunis, capital of Tunisia. The talks began in December
after PLO chairman Yasser Arafat publicly renounced terrorism and
recognized Israel's existence. Four rounds have been held so far.
   Baker's five-point plan has not been officially disclosed. But
officials in Washington and Jerusalem said it sought to reconcile
Israeli and Egyptian views on a proposed Israeli-Palestinian
dialogue. Baker suggested he and the foreign ministers of Egypt and
Israel meet in Washington in two weeks for talks.
   Baker advanced his plan after Israel's decision-making inner
Cabinet rejected last Friday an Egyptian proposal for an
Israeli-Palestinian dialogue in Cairo. Israel objected mainly to
Cairo's suggestion that the Palestinian delegation include members
from outside the occupied territories, possibly activists deported
by Israel. Jerusalem saw it as a ploy to bring the PLO to the
negotiating table.
   The PLO's Central Council is to meet Sunday in Baghdad, Iraq, to
review all peace ideas of past months and is expected to issue a
policy statement. The council is an intermediary between the
Executive Committee and the Palestine National Council, the PLO's
parliament-in-exile.
</TEXT>
