<FIRST>r i AM-Honduras-Strike     10-13 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras-Strike,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Azcona Warns Against Nationwide Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Jose Azcona Hoyo said
Friday that he may declare a state of emergency to prevent a
walkout at a U.S.-based banana and real estate company from
becoming a nationwide strike.
   ``We will act with responsibility. We could declare a state of
emergency in the country because the interests of Honduras are
first,'' Azcona said.
   About 11,000 workers at Castle &amp; Cooke have been on strike since
Oct. 3.
   The Workers Confederation and the National Farmworkers
Organization, which together have 500,000 members, said Friday they
will join the strike Monday.
   ``I won't stand for any type of threats. The problem was not
created by the government,'' Azcona said at a news conference.
``Honduras would not put up with a general strike for even a week.
Because of this, we could declare a national state of emergency or
assume other positions.''
   Castle &amp; Cooke, based in San Francisco, has operated in Honduras
since the turn of the century and sells about 60 percent of the
nation's banana exports. Honduras exports 50 million 100-pound
boxes annually.
   The company, among other things, also has extensive land
holdings in Southern California and Hawaii.
   The labor dispute began Sept. 18 when Castle &amp; Cooke sold one of
its plants to independent packers and transferred the workers
without giving them salary increases. The union rejected the
action, saying Honduran law stipulates that pay raises accompany
transfers.
   Azcona on Monday ordered the workers back on the job and the
company not to take punitive measures.
   The strike continued, however, and negotiations Friday at the
presidential palace were unsuccessful.
   Castle &amp; Cooke is losing $250,000 daily during the strike,
according to the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
