<SECOND>AM-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0738,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Minister Resigns; Opposition Wants to Discuss Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with opposition saying it is willing
to discuss new elections, details. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The minister of government and
justice in the Cabinet controlled by Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega
resigned without explanation Friday as the regime prepared to purge
``disloyal'' public employees.
   Meanwhile, the opposition said it was willing to talk about new
elections if Noriega steps down as chief of the Defense Forces, a
condition the government rejected in unsuccessful negotiations in
August.
   Justice ministry spokesman Luis Romero Villalobos said an
official explanation for the resignation of Minister Olmedo Miranda
would be given later.
   Miranda was appointed Sept. 3, two days after provisional
President Francisco Rodriguez took office. The provisional
government was created when Noriega annulled the May 7 elections,
which independent observers said the opposition won by a landslide.
   The public payroll includes nearly 140,000 people and one-third
may be fired in the next few weeks. Earlier this week, the
government announced tough measures that, among other things, make
it easy for the government to dismiss employees considered disloyal.
   Official reports said many public employees celebrated on Oct. 3
when rebels tried to overthrow Noriega, who commands the Panamanian
Defense Forces and runs the country.
   ``Every public employee must watch out for traitors that are
infiltrated,'' Noriega told supporters two days after the botched
coup. ``We are going to make a list.''
   New laws also have frozen pay, suspended Christmas bonuses and
forbidden political activity by professional and business
associations. The government said the intent was ``preserving
national sovereignty and defending the economy'' in the face of
``aggression by the United States.''
   The United States has tried to oust Noriega since he was
indicted in Florida in February 1988 on federal charges of drug
trafficking and money laundering. He denies the charges.
   Opposition leader Guillermo Endara said Friday that the
opposition would be ``willing to hold talks on many grounds'' about
new elections.
   ``If Gen. Noriega is willing to leave, we would be willing to
consider what kind of elections could be held,'' said Endara.
   He was the opposition presidential candidate in the May
elections and international observers said he beat the government
candidate by a 3-1 margin.
</TEXT>
