<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 2334EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RapistFreed     10-13 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rapist Freed,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lifeguard Serves One-Day Sentence for Rape Conviction</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lifeguard who pleaded guilty to raping
an 11-year-old girl at a YMCA is free after serving only one day of
a three-day sentence.
   Derrick Anthony Parker pleaded guilty in August to second-degree
rape, which carries a maximum penalty of 20 years in prison. He had
been accused of raping the girl in an equipment room at the
Bethesda YMCA.
   ``I'm appalled,'' Gloria Goldfaden, executive director of the
Maryland chapter of the National Committee Against Child Abuse,
said after Parker's release. ``This is not justice.''
   State sentencing guidelines for Parker, who had no previous
record, were four to nine years. In a presentencing report, a
probation officer recommended 18 months in jail.
   But Montgomery County Circuit Court Judge William Cave on Oct. 6
sentenced Parker, 21, to five years in prison with all but three
days suspended. Cave also placed Parker on three years supervised
probation, ordered him to perform 1,000 hours of community service
and told him to have no unsupervised contact with young girls.
   Parker, a Washington resident, was released from the county jail
after spending only one day in jail. Inmates typically serve
one-third of their sentence.
   Cave said it was it one of the most difficult sentences he ever
had to hand down. But he said giving Parker a long prison term
``wouldn't benefit him and may conceivably have a disastrous
effect.''
   ``Incarceration will not restore that which was taken from
her,'' he said. ``Incarceration will not in my opinion, deter other
people from (committing rape) because they do not think of that at
the time.''
   Before announcing the sentence, Cave said, ``I'm not unmindful
that this sounds like a lack of concern or consideration on behalf
of (the victim). I certainly don't mean it to be that way.''
   Parker's attorney, Assistant Public Defender Lois Coon, said at
the sentencing that Parker had expressed ``true remorse'' for what
happened.
   Assistant State's Attorney Michelle Taylor asked Cave to
sentence Parker within the state guidelines, four to nine years.
She said the victim, a sixth-grader who told police she had a crush
on Parker, was not expecting to have sex when she went into the
room with him in October 1988.
   ``Before she knew it, it was happening,'' Taylor argued.
   Parker was arrested in January after authorities at the girl's
school learned about the incident and called the police.
</TEXT>
