<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 2336EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-King-Abernathy 1stLd-Writethru a0678 10-13 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-King-Abernathy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0678,0810</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abernathy Book Continues To Draw Attacks, A Breach In The Movement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf, `Civil rights ...,' to UPDATE
with Alabama demonstration; picks up 6th graf, `Other King ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Other books have detailed extramarital affairs
involving the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., but the Rev. Ralph David
Abernathy's autobiography was written from the inside.
   Unlike the other books' authors, Abernathy is neither a
historian nor a journalist, but a former confidante of King. And
the book's publication has opened a rift in what was King's inner
circle more than two decades ago.
   ``The other people in the movement have not written (such) books
at all; none of us have described what's alleged here,'' former
King aide John Lewis said Friday.
   In ``And The Walls Came Tumbling Down,'' Abernathy said King
``had a weakness for women.'' He wrote that King spent part of the
last night of his life in Memphis, Tenn., with two women, then
fought with a third who'd been looking for him.
   Civil rights leaders, including King aides Andrew Young Jesse
Jackson and Lewis, denounced the book Thursday, calling on
Abernathy to repudiate it and expressing doubt he'd written ``the
Memphis section.''
   On Friday, about two dozen people, including Alabama black
leaders, gathered at King's first church in Montgomery, Ala., to
call for a boycott of the book.
   ``Martin Luther King is like Christ. You've got your Judases,''
Joe Reed, head of the Alabama Democratic Party's black caucus, said
at Dexter Avenue King Memorial Baptist Church.
   Other King historians, including Pulitzer Prize-winners Taylor
Branch and David Garrow, have written King had a predilection for
women.
   In ``Parting the Waters: America in the King Years,'' Branch
wrote how King's inner circle _ including Abernathy, Young and
others _ was defined by an adjustment each made to King's private
life.
   ``These were people who tolerated or even applauded King's demon
delights as a humanizing revelation that bonded them even closer to
him and his public purpose,'' Branch wrote. ``They objected to
King's mistresses no more than to the scores of concubines who had
soothed King David.''
   Garrow also dealt with the subject in ``Bearing the Cross:
Martin Luther King Jr. and the Southern Christian Leadership
Conference.''
   ``They were not participants,'' said Lewis, now a Democratic
congressman from Atlanta. ``But this is not only a participant, but
a close friend, a leader within the movement.''
   The Rev. Otis Moss Jr., pastor of Cleveland's Olivet
Institutional Baptist Church and a friend of Abernathy, told him in
a letter that he should have higher standards than others who've
written about King.
   Moss said that while Garrow and others may focus on King's sex
life, ``you and I must forever focus on his spiritual genius.''
   The letter was released Friday by Jesse Hill, an insurance
executive who is chairman of the board of The King Center in
Atlanta and who spoke for Young, Jackson, Lewis and others in
denouncing the book Thursday.
   Lewis said he was ``hurt that someone so close to Dr. King and
so critical to our struggle for civil rights would attempt to
discredit Dr. King and our movement in this way.''
   Lewis also said he objects to ``the specific stories'' _
Abernathy's woman-by-woman account of King's last night. ``Taylor
Branch doesn't go into the gory detail,'' he said.
   ``I'm for not distorting the truth,'' Lewis said. ``Whether this
is true or not true shouldn't take anything away from the
leadership the man provided this nation.''
   A prominent black Alabama attorney, J.L. Chestnut, complained
Thursday that Abernathy ``should not be throwing stones about other
people,'' in light of reports about his own past.
   According to Branch's book, a flamboyant Montgomery, Ala., man
armed with a hatchet once chased Abernathy and complained the
minister had been sleeping with his wife since she was 15.
Abernathy refused to sign a complaint against the man.
   ``Some years later,'' Branch wrote, ``King confided to a
colleague that he not only had known of Abernathy's extramarital
liaisons in Montgomery, but had joined in some of them himself.''
   Abernathy has not returned repeated calls from The Associated
Press seeking elaboration on his book and comment on reaction to
it. Representatives of Harper &amp; Row, the book's publisher, have
said the words are his own.
   Abernathy spoke with reporters in Memphis on Thursday, where he
was promoting the book. He told them he was no betrayer of King and
that he resents accusations that strokes and brain surgery have
left his mind impaired.
   ``I'm not Judas,'' he said. ``I know who I am. I'm a Christian
minister. ... I am most surprised anybody would think I'm mentally
incompetent.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
