<FIRST>r a AM-PoliceBrutality     10-13 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Police Brutality,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two White Police Officers Indicted on Charges They Hit Black Teen-Agers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SARAH NORDGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two white police officers were indicted Friday on
battery and other charges for allegedly hitting two black
teen-agers, then forcing them out of a squad car in a white
neighborhood where they were beaten by residents. The August
incident and another in which a black man was shot to death by
police sparked allegations of police racism and prompted City
Council hearings on police brutality.
   But Cook County's chief prosecutor on Friday cautioned against
concluding the officers were racist.
   ``Why must it be put in a racial context?'' State's Attorney
Cecil Partee said at a news conference announcing the indictments.
``That's part of the problem in Chicago today. Everything is being
put in a racial context.''
   The officers _ Kathleen Moore, 31, and James Serio, 35 _ were
each charged with two counts of official misconduct, a felony, and
one count of misdemeanor battery. They will be suspended without
pay, said police spokesman Patrick Camden.
   Serio and Moore allegedly picked the 14-year-old boys up for a
curfew violation outside of Comiskey Park shortly after an Aug. 15
White Sox game.
   The standard procedure in curfew violations is to take the
offender home. But, according to prosecutors, the officers instead
drove the boys to a white neighborhood not far from the ballpark.
   Moore hit the boys before forcing them out of the patrol car,
prosecutors said.
   The boys were then beaten by a group of residents who were later
charged with aggravated battery and ethnic intimidation, said
state's attorney spokesman Dan McCullough.
   Each misconduct charge carries a maximum penalty of five years
in prison and a $10,000 fine. The battery count is punishable by up
to a year in jail and a $1,000 fine.
   Although Moore is the officer accused of hitting the boys, Serio
also faces the charge because he ``could have intervened and did
not,'' said McCullough.
   Arraignment was set for Nov. 9. The officers will not be
arrested before then because they are not considered at risk to
leave the jurisdiction, he said.
   In the second case of alleged brutality, 24-year-old Leonard
Bannister was shot to death on a South Side street by a police
officer.
   Police maintain that Bannister was shot while trying to grab the
officer's gun. But other witnesses have said that was not the case.
The man's family has filed a $5 million civil rights lawsuit
against the officer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891013-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 1138EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-TVExtra-FrogGirl Adv16   10-13 0784</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TV Extra-Frog Girl, Adv 16,0805</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday PMs, Oct. 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>Special Looks at Case of Girl Who Refused to Dissect Frog</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jenifer Graham, who refused to dissect a frog
in her high school biology class because it violated her beliefs,
is the subject of a television dramatization aimed at her fellow
students.
   ``Frog Girl: The Jenifer Graham Story,'' will be broadcast
Tuesday afternoon in the ``CBS Schoolbreak Special,'' a one-hour
show that details Miss Graham's refusal to compromise her belief
that all life is sacred.
   The show, starring Ellen Dunning as Jenifer and Kerrie Keane as
her mother Patricia, has a script by Harry and Renee Longstreet
that keeps its focus on the story and avoids the issue-of-the-week
feel that many such shows carry.
   The show was directed by Harry Longstreet and camerawork was by
Don Fauntleroy, whose wife, actress Lesley-Anne Down, was so taken
by a reading of the script that she volunteered for a bit part.
   ``I respect other people's beliefs, I just want mine respected
too,'' said Miss Graham in a recent interview. She is now 18 and a
freshman at California State University, San Bernardino with an
undeclared major.
   In the spring of 1987, her biology teacher and principal at
Victor Valley High School, and its governing board, refused a
request from Miss Graham and her attorneys to perform some
alternate work instead of dissecting a frog that had been raised
and killed specifically for lab science.
   ``I was trying to make it obvious that I would do just as much
work, if not more,'' she said. ``I felt like I was talking to a
wall. I was compared to a kid who didn't want to sit next to a
black person in typing class and someone who didn't want to run in
PE.''
   All of that just one month after starting school as a transfer
student from Nebraska, where she and her mother reached a
compromise with teachers when she refused a lab dissection in 7th
grade.
   There was initially no room for compromise at Victor Valley High
School, located in the high desert community of Victorville, 70
miles northeast of Los Angeles.
   Miss Graham said she suffered depression and her grades dropped
while she received international attention in the spring of 1987 as
the ``Frog Girl'' _ a term she loathes.
   ``Different schools act differently,'' said Miss Graham. ``But
look at the good it (the controversy) did. It passed a bill for the
whole state of California.'' She was referring to the ``Students
Rights Bill,'' which permits students morally opposed to dissection
to refrain from it in return for equivalent work.
   But the bill took effect Jan. 1 of this year _ too late to help
Miss Graham, who was stuck with a ``C'' on her transcript for the
biology class, down from an ``A.''
   A lawsuit was dismissed in August of 1988 when a federal judge
accepted the high school's offer of substituting photographs of a
frog which had died a natural death.
   But Miss Graham objected, saying she was dissatisfied with how
the school would guarantee the frog was not killed. An appeal
continues.
   Although she said she ``never lost a single friend'' over the
controversy, she is happy to resume anonymity as a college student.
``No one even recognizes me, and I don't mind a bit, to tell you
the truth.''
   Since her exposure to the power of media, she said she has
gained an interest in marketing and advertising.
   ``There are not many people who have the courage to do as she
did, and stand by her convictions,'' said Miss Down, who briefly
appears in the show as a witness before a legislative committee
considering the Students Rights Bill.
   ``It's hard enough to do when you are a grownup, but when you
are a kid, that makes you something pretty special,'' Miss Down
said. ``The lesson this teaches young people is invaluable.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in Television:
   ANSWER IS YES _ A documentary-style show, ``There Really Is A
Santa Claus,'' with veteran former NBC News correspondent Jack
Perkins as host, is being prepared after it was sold in syndication
for 115 markets, or about 81 percent of the country. There will be
interviews with a toy manufacturer, children, scientists and
government officials. Scenes are being shot at shopping malls, the
North American Air Defense Command, and, of course, the North Pole.
The Group W Productions show will be broadcast between Nov. 23
through Dec. 17. Check local listings.
   Don't worry, parents, the conclusion of Perkins' inquiry into
Santa's existence is ``yes.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, Oct. 16</NOTE>
