<DOCNO> AP891013-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 1154EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:StreetScene Adv16   10-13 0773</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Street Scene, Adv 16,0791</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs, Oct 16 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>A New York ``Street Scene'' Takes Shape in London</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inside a North London rehearsal hall lurk the
tempestuous passions of a New York tenement.
   ``Dere's been a moider,'' one actor cries in his best Noo Yawk
mimicry, while another gets advice on the correct way to say
``shirt torn'': ``It's not very articulate. It's like `shirddorn,'
'' says dialogue coach Charmian Hoare. The moment is the tragic
second-act climax of Kurt Weill's 1947 ``Street Scene,'' the German
composer's look at sultry summertime life in the Big Apple slums.
The show, which has had a checkered history, is readying its
professional London debut with an Anglo-American creative team.
   ``This is totally unique; I've never done anything like it,''
said American soprano Kristine Ciesinksi. She sings the role of the
doomed Anna Maurrant, the wife whose adultery leads to her
``moider,'' or murder.
   Internationally known English bass Richard Van Allan sings the
part of her vengeful husband, Frank, and Janis Kelly, a Scot, is
their daughter, Rose.
   Both Ciesinski and Kelly appeared in the production's British
premiere at the Scottish Opera in Glasgow last May. That was the
first professional British production of a work whose exposure here
has been limited to school stagings and a one-night charity benefit.
   Now, restaged and somewhat recast after Glasgow, ``Street
Scene'' joins London's English National Opera repertory for an Oct.
17 opening. Briton David Pountney, the ENO's director of
productions, again directs. American conductor Carl Davis is new to
the venture in London.
   Weill became famous for his collaboration with the playwright
Bertolt Brecht on such works as ``The Threepenny Opera.'' With his
wife, the singer Lotte Lenya, he emigrated to the United States in
1935. He died in 1950.
   ``Street Scene'' reunites conductor Davis with a show he first
saw in its Broadway premiere, when he was 11. He went on to be a
repetiteur (coach) on its 1959 revival at the New York City Opera,
where the show is once again in the repertory this autumn.
   ``In a way, this is a funny full circle,'' Davis said of his
current assignment. He said Peter Jonas, ENO's artistic director,
telephoned and suggested the idea. ``I said, `This is madness, but
I'd love to, for nostalgia.'''
   ``Street Scene'' has traditionally confounded purists with its
blend of operatic bravura and populist Broadway savvy.
   The show has a knockout dance number, ``Moon-faced,
starry-eyed,'' right out of Broadway's golden age. But its choral
passages and arias recall the lyricism of another hybrid, George
Gershwin's 1935 ``Porgy and Bess.''
   And despite its lowlife setting, ``Street Scene'' has more
sentiment than did Weill's earlier hard-edged collaborations with
Brecht, ``Mahagonny'' which was recently restaged in Los Angeles,
and ``The Threepenny Opera,'' due on Broadway in November, starring
pop singer Sting.
   Audiences initially found ``Street Scene'' perplexing.
   ``It was very unconventional,'' explained Davis, who has a
separate career composing and conducting music for film classics
such as Abel Gance's ``Napoleon'' and Charlie Chaplin's ``City
Lights.''
   ``At the same time, it had elements that made it attractive for
an opera company _ long developed passages for legitimate opera
voices for which all of the formulas of Broadway musicals are swept
aside.''
   ``Street Scene'' is only the second ENO production of a work
that originated on Broadway. It will play in repertory with such
operatic warhorses as Verdi's ``A Masked Ball'' and Puccini's
``Madam Butterfly.''
   Is it opera or musical? Pountney says it doesn't matter.
   ``Opera has been so many different things in its life from what
Monteverdi wrote to what Mozart wrote to what Wagner wrote,'' said
the Cambridge-educated director.
   ``To me, anything which combines theater and music might as well
be called opera as anything else.''
   Ciesinski said the show combined ``humor, tragedy, Broadway
dancing, blues, jazz, operatic singing _ all of them built up so it
flows along very naturally.'' Ciesinksi, who is married to British
baritone Norman Bailey, is making her London debut with ``Street
Scene.'' She returns to ENO next year to sing two heavyweight
roles: Strauss's Salome and Verdi's Lady Macbeth.
   ``That's more my normal meat and potatoes, so this is sort of
unusual: to create something very natural and moving _ not a crazy,
bitchy lady,'' she said.
   And although she also sings Salome in Baltimore in December, she
is pleased to be based in Europe: ``Being an opera singer is more
of a way of life here; in America, I can't even get a credit card.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Mon Oct. 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
