<FIRST>r f PM-MilkenPlaque     10-13 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Milken Plaque,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plaque Honoring Junk-Bond Financier Stolen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Pennsylvania's Wharton
School said today it would replace a plaque honoring indicted
junk-bond financier Michael Milken that was stolen from its alumni
``hall of fame.''
   The photograph of the 1979 Wharton graduate, who was indicted in
March on 98 counts of racketeering and fraud, was reported missing
Tuesday. Campus police said they believe the photograph was stolen
during the weekend.
   Wharton spokeswoman Denise Portner said today the school will
replace the plaque ``as soon as possible.''
   Milken in June as head of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s ``junk''
bond division, where he was credited with revolutionizing the
market for the high-yield debt securities used widely during the
1980s takeover boom.
   Wharton advisory board co-chairman George Walker said he thought
the plaque was stolen by students.
   ``I certainly imagine that there are some students who would be
happy to have a picture of Michael Milken hanging on their wall,''
Walker said.
   Other alumni honored at Wharton include entrepreneur Donald
Trump, media magnate Walter Annenberg and Supreme Court Justice
William Brennan.
   Drexel is the Wall Street firm that in September pleaded guilty
to six counts of securities-law violations and agreed to pay a
record $650 million in fines and penalties.
   A broader indictment against Milken, his brother, Lowell, and
former Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. trader Bruce L. Newberg is
expected to be filed by the government soon. The three have pleaded
innocent and a March trial is scheduled.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
