<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed Following Crop Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices moved slightly higher in
early trading on the Chicago Board of Trade, today while corn and
soybean futures firmed after opening lower in reaction to the
Agriculture Department's latest crop report.
   The government's new crop estimates for corn and soybeans came
in higher than expected at 7.45 billion bushels and 1.93 billion
bushels respectively.
   The 1989 wheat-crop estimate of 2.04 billion bushels was below
expectations, as was the government's projection that U.S. wheat
stocks would total 443 million bushels next May 31, the end of the
current marketing year, compared with 698 million bushels at the
end of the 1988-89 marketing year.
   ``If there was a surprise in the report, it was probably in the
wheat,'' said Walter Spilka, grain market analyst with Smith
Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. in New York. ``Those wheat stocks are
fairly tight.''
   The corn market's losses were limited by buying linked to the
USDA's announcement late Thursday of a sale of 100,000 metric tons
of U.S. corn to the Soviet Union.
   In early trading, wheat futures were { cent to 1} cents higher
with the contract for delivery in December at $4.08{ a bushel; corn
futures were \ cent to 1} cents lower with December at $2.34 a
bushel; oats were unchanged to \ cent lower with December at $1.40{
a bushel; soybeans were unchanged to 2\ cents lower with November
at $5.51{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .20 cent to .30 cent higher with October at
73.32 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to .58 cent higher
with October at 83.47 cents a pound; live hoggs were .22 cent lower
to .23 cent higher with October at 48.80 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .60 cent to 1.05 cents higher with February at 50.65
cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Thursday while pork futures were
higher, led by gains of 2 cents, the permitted daily limit, in the
pork-belly market.
</TEXT>
