<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     10-13 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0324</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices declined broadly today as the
market absorbed the news of a jump in the producer price index.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 19.88 points to
2,739.96 by noontime on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 2 to 1 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 392 up, 890
down and 510 unchanged.
   The Labor Department reported that the producer price index of
finished goods rose 0.9 percent in September, abruptly reversing a
series of declines through the summer months.
   At first, the market took the news with little evident concern.
Analysts noted that a rise of about that size had been widely
expected in the financial world.
   Economists also said they believed that much of the increase
stemmed from temporary influences that didn't necessarily portend
more bad news on inflation in the months ahead.
   However, the figures still were taken as a message that the
Federal Reserve wouldn't be very likely to take any steps soon to
relax its credit policy.
   That concern was reinforced by a separate report of an
unexpectedly strong 0.5 percent gain in retail sales last month.
   Aristech Chemical led the active list, up 4{ at 21~. The company
said it received a $25-a-share takeover proposal from a group
including investor Jon M. Huntsman.
   Losers among the blue chips included Philip Morris, down 1[ at
43\; International Business Machines, down ] at 107\; Eastman
Kodak, down { at 46{, and Procter &amp; Gamble, down 1[ at 128].
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
1.22 to 195.76. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was off 1.01 at 394.00.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 80.86 million shares at
noontime, against 71.59 million at the same point Thursday.
</TEXT>
