<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Intel     10-13 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Intel,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Intel Third Quarter Net Income Down Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Semiconductor maker Intel Corp.
Friday reported its profit in the third quarter dropped to about
half of the year-ago amount, depressed by a one-time charge related
to the end of a joint venture.
   The computer chip maker reported that net income for the third
quarter ended Sept. 30 was $72 million, or 38 cents per share,
compared to $143 million, or 78 cents per share, for the same three
months last year.
   Revenue totaled $771 million for the third quarter, down
slightly from $785 million a year ago.
   The Silicon Valley company said in a news release that the net
income figures ``reflect a previously announced $35 million charge
against pre-tax income for anticipated costs'' associated with
Intel's plans to end a computer systems venture with Siemens AG.
The charge reduced earnings per share by 12 cents for the quarter.
   For the first nine months of the year, Intel, based in Santa
Clara, Calif., said it earned $268 million, or $1.43 a share, down
about 27 percent from $367 million, or $2.05 a share, a year
earlier.
   Revenue came to $2.2 billion through September of this year,
compared to $2.1 billion through the first nine months of 1988.
</TEXT>
