<FIRST>r f BC-ContinentalBaking     10-13 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Continental Baking,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>President of Continental Baking to Retire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph A. Signore, president and chief
operating officer of Continental Baking Co., announced Friday he
plans to retire Jan. 1, ending a career that he began more than 33
years ago as a bread route salesman.
   Continental, based in St. Louis and owned by Ralston Purina Co.,
makes Wonder bread and Hostess snack cakes and is the nation's
largest wholesale maker of fresh bakery products.
   Signore, 55, joined Continental in 1956 as a route sales
representative. He was appointed as vice president and director of
sales in 1977, executive vice president and general manager of the
company's Eastern Division in 1982, and had been in his present
position since 1983.
   Signore will remain a member of Continental's board of
directors. He also will work on a variety of consulting assignments
and will continue to represent the company on various industry
trade association matters.
   Signore's duties will be divided between company Continental
Chairman Jay W. Brown and Robert W. Bracken, executive vice
president, according to Brown.
</TEXT>
