<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Media     10-13 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Media,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pulitzer Posts 2.6 Percent Profit Pickup Despite Virtually Flat Revenue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pulitzer Publishing Co. Friday posted a 2.6
percent increase in its profit for the third quarter, which the
media company said reflected cost-cutting and debt reduction
efforts.
   Revenue edged up just 0.2 percent for the quarter, which ended
Sept. 30, and would have declined slightly if not not for one-time
gains related to the company's conversion from independent
newspaper carriers to a contract delivery system in St. Louis.
   Pulitzer's net income came to $3.21 million, or 31 cents a
share, compared to $3.13 million, or 30 cents a share, in 1988's
third quarter.
   Revenue for the quarter amounted to $94.61 million, up from
$94.41 million for the same period a year ago.
   ``Despite a soft advertising market in the publishing and
broadcasting industries during the third quarter, we continued to
benefit from our debt reduction and cost-control efforts,''
Chairman Joseph Pulitzer Jr. said in a news release.
   He said the company decreased its net interest expense by
$503,000 in the quarter as compared to the same period a year
earlier.
   For the first nine months of this year, Pulitzer reported
after-tax earnings of$13.18 million, or $1.26 a share, up nearly 10
percent from $11.99 million, or $1.15 a share, a year earlier.
   Revenue through three quarters of 1989 was $292 million, a gain
of about 2.5 percent from the prior year's $285 million.
   Pulitzer publishes two metropolitan daily newspapers, the St.
Louis Post-Dispatch and the Arizona Daily Star in Tuscon, Ariz.,
and newspapers and shoppers in the Chicago area.
   The company also owns television stations in seven states and
two radio stations in Phoenix, Ariz.
</TEXT>
