<FIRST>u f PM-Spending-Taxes 3rdLd-Writethru f0054-f0024 10-13 0801</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spending-Taxes, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0054-f0024,0825</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Leaders Reach Deal on Deficit-Reduction Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs; minor editing; cuts from end to shorten. Also
moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate leaders today agreed on a plan to strip
hundreds of special-interest provisions from a $14.1 billion
deficit-reduction bill, leaving partisan fights over a capital
gains tax cut and other controversial issues for the future.
   Republican and Democratic leaders were attempting to sell the
agreement to their respective members, which if successful would
ease the way for completion of the budget-cutting bill later in the
day.
   ``We think this is absolutely the best approach,'' said Sen.
Pete Domenici of New Mexico, ranking Republican on the Senate
Budget Committee.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, said the deal would allow the Senate to pass ``a
stripped-down bill, I mean really stripped.''
   Sen. Robert Packwood of Oregon, ranking Republican on the
finance panel, said, ``This ensures we will have another tax bill
very soon _ two or three weeks.''
   He said a capital gains tax cut, a Democratic plan to expand
Individual Retirement Accounts and other proposals could be
attached to that tax measure.
   Across-the-board spending cuts on government programs totaling
$16 billion will take effect Monday unless the Senate finishes its
deficit-reduction bill, the House and Senate agree to a compromise
version and President Bush signs it into law.
   The House previously passed its own $11 billion deficit-cutting
bill loaded with special-interest provisions of its own.
   With House members out of town until next week, it seems
unlikely that a compromise bill can be completed until then. If the
automatic cuts take effect, they can be rolled back by Congress
later.
   Earlier today, Bush told reporters that while ``mixing capital
gains and IRAs in this debate is troublesome to me,'' he would let
Republicans on Capitol Hill find the solution to a dispute that has
slowed work on a $14.1 billion deficit-reduction bill.
   Asked if he was ruling out accepting broader IRAs, he said, ``I
am not ruling out anything in that regard. I am ruling in capital
gains.''
   The leaders worked out the deal as the Senate headed into a
second day of debate on the budget-cutting measure, which has drawn
criticism from members of both parties for being loaded with
provisions for special interests that do little to shrink the
deficit.
   Republicans, with support from some Democrats, have been
threatening to offer an amendment reducing the capital gains tax, a
top priority of Bush. But Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell,
D-Maine, told reporters Thursday ``without a doubt'' he would
prevent the GOP from getting the 60 votes it needs.
   ``We're going to offer it every chance we have,'' including
putting it on the deficit-reduction bill, Senate Minority Leader
Bob Dole, R-Kan., told reporters.
   The budget-cutting legislation, aimed at whittling the deficit
to below $110 billion for the fiscal year that began Oct. 1, took
its share of abuse Thursday from lawmakers who said it was stocked
with unnecessary items.
   Senate Budget Committee Chairman James Sasser, D-Tenn., whose
panel sent the legislation to the Senate floor Thursday on a 9-7
vote, said the 1,376-page measure would be only 100 pages long if
extraneous provisions were removed from it.
   Sen. William Armstrong, R-Colo., hefted the bill, which he said
weighed 12 pounds, 15 ounces.
   ``I don't think there's a single senator who has more or less a
general idea about what is in this legislation,'' he complained.
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, cited some language he said had little
to do with reducing the federal budget shortfall: ``strike
`eggplants' and substitute, `eggplants, kiwi fruits, nectarines and
plums,''' he read.
   The first amendment the Senate approved Thursday boosted
hospital spending by $40 million.
   The legislation would raise $5.3 billion in mostly minor new tax
increases, including a doubling of the current $3 tax charged to
departing international airline passengers and a new tax on
chemicals that deplete the atmosphere's ozone. It also makes
permanent the 3 percent tax on long-distance and local telephone
service that otherwise would expire next year.
   The measure raises $50 million by requiring boat owners to
purchase decals and $239 million by forcing airlines to pay for
using airports in New York, Chicago and Washington, D.C.
   It would save $3.1 billion under Medicare by reducing payments
to hospitals, freezing reimbursement rates for doctors and limiting
increases in other medical costs.
   The bill takes credit for nearly $1.8 billion in savings merely
by moving the money-losing Postal Service off-budget, and $420
million more by postponing some agriculture payments until a later
fiscal year.
   Other provisions have little to do with eliminating budgetary
red ink. Federal child care efforts are beefed up and a Commission
on Child Disability is established.
</TEXT>
