<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     10-13 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0319</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices slumped again today as the market
absorbed the news of a jump in the producer price index.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 23.16 points to
2,736.68 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 5 to 2 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 377 up,
1,040 down and 472 unchanged.
   The Labor Department reported that the producer price index of
finished goods rose 0.9 percent in September, abruptly reversing a
series of declines through the summer months.
   At first, the market took the news with little evident concern.
Analysts noted that a rise of about that size had been widely
expected in the financial world.
   Economists also said they believed that much of the increase
stemmed from temporary influences that didn't necessarily portend
more bad news on inflation in the months ahead.
   However, the figures still were taken as a message that the
Federal Reserve wouldn't be very likely to take any steps soon to
relax its credit policy.
   That concern was reinforced by a separate report of an
unexpectedly strong 0.5 percent gain in retail sales last month.
   Aristech Chemical climbed 4] to 21} in active trading. The
company said it received a $25-a-share takeover proposal from a
group including investor Jon M. Huntsman.
   Losers among the blue chips included Philip Morris, down 1 at
43]; International Business Machines, down } at 106~; Eastman
Kodak, down | at 46], and Procter &amp; Gamble, down 1} at 127}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
1.65 to 195.33. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was off 1.66 at 393.35.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 117.46 million shares with two
hours to go.
