<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 1545EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Japan-USTrade     10-13 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-US Trade,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exhort Japan to Reverse `Strong Feeling of Inequality' on Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills urged Japan
Friday to scrap what she called discriminatory, anti-competitive
trade practices and said Tokyo must work with Washington to
overcome U.S. frustration with the Japanese.
   ``Anti-competitive practices, whether official or private, run
counter to the world we seek, and to the world that brought Japan
its prosperity,'' Mrs. Hills told reporters at the Japan National
Press Club.
   ``There is a strong feeling of inequality _ where the American
market is open but markets overseas are closed, where the overseas
investor buys stocks, bonds, businesses (in America), but Americans
cannot do so overseas,'' she said. ``We must work together to bring
down that feeling of frustration.''
   Mrs. Hills arrived in Tokyo from South Korea Thursday for a
four-day visit and met later with Construction Minister Shozo
Harada.
   On Friday, Mrs. Hills told Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu that she
hopes for a ``quiet, friendly resolution'' to trade problems
between the two countries, Foreign Ministry officials said.
   She told the Japanese leader she hoped Japan would implement by
November measures to liberalize its construction market, and
increase imports of American satellites, supercomputers and
forestry products.
   Kaifu said he was working hard to get Japan to import more U.S.
products and noted that Japanese imports from the United States
last year rose $10 billion over 1987, ministry officials said.
   In her speech Mrs. Hills criticized Japan for what she described
as unfair business practices such as Japanese firms' alleged habit
of buying only from Japanese suppliers, and discrimination against
foreign investors.
   She said she was happy that a joint venture between McDonalds
Japan and an American toy retailer to set up shop in this country
was likely to be approved by the Japanese government within two
years, but added, ``even two years is a long time compared to no
wait at all when a foreign investor wishes to open a large store in
the United States.''
   The tough-talking ex-attorney also criticized a practice called
``patent flooding'' in which certain firms apply for so many
patents that competitors cannot easily market rival products.
   Asked about a public opinion poll conducted in the United States
earlier this month by the Gallup Organization that showed more
Americans thought Japan's economic strength was a greater threat to
the United States than the Soviet military, Mrs. Hills said, ``I
don't see Japanese economic power as a threat. It's a wonderful
accomplishment. But I see the destruction of the world trading
system as a threat.''
</TEXT>
