<FIRST>r f BC-MGM-UA     10-13 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-MGM-UA,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC Pondered Role With Qintex in MGM-UA Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Broadcasting Co. has
expressed an interest in joining Qintex Australia Ltd. in a bid for
the historic MGM-UA Communications Co. film and TV studio.
   But MGM-UA spokeswoman Mary Stevens Hardy and Qintex spokesman
Dan Saks declined comment Friday on whether MGM-UA and Qintex,
whose $1.5 billion merger collapsed Monday, were renegotiating the
deal.
   However, a source close to the transaction, who asked not to be
identified, said no formal talks had taken place and that if
contacts had taken place, they were extremely tentative.
   NBC spokesman Joseph Rutledge said Qintex had approached NBC
with a proposal to become a participant in their bid for MGM-UA and
``we were interested.''
   Rutledge wouldn't say how much NBC had been asked to chip in,
nor would he disclose plans to cope with federal rules that
restrict the major networks' role in owning or distributing
programming to local TV stations.
   NBC owns the NBC Television Network and NBC's chairman and chief
executive, Robert C. Wright, has been a vocal opponent of the
so-called financial interest and syndication rules, calling them an
outmoded restriction on the networks.
   Qintex first bid for MGM-UA last spring in a complicated deal
that would have resulted in it paying about $600 million for some
assets.
   Three weeks ago, media magnate Rupert Murdoch stepped in with a
last-minute, $1.4 billion bid for the entire company, but Qintex
topped that by bidding $25 a share, or $1.5 billion.
   MGM-UA's principal shareholder, Beverly Hills billionaire Kirk
Kerkorian, accepted and the deal was to have become final Dec. 15.
But the agreement collapsed Monday after MGM-UA charged Qintex with
failing to deliver a $50 million letter of credit, a nonrefundable
down payment.
   MGM-UA has filed suit in federal court in Los Angeles against
Qintex seeking at least $50 million in damages.
</TEXT>
