<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   10-13 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybeans Drop to New 23-Month Lows, Grain Markets Follow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bearish crop report and forecasts for a weekend
of good harvesting weather triggered a late plunge in soybean
futures prices to new 23-month lows Friday on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Grain futures closed mostly lower, following the soybean market
down as the trading day ended.
   The Agriculture Department's new crop estimates for corn and
soybeans were higher than expected at 7.45 billion bushels and 1.93
billion bushels respectively in a report released after Thursday's
close.
   A higher-than-expected wheat-crop estimate of 2.04 billion
bushels held traders' attention for most of the day, supporting the
wheat futures and keeping the corn and soybean markets from falling.
   But when some of the big players started selling soybeans near
the close, others rushed to join them and soybeans for November
delivery fell rapidly below $5.50 a bushel to the market's lowest
close since at least Nov. 11, 1987.
   Although the crop report didn't precipitate a major decline in
the soybean market at the opening, ``a combination of that and
other seasonal factors led to some pressure in the second half to
the session,'' said Ted Mao, grain specialist with Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. in New York.
   At the close, soybeans were 2 cents to 9} cents lower with the
November contract at $5.45 a bushel; wheat futures were 5 cents
lower to { cent higher with December at $4.06} a bushel; corn
futures were 2 cents lower to 1 cent higher with December at $2.34\
a bushel; oats were \ cent to } cent lower with December at $1.40\
a bushel.
</TEXT>
