<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 1539EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-LincolnS&amp;L 3rdLd-Writethru   10-13 0882</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lincoln S&amp;L, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0906</SECOND>
<HEAD>Citizen's Group Calls for Investigation of Five Senators</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Top 6 grafs new to CORRECT and say Common Cause asked Justice
to investigate Keating sted senators and add DeConcini response. Also subs
graf 13, In a, to conform. This also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Common Cause today asked the Senate Ethics
Committee to investigate the activities of five senators who
intervened on behalf of a California savings institution after
receiving large campaign contributions from its owner.
   At the same time, the group called on the Justice Department to
determine whether Charles H. Keating Jr. and the savings and loan
association he heads violated federal election laws.
   Lincoln Savings and Loan Association of Irvine, Calif.,
eventually collapsed and was seized by the government in April.
Analysts estimate that it could cost taxpayers $2 billion to
protect the institution's depositors.
   Fred Wertheimer, president of Common Cause, a self-styled
citizen's lobby, called for ethics committee investigations of five
senators who met with regulators in April 1987 at the request of
Keating, chairman of American Continental Corp., Lincoln's parent.
   The five are Sens. Alan Cranston, D-Calif.; Dennis DeConcini,
D-Ariz.; John Glenn, D-Ohio; John McCain, R-Ariz.; and Donald W.
Riegle Jr., D-Mich.
   McCain and DeConcini today pledged their full cooperation with
any probe. McCain, in letters to the ethics panel and Justice
Department, added, ``I am fully confident that I engaged in no
unethical conduct.''
   Cranston's spokesman, Murray Flander, said the senator met with
regulators only to urge them to bring their lengthy examination of
Lincoln to a conclusion, not to influence its outcome.
   The other senators' offices did not respond immediately to
requests for comment.
   Common Cause, along with Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., requested
the ethics investigation last year that eventually led to the
downfall of former House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas.
   Wright was also accused of intervening with regulators on behalf
of S&amp;L owners, but Wertheimer said, ``I think we have a different
case, different circumstances.''
   After three years of examinations and audits, regulators seized
Lincoln on April 14. Last month, they filed a $1.1 billion civil
lawsuit charging Keating, his family and associates with fraud and
racketeering. Among the allegations are that Keating diverted money
from Lincoln to fund his personal, political and charitable
convictions.
   All five senators received campaign contributions from Keating.
Riegle, now chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, returned his
a year later and DeConcini last month.
   Wertheimer said the Senate Ethics Committee should appoint a
special counsel to determine whether the intervention violated the
Code of Ethics for Government Service that prohibits members of
Congress from accepting ``favors or benefits under circumstances
which might be construed by reasonable persons as influencing the
performance of governmental duties.''
   In a letter today, he asked Gerald E. McDowell, chief of the
Justice Department's public integrity section, to determine whether
Keating's contribution to the senators violated federal election
laws or other statutes.
   Meanwhile, the House Banking Committee, in preparation for four
public hearings on the case, voted Thursday to subpoena Keating.
   ``We already know that in Lincoln we have on our hands a case
that will cost the savings an loan insurance fund at least $2
billion,'' House banking panel chairman Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez said
in a statement. ``This committee ... is required to determine what
went wrong within the regulatory agencies.''
   Also subpoenaed Thursday by the House panel were L. William
Seidman, chairman of the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.; M. Danny
Wall, director of the Office of Thrift Supervision; William
Crawford, California savings and loan commissioner, and other
officials.
   The hearings are expected to focus on why Wall, as the nation's
top S&amp;L regulator, delayed action from mid-1987 until April on a
recommendation from field examiners that the government take
control of Lincoln.
   The panel, on a 41-0 vote, approved the subpoenas, legal orders
to appear before the committee or produce documents. Rep. Frank
Annunzio, D-Ill., voted ``present,'' explaining later that he
believed the committee was unfairly creating the impression that
those receiving subpoenas are guilty.
   The banking committee hearings are scheduled for Tuesday and for
Oct. 24, Oct. 31 and Nov. 7.
   Keating, tentatively scheduled to testify at the last of the
hearings, issued a statement through a spokesman in Washington
saying he had not decided whether to appear voluntarily.
   ``He wants to cooperate with the committee to the maximum extent
possible but in light of the number and complexity of the legal
proceedings in which he is involved, he wants to reflect on this
decision,'' said the spokesman, Leonard Bickwit.
   Gonzalez, D-Texas, noted that Seidman requested subpoenas ``so
that the agency's testimony may be complete and the necessary
documents provided without incurring additional legal risks.''
California regulators made a similar request, he said.
   Gonzalez said the committee did not intend to ``cause
unnecessary problems'' for the lawsuits surrounding Lincoln and
American Continental, but said ``there is no question about the
paramount rights of the legislative branch in this area.''
   Also subpoenaed was Edwin J. Gray, Wall's predecessor, who met
in April 1987 with four senators regarding Keating's complaints he
was being unfairly targeted by regulators. Riegle did not meet with
Gray, but attended a second meeting with officials from the
agency's San Francisco office.
</TEXT>
