<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     10-13 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dow Plunges 100 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices took a sudden nosedive late today,
driving the Dow Jones industrial average down to a loss of 100
points with less than an hour to go before the closing bell.
   At 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow was off just 23 points, but in an hour
the average had plunged 115 points amid news that a
labor-management group failed to secure financing for its buyout of
UAL Corp., parent of United Airlines.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 3 to 1 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 353 up, 1,138 down
and 429 unchanged.
   The market had been retreating steadily but gradually for most
of the session until the group planning to buy UAL said it had run
into trouble arranging financing.
   That quickly cast a pall over shares of UAL and other companies
that have been involved in or are planning debt-financed deals.
   Brokers said the news touched a particularly sensitive nerve
among traders who had been worried lately about problems in the
market for high-yielding ``junk'' bonds.
   Earlier, the Labor Department reported that the producer price
index of finished goods rose 0.9 percent in September, abruptly
reversing a series of declines through the summer months.
   The figures were taken as a message that the Federal Reserve
wouldn't be very likely to take any steps soon to relax its credit
policy.
   That concern was reinforced by a separate report of an
unexpectedly strong 0.5 percent gain in retail sales last month.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
3.78 to 193.26. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was off 2.78 at 392.23.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 143 million shares with an hour
to go.
</TEXT>
