<FIRST>u f BC-AutoSales     10-13 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Sales,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Early October Sales Tumble</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs version planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of North American-made cars and light
trucks for the first 10 days of the 1990 model year tumbled 12.2
percent compared with the same period last year, mainly because of
declines in General Motors Corp. sales, the companies reported
Friday.
   For Oct. 1-10, GM car sales were off 24.2 percent and its truck
sales were off 28.7 percent from early October of 1988.
   The eight U.S.-based manufacturers said they sold vehicles at an
average daily rate of 30,626, compared with a rate of 34,867 during
the same time last year.
   Car sales for all makers were down 13.1 percent in early October
while truck sales were off 10.4 percent.
   Ford Motor Co.'s early-October car and truck sales were down 0.3
percent and Chrysler Corp.'s sales were off 2.3 percent.
   There had been speculation that fourth-quarter sales this year
would be significantly softer than during the third quarter. In
early October last year, sales were relatively soft compared with
earlier periods and with what proved to be the average annual sales
rate.
   Part of the reason for predictions of a soft fourth quarter was
the expectation that consumers would flock to showrooms to pick up
1989 models to beat the price 990 models.
   It was difficult to determine Friday whether that was a factor
in the decline in sales. There still are 1989 models for sale, some
with attractive rebates and low-interest financing deals.
   Chrysler on Friday announced the average price for its 1990 cars
would be 5 percent more than for 1989 versions. Earlier, Ford
announced an average increase of 4.9 percent, and GM said its 1990
prices would be 3.4 percent higher.
   For the calendar year so far, domestic cars and trucks are
selling at an average daily rate of 38,236, compared with a rate of
38,773 through Oct. 10 last year, a decline of 1.4 percent.
   Car sales for the year are running 2.5 percent behind last
year's pace while truck sales are 0.6 percent ahead.
</TEXT>
