<FIRST>r f AM-AutoPrices     10-13 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Prices,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Sets Retail '90 Prices 5 Percent Above '89 Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. on Friday said its
1990 cars would cost an average of 5 percent more than in 1989.
   It was the same increase as Chrysler's pre-introduction prices
announced earlier and the largest price increase among the Big
Three.
   Earlier, Ford Motor Co. announced a 4.9 percent increase and
General Motors Corp. an increase of 3.4 percent.
   Chrysler, like GM and Ford, said about half the price increase
was due to government requirements for air bags or automatic seat
belts for front-seat passengers.
   All of Chrysler's U.S. built cars are equipped with
driver's-side air bags as standard equipment. Chrysler said air
bags accounted for 3 percentage points in the increase.
   ``This modest increase reflects our intention to be price
competitive,'' said Chrysler Vice Chairman Gerald Greenwald.
   Base prices for the No. 3 automaker's 1990 cars range from
$6,995 for the Dodge Omni and Plymouth Horizon hatchback to $25,495
for the Chrysler Imperial.
</TEXT>
