<FIRST>r f AM-MilkenPhoto     10-13 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Milken Photo,0290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plaque Honoring Junk-Bond Financier Michael Milken Stolen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Pennsylvania's Wharton
School plans to replace a photograph of indicted junk-bond
financier Michael Milken that was stolen from the school's alumni
Hall of Fame.
   ``We have no idea of how or why it was taken, and no one has
claimed responsibility for taking it,'' Wharton spokeswoman
Margaret Barry said Friday.
   Security guards discovered Tuesday that the photograph,
described as a plaque in the campus newspaper, The Daily
Pennsylvanian, was missing.
   ``It is a photograph in a frame and it will be replaced as soon
as possible,'' she said. ``Mr. Milken was chosen by Wharton
students several years ago to be honored on the wall.''
   Wharton spokeswoman Denise Portner said the school will replace
the photograph ``as soon as possible.''
   Wharton students choose alumni to be honored for outstanding
achievements and contributions to society.
   Among the 17 alumni honored by having their photographs on a
wall of the school are entrepreneur Donald Trump, media magnate
Walter Annenberg, Supreme Court Justice William Brennan, CBS
founder William Paley, John Sculley of Apple computers, Robert
Crandall of American Airlines, and beer tycoon August Busch III.
   Milken was indicted in March on 98 counts of racketeering and
fraud in connection with his activities with the Wall Street
investment firm of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., where he headed the
junk bond division. He has pleaded innocent.
   Milken resigned from Drexel in June after the firm pleaded
guilty to six counts of securities-law violations and agreed to pay
a record $650 million in fines and penalties.
   The trial of Milken and two co-defendents is scheduled to begin
in March.
</TEXT>
