<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 2049EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-BankingHealth     10-13 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Banking Health,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Overall Banking Health Masks Problems In Northeast, Analyst Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The banking industry's overall profitably is
masking weakness in the Northeast, where real estate loans are
causing increasing problems, industry analyst Alex Sheshunoff said
Friday.
   ``Real estate is often the industry's Achilles' heel,'' he said.
   Sheshunoff singled out New York, Massachusetts and Connecticut
as trouble spots.
   ``I don't think that New England is about to become known as
`Little Texas,''' he said, ``but you're starting to see a replay of
what happened in Texas in some markets in the Northeast.''
   Banking problems have been centered in Texas and the Southwest,
where failures have set records each of the last two years.
Sheshunoff said the worst has passed in that region.
   ``The level of non-performing loans and the return to
profitability indicate that this region is beginning to bottom
out,'' Sheshunoff said. ``We anticipate that the regional economy
and its banks will be climbing back, but not bouncing back.''
   During the first half of the year, three states reported overall
losses: Arizona, $132.3 million; Texas, $98.7 million; and
Louisiana, $31.5 million.''
   Nationally, earnings were $14.1 billion, with 90 percent of the
nation's banks making a profit, Sheshunoff said.
   But those earnings ``do not reflect some underlying problems,
particularly in Northeastern states,'' he said.
   ``Particularly worrisome is the fact that real estate loans have
constituted the fastest growing segment of bank lending not only in
this quarter, but for the past five years,'' Sheshunoff said.
   ``Unfortunately, some of this real estate lending financed
speculative excesses which will take time to be absorbed, often at
significantly reduced prices with resulting loan losses.''
   Just Thursday, two large New York banks reported combined losses
of $1.1 billion in the third quarter. A large portion of the losses
came from increased reserves for loans to Third World nations.
   Included in those losses was $300 million set aside by Chemical
Banking Co. to cover possible losses on non-performing loans _
those three months past due _ at Texas Commerce Bancshares Inc., a
Chemical subsidiary.
   ``In every major bank on the East Coast, there is now somebody
taking a much harder look at their real estate loans and seeing if
they need to increase their reserves,'' said Sheshunoff.
   Sheshunoff said 57.7 percent of all non-performing loans in
Massachusetts were on real estate, 46 percent in Connecticut and
15.4 percent in New York.
   Overall, New York had the largest amount of non-performing loans
at $22.2 billion, reflecting the large concentration of loans to
Third World banks in the money center banks.
   Maine had the largest increase during the first half of the
year, as non-performing loans increased 61.3 percent, followed by
New Hampshire at 56.5 percent and Massachusetts at 44.3 percent.
   ``We're just starting to see some of the effects of the
speculative excesses that have occurred in those regional real
estate markets,'' Sheshunoff said by telephone from his Austin
office. ``In Texas, it's the aftermath; in the Northeast, it's been
really building for the last five years.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
