<FIRST>u f BC-Week'sBusiness Adv14-15   10-13 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Week's Business, Adv 14-15,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release weekend editions Oct. 14-15</HEAD>
<HEAD>Signs of Drastic Realignments in the Auto Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you're looking skyward to see whether
American Airlines has Donald Trump's name on it yet or KLM owns
part of Northwest, you may miss those Saab-Fords, GM-Jaguars or
Renault-Volvos barreling down the road.
   Like their transportation counterparts in the air, the
automakers of the world are reaching out to each other to form
strategic relationships that reflect increasingly brutal
competition on the ground.
   These alliances are coming against a backdrop of trouble in the
U.S. car market, by far the most lucrative for any major automaker.
   There are signs that Ford Motor Co., General Motors Corp. and
Chrysler Corp. all could report third-quarter losses on North
American automotive operations because of slow sales and costly
incentives aimed at luring buyers. If so, it would be the worst
showing by the Big Three since the 1982 recession.
   Problems in the American market have spilled over to Europe,
where several major automakers are struggling because they aren't
selling as many cars in the United States.
   Aggravating matters for them is the impending relaxation of
trade barriers in the 12-nation Common Market in 1992. This will
make it much easier, for example, to buy a Fiat in France, a
Renault in Italy or a Rover in Spain. That means the makers of
those cars face more competition from their neighbors.
   Moreover, competition from the aggressive Japanese is hurting
both American and European carmakers. Nissan Motor Corp., Honda
Motor Ltd. and Toyota Motor Corp. already have well-established
assembly operations in the United States, a response to Detroit's
efforts years ago to restrict foreign imports.
   Toyota said this past week it plans to double vehicle-building
capacity in the United States within the next five years. Toyota
and other Japanese carmakers are now moving quickly to establish
plants in Europe before 1992.
   These developments have forced many automakers to reassess their
ability to sell vehicles all over the world. For the weaker
competitors, that has meant forging alliances with stronger rivals
or each other.
   This past week, Renault of France and AB Volvo of Sweden
disclosed they have begun talks aimed at exploring a possible
merger or collaboration in truck or car manufucturing. Both
companies have been finding it increasingly difficult to sell cars
in the United States.
   Earlier in the week, Britain's money-losing Jaguar PLC said it
was mulling whether to sell a minority stake to GM and was
discussing possible joint manufacturing and marketing ventures with
the biggest U.S. automaker.
   Jaguar's move was partly a defensive response to unwelcome
overtures by Ford, which had earlier expressed interest in buying
all or part of the luxury carmaker and had received U.S. antitrust
clearance to purchase up to 15 percent.
   Ford also has expressed interest in buying all or part of Saab,
the Swedish carmaker that has been suffering weak sales in the
United States but has significant truckmaking operations in Europe.
   In other business and economic news this past week:
   _Signs of higher inflation and the collapse of a big buyout for
airline giant UAL Corp. sent the stock market plummeting in the
worst day since the Oct. 19, 1987 collapse almost exactly two years
earlier.
   _MGM-UA Communications Co. scrapped its agreement to be acquired
by Qintex Australia Ltd. for $1.5 billion because of financing
problems. The collapse of that deal opened the way for resumption
of takeover talks with other possible interested buyers of one of
the largest American entertainment concerns.
   _Despite little or no movement to resolve a Machinists union
strike at Boeing Co., the aerospace giant received an order
potentially worth $5 billion from Northwest Airlines. The order was
considered a blow to Boeing's European rival Airbus Industrie,
which had hoped for a longstanding relationship with Northwest
after securing a $3.2 billion order from the carrier three years
ago.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for weekend editions Oct. 14-15</NOTE>
</DOC>
