<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing 2ndLd-Writethru   10-13 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to RESTORE closing average.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The biggest wave of selling since the crash of
1987 swept through the stock market today, sending prices plunging
on the news that a big buyout deal for UAL Corp. had fallen through.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials nosedived 190.58 points,
or 6.91 percent, to 2,569.26. That marked its second biggest point
drop ever, exceeded only by the 508-point loss recorded on Black
Monday Oct. 19, 1987.
   Just four days ago the average hit a record closing high of
2,791.41.
   The market had been retreating steadily but gradually for most
of the session until the group planning to buy UAL said it had been
unable to get enough bank financing for the transaction it had
planned.
   That quickly cast a pall over shares of UAL and other companies
that have been involved in or are planning debt-financed deals.
   Brokers said the news touched a particularly sensitive nerve
among traders who had been worried lately about problems in the
market for high-yielding ``junk'' bonds.
   Earlier, the Labor Department reported that the producer price
index of finished goods rose 0.9 percent in September, abruptly
reversing a series of declines through the summer months.
   The UAL news ``was the trigger for the whole thing,'' said
Newton Zinder, an analyst at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   ``Also, it's October,'' Zinder added. ``Memories of 1987 are
still very vivid.''
   Volume on the New York Stock Exchange totaled 251.17 million
shares, up from 160.12 million in the previous session and the
heaviest total since 254.87 million were traded on Jan. 27.
   The NYSE's composite index tumbled 11.43 to 185.55. At the
American Stock Exchange, the market value index was down 16.56 at
378.45.
</TEXT>
