<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold 1stLd-Writethru   10-13 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru,0733</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Plunges After Stock Market Selloff</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 7th graf, Dollar sales...slide continues, delete extraneous
words</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Currency dealers pounded down the dollar Friday
in hectic selling incited by the worst stock plunge since the crash
two years ago.
   Harried traders reported an atmosphere of alarm suddenly
engulfed the currency markets late in the afternoon as stock prices
skidded on the New York Stock Exchange.
   ``It just seemed everybody wanted to sell dollars. It was just a
mass panic,'' said Thomas Palladino, an assistant vice president at
the New York office of the Amsterdam Rotterdam Bank.
   The intensity of the stock market selloff was especially
unnerving because it occurred almost two years to the day after the
worst Wall Street crash ever. ``There was an eerie sense of deja
vu,'' said Kevin Laurie, manager of treasury operations at the Bank
of Boston in New York. ``The dollar reacted to it pretty
violently.''
   The widely watched Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks
plunged 190.58 points to 2,569.26, the largest drop since the crash
on Oct. 19, 1987. Other stock indices also fell sharply.
   Dollar sales bred additional selling as the dollar sank below
thresholds that professional traders had designated as ``stop
loss'' levels. In stop-loss maneuvers, traders sell to guard
against possibly losing more money in case a market slide continues.
   The drop in the dollar was exaggerated by the diminished trading
volume that is typical for Friday afternoons.
   On Fridays, banks stop dealing directly with one another earlier
than on other days of the week, which reduces liquidity in the
market. Price movements have a greater impact when liquidity is low.
   Dealers said they expected the dollar to lose additional ground
against other major currencies in Asian trading over the weekend.
   Initially on Friday, two economic reports had encouraged some
dollar buying. A 0.9 percent surge in the U.S. Producer Price Index
during September and a rise of 0.5 percent in retail sales
indicated that interest rates would not decline anytime soon.
   The early enthusiasm for dollars was dampened somewhat, however,
by unconfirmed reports that central banks had sold dollars to keep
the currency in check.
   By the time trading was done for the day in New York, the dollar
stood at 142.05 yen, down from 144.15 yen on Thursday. The loss of
about 2 yen was unusually large.
   Earlier, in Tokyo, the dollar fell to 144.00 Japanese yen from
144.60 yen at Thursday's close and in London, it edged up to 144.10
yen.
   The British pound benefited from the dollar's decline. A pound
fetched $1.5820 late in New York vs. $1.5527 Thursday. In earlier
London dealings, the pound rose to $1.5625 from $1.5520 late
Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Thursday's
late rates, included: 1.8720 West German marks, down from 1.9075;
1.6420 Swiss francs, down from 1.6735; 6.34375 French francs, down
from 6.4670; 1,376.00 Italian lire, down from 1,399.25; and,
1.17385 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1749.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Thursday's
rates included: 1.9025 West German marks, down from 1.9068; 1.6720
Swiss francs, up from 1.6715; 6.4562 French francs, down from
6.4650; 2.1465 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1510; 1,396.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,397.50; and, 1.1750 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1737.
   Gold prices registered little reaction to the slump in stocks
and the dollar.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $363.30 a troy ounce, 10 cents lower than
Thursday's settlement. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
late bid for gold of $364.80 an ounce, compared with Thursday's
late bid of $363.
   In London, the metal rose to a late bid price of $364.25 a troy
ounce from $362.75 bid late Thursday.
   In Zurich, gold rose to a bid of $363.70 from $363.10 late
Thursday.
   Gold in Hong Kong rose 49 cents to a close of $363.69 from
$363.20 at Thursday's close.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid of $5.12 a troy ounce, up
from late Thursday's bid of $5.10. On New York's Comex, silver for
current delivery settled at $5.079 a troy ounce, down from $5.090
on Thursday.
</TEXT>
