<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 1830EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-S&amp;Ls-Lincoln Bjt   10-13 0721</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Lincoln, Bjt,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>Common Cause Askes Probes of Five Senators in Lincoln S&amp;L Matter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lobbying group Common Cause asked the
Justice Department and a Senate panel Friday to investigate the
intervention of five senators in the regulation of what's expected
to become the nation's costliest S&amp;L collapse.
   Common Cause, along with Rep. Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., requested
the ethics investigation last year that eventually led to the
resignation of House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas.
   Fred Wertheimer, president of Common Cause, asked the Senate
Ethics Committee to determine whether Sens. Alan Cranston,
D-Calif.; Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., John McCain, R-Ariz., John
Glenn, D-Ohio, and Donald W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich., violated ethics
rules when they met with regulators in April 1987 concerning
Lincoln Savings and Loan Association, Irvine, Calif.
   All five had received substantial campaign contributions from
Phoenix millionaire Charles H. Keating Jr., chairman of American
Continental Corp., Lincoln's parent.
   At the same time, the group called on the Justice Department to
determine whether Keating and Lincoln violated federal election
laws in their efforts to influence the senators.
   ``The joint intervention ... into a case involving alleged
violations by a specific company ... appears to be an extraordinary
action,'' Wertheimer said.
   Lincoln, which is insolvent, was seized by federal regulators on
April 14 after more than two years of audits and examinations.
Analysts estimate that it could cost taxpayers $2 billion to
protect the institution's depositors.
   Last month, the government filed a $1.1 billion civil lawsuit
charging Keating, his family and associates with fraud and
racketeering. Among the allegations are that Keating diverted money
from Lincoln to fund his personal, political and charitable
convictions.
   Leonard Bickwit, an attorney representing Keating's company,
defended the millionaire's right to contribute to and seek help
from the senators.
   ``Mr. Keating and the organizations he's been in association
with had every right to make these contributions, which were within
the limits of the law. He also has the right to seek the support of
his representatives on matters of importance to him and he ought
not to be more restricted in that regard than others who have not
contributed,'' Bickwit said, reading a prepared statement.
   According to Common Cause, Keating contributed $850,000 to three
private organizations founded or controlled by Cranston and $47,000
to Cranston's campaigns; $200,000 to a political committee
controlled by Glenn as well as a $34,000 campaign contribution;
campaign contributions of $112,000 and free jet flights valued at
$13,433 to McCain and his family; $76,100 to Riegle's campaign and
$55,000 to DeConcini's election effort.
   Riegle returned the contribution in March 1988, DeConcini last
month. McCain reimbursed American Continental for the jet flights
but has not given back the $112,000.
   The five senators all issued statements pledging their
cooperation with any probe. McCain, in letters to the ethics panel
and Justice Department, added, ``I am fully confident that I
engaged in no unethical conduct.''
   Cranston said he met with regulators to urge them to bring their
lengthy examination of Lincoln to a conclusion, not to influence
its outcome. ``I did not violate any ethics rules or standards,''
he said.
   Riegle said he attended the meeting only at the request of
McCain and DeConcini and said his conduct was ``entirely proper.''
   Wertheimer said the Senate Ethics Committee should appoint a
special counsel to determine whether the intervention violated the
Code of Ethics for Government Service that prohibits members of
Congress from accepting ``favors or benefits under circumstances
which might be construed by reasonable persons as influencing the
performance of governmental duties.''
   In a letter, he asked Gerald E. McDowell, chief of the Justice
Department's public integrity section, to determine whether
Keating's contribution to the senators violated federal election
laws or other statutes.
   In the case against Wright, the former speaker also was accused
of intervening with regulators on behalf of S&amp;L owners. But
Wertheimer said, ``I think we have a different case, different
circumstances.''
   Meanwhile, the House Banking Committee, in preparation for four
public hearings on the case beginning next week, voted Thursday to
subpoena Keating and regulators who oversaw his institution.
   The hearings are expected to focus on why M. Danny Wall, as the
nation's top S&amp;L regulator, delayed action from mid-1987 until
April on a recommendation from field examiners that the government
take control of Lincoln.
</TEXT>
