<FIRST>r f AM-CenTrust-Payments     10-13 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CenTrust-Payments,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Regulators Tighten Reins on Troubled CenTrust Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banking regulators Friday ordered financially
troubled CenTrust Bank to cease dividend payments to shareholders
and halt any stock repurchases.
   The decision by the federal Office of Thrift Supervision angered
the chairman of the Miami-based institution who said a proposed
$150 million sale of nearly all its branches would restore
financial stability.
   ``We regret the issuance of the directive, which came as a total
surprise to us,'' said David L. Paul, chairman and chief executive
officer at CenTrust, which grew since 1983 into the largest thrift
in the Southeast.
   CenTrust is seeking federal approval to sell 63 of its 71
branches _ and all the accounts in the branches _ to Great Western
Bank of Beverly Hills, Calif. The branches have more than $2.4
billion in deposits.
   CenTrust would be left with eight Dade County branches holding
about $800 million in deposits.
   ``If the regulators would approve the transaction, they would
allow us to solve our problems and, we would hope, continue to pay
our dividends,'' said Paul in a news release. ``We will use our
best efforts to try to convince our regulators that the suspension
of dividends is not in their best interest or those of the
institution. We hope they will reverse their decision.''
   CenTrust has two classes of preferred stock, both of which were
affected by the dividend ruling.
   Both stocks closed down $3.50 to $4.75 on over-the-counter
trading Friday.
   With losses of about $16 million for the first half of this
year, CenTrust has come under pressure from regulators to improve
performance and streamline operations.
   CenTrust has shrunk from more than $10 billion in assets to
about $9 billion in recent months. The institution also has been
criticized for a host of high-risk or unusual investments.
   Paul, who took over the insolvent Dade Federal Savings in 1983,
was ordered by regulators to sell a collection of paintings
purchased with CenTrust funds.
</TEXT>
