<FIRST>r f AM-Aquino-Penney's     10-13 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aquino-Penney's,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philippines President Aquino to Attend Store Festivities in Dallas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philippines President Corazon Aquino will
attend a reception and dinner in Dallas next month on behalf of a
$100 million promotion of Philippine merchandise by J.C. Penney Co.
Inc., a spokesman for the retailer said Friday.
   Spokesman Harvey McCormick said he couldn't confirm, however, if
Mrs. Aquino would visit a J.C. Penney store. Her visit to Dallas on
Nov. 10 comes three years after Britain's Prince Charles and
Princess Diana visited a suburban Washington J.C. Penney on Nov.
11, 1985, for ``The Best of Britain'' promotion.
   McCormick said Mrs. Aquino's visit would be the first time a
head of state has attended a company function. She will be in
Dallas Nov. 10-11, the same time as President George Bush, but
McCormick said he didn't know whether Bush would attend the J.C.
Penney events with Mrs. Aquino.
   The Penney ``Festival of the Philippines'' presentation of
merchandise, special events, and cultural exhibits, with a retail
value of nearly 100 million dollars, will be the largest promotion
of the Philippines ever outside the 7,100-island nation, the
company said. The promotion will be held in May.
   ``They invited Mrs. Aquino to drop by Dallas on the course of
her state visit here, so that they could show her what J.C.
Penney's is all about,'' said Philippines Embassy spokesman Adolfo
Paglinawan. ``And it may even include a visit to the J.C. Penney
store at the Preston Mall.''
   Paglinawan said the impact of J.C. Penney's orders, which he
said have a value of $30 million to $50 million, will be felt
immediately in his country.
   To meet the company's orders, factories will have to ``beef up
production,'' resulting in a ``direct infusion of dollars'' and an
anticipated increase in labor.
   ``Most of the products (being ordered) would actually benefit
the low income groups, because they are the ones that engage in the
manufacturing activities,'' he said.
   Paglinawan said Mrs. Aquino's visit is ``consistent with her
desire to really promote the expansion of trade and investments
with the Americans.''
   David F. Miller, vice chairman and chief operating officer of
J.C. Penney stores and catalogue, said in announcing the promotion
that the Philippines has a tradition of quality and fine
craftmanship had has been a growing apparel and home-furnishings
source for the company for several years.
   The promotion will include clothing, accessories and home
furnishings. It is the company's fourth international promotion.
Others have featured Italy, Great Britain and India.
   Mrs. Aquino also will be meeting with executives of oil
exploration companies during her visit to Dallas, Paglinawan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
