<FIRST>u f AM-BusinessCouncil-Markets     10-13 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Council-Markets,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Market Drop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN S. CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Executives of the country's largest
corporations were generally at a loss to explain Friday's huge drop
in the stock market although some suggested that it could be a good
thing if it cools speculative fever.
   The market plunge was an unwelcome intrusion on the annual
meeting of the Business Council, the chief executive officers of
the nation's 100 largest corporations.
   Many of them learned of the sudden plunge while out on the golf
course at the posh mountain resort where the conference is held.
   Executives swapped details of how their own stock had faired,
but few were willing to give snap judgements about what went wrong.
They said they had heard only sketchy details about the overall
decline.
   They also were not willing to forecast what direction the market
might take when it reopens on Monday.
   Howard P. Allen, head of Southern California Edison Co., said
that he did not buy the explanation, offered widely on Wall Street,
that the market drop was fueled entirely by the failure of the
buyout deal for United Airlines.
   ``I think that there has to be something more fundamental that
caused the crash,'' he said.
   Asked if he was concerned about the huge sell-off, John
McGillicuddy, head of Manufacturers Hanover Corp., said, ``Anytime
you have the market drop by 197 points, if you aren't concerned,
there's something wrong with you.''
   The drop in the Dow Jones average was actually 190.58 at the
close of trading.
   Allen Murray, chairman of Mobil Corp., said the market plunge
could turn out to be a good thing if it ``leads to a flight to
quality'' stocks and away from heavy speculation about takeover
possibilities.
   John Akers, the head of IBM Corp., noted Friday's decline was
``nowhere near as violent'' as the 508-point drop which occurred on
Oct. 19, 1987.
   But Akers said he was concerned that the rash of company
takeovers had left many corporations so deeply in debt that they
could be in serious trouble the next time interest rates increase.
</TEXT>
