<FIRST>u f AM-Market-CircuitBreakers 1stLd-Writethru   10-13 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Market-Circuit Breakers, 1st Ld-Writethru,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Market Plunge Triggers Circuit Breakers In Futures Market</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd grafs pvs, It was ... to CLARIFY that this is first
time circuit breakers triggered. Picks up 3rd graf pvs, The program ...;
SUBS 10th graf pvs, Installed last ... to spell out last breaker incident.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock-index futures trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange was halted twice Friday as tumbling stock
prices triggered ``circuit breakers'' designed to prevent a rapid,
computer-driven collapse.
   It was the first time the market had fallen far enough to
trigger 30-minute halts in trading since the circuit breakers were
installed a year after the stock market's October 1987 collapse.
   The program was enacted to provide a series of market breaks in
hopes that pauses in trading would discourage panic selling.
   But some critics of the program argued that the circuit breakers
could have the opposite effect, contributing to a frenzied rush to
sell.
   The first 30-minute halt occurred about 2 p.m. CDT after the
Merc's contract for December delivery of stocks tracked by the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index had fallen 12 points from Thursday's
close to 346.85.
   A 12-point drop in the index corresponds to a 100-point drop in
the Dow Jones industrial average.
   At that point, traders were not allowed to execute any more sell
orders at lower prices until trading resumed at 2:30 p.m. CDT.
   When trading resumed, the market traded back and forth for about
10 minutes, then plunged to 328.85, 30 points below Thursday's
close, triggering a second 30-minute pause in trading below that
price at about 2:45 p.m., traders said.
   The second trading halt extended through the market's 3:15 p.m.
closing time.
   A less-dramatic circuit breaker was triggered on March 17, when
the S&amp;P 500 futures opened with a 5-point loss, triggering a
10-minute halt to selling followed by a two-minute halt to all
trading, said Merc spokeswoman Iris Poliski. On that day, the Dow
Jones industrial average fell 48 points.
   Robert Ray, a stock-index trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
in Chicago, said the market plunged on news that a group seeking to
buy UAL Corp. had been unable to obtain financing, which triggered
new doubts about the market for high-yielding, high-risk junk bonds.
   Institutional investors use stock-index futures to hedge against
losses in the stock market, sometimes employing computer-driven
program trading strategies that can cause wild swings in prices on
both markets.
   Ray said he sympathized with program traders who tried to cut
their losses when the Dow started sliding toward what would become
a loss of nearly 191 points on the day.
   ``From the program trading end I can't blame those guys,'' Ray
said. ``At one point I don't think they could tell where the
markets were.''
   The Chicago Merc, the world's largest market for S&amp;P 500
futures, installed the trading limits last year as part of a
coordinated effort with the New York Stock Exchange to prevent
another market collapse like the 508-point drop in the Dow Jones
industrial average that occurred on Oct. 19, 1987.
   Under the coordinated program between the Merc and the NYSE, the
next trigger point would have come had the Dow Jones industrial
average fallen 250 points from Thursday's close. The Dow never
dipped that low on Friday, but if it had the procedures called for
a one-hour halt in all stock trading on the NYSE. A decline of
another 150 points on the same day would have triggered an
additional two-hour delay.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
