<FIRST>u f AM-AMR     10-13 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AMR,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump's Effort To Buy AMR Clouded By Stock Market Drop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald Trump's proposed $7 billion buyout of AMR
Corp., already surrounded by skepticism, was placed in further
doubt Friday by a stock market drop blamed in part on problems in
another airline buyout, analysts said.
   ``This seems to poison the atmosphere, at the very least, for
airline buyouts involving a lot of debt,'' said one industry
analyst who asked not to be named.
   The Dow Jones industrial average of 30 stocks fell 190.58 points
after a management-pilot group said it could not obtain financing
for a $6.75 billion buyout of UAL Corp., parent of United Airlines.
   Trump has proposed a $120-per-share buyout of Fort Worth-based
AMR, the parent of American Airlines, but the company has not
responded beyond a promise that it will consider the offer,
although it prefers to remain independent.
   Trump has said he will include $1 billion of equity in his
offer, but has provided no other financing details, leading to
skepticism over his ability to complete the deal.
   AMR's stock price slippped to $98.62{ Friday in composite
trading on the New York Stock Exchange, before trading halted in
the mad sell-off during the last hour of business. Trading was
stopped because of an imbalance of orders for AMR, with many more
sellers than buyers.
   Although the close was down just 12{ cents from Thursday, it
represented a $4.62{ drop during the day. AMR had climbed to
$103.25 before its slide began in early afternoon.
   The close was also the stock's lowest price since Trump's offer
was disclosed Oct. 5. Analysts expect the stock to continue to
trade far below the level of Trump's offer until there is a
significant move by either side.
   AMR officials would not comment on Friday's market developments;
Trump officials in New York did not return telephone calls.
   Analysts said Trump will have to lower his price if he expects
to pull off the deal.
   ``If you look at history's precedents, those situations that
were in an arbitrage environment were materially altered (by market
swings) on the downside,'' said airline analyst Kevin Burke in
Charlotte, N.C.
</TEXT>
