<FIRST>u f AM-MarketDrop-Economy 1stLd-Writethru   10-13 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Market Drop-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Treasury Secretary Sees No Economic Downturn</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4th graf: ``Securities and,'' with no comment from SEC
chairman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market plunge does not signal an
economic downturn, Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady said Friday.
   Brady was the only high administration official to comment on
the loss of more than 190 points in the Dow-Jones industrial
average.
   President Bush refused to answer reporters' shouted questions as
he boarded a helicopter at the White House to fly to his Camp David
retreat in Maryland.
   Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman Richard C. Breeden,
who took office earlier this week, spent most of the afternoon and
early evening taking calls from members of Congress and others.
Shortly before 7:30 p.m. his spokeswoman Mary McCue said there
would be ``nothing tonight'' by way of comment from Breeden.
   Also, a spokesman for the Federal Reserve Board said the central
bank would have no comment.
   But Brady said, ``Today's decline ... should be viewed in the
context of a 591-point rise since Jan. 1, 1989. It's important to
recognize that today's stock market decline doesn't signal any
fundamental change in the condition of the economy.
   ``The economy remains well balanced and the outlook is for
continued moderate growth.''
</TEXT>
