<DOCNO> AP891013-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 2213EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CouriersSuit     10-13 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Couriers Suit,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Couriers Sue U.S. Postal Service on Overseas Rates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several air courier companies have sued the U.S.
Postal Service, claiming its low price for some overseas packages
creates unfair and illegal competition.
   In a suit filed Thursday in U.S. District Court in Delaware, the
companies allege the government's $10.75 rate for express delivery
overseas of packages weighing eight ounces or less ``results in
unfair and illegal competition between the Postal Service and
private enterprise carriers.''
   The Postal Service cut its rate for that category in April from
$18 to $8.75 per package, which it described as a ``special
introductory rate.'' In June, it established a ``permanent'' rate
of $10.75. Private couriers usually charge about $20 for the same
service.
   In their suit, the companies ask the court to enjoin the Postal
Service from offering the $10.75 rate or any price that isn't
``fair and equitable.'' They contend that the government's rate is
below cost and that the Postal Service failed to get approval for
it from the Postal Rate Commission.
   Postmaster General Anthony M. Frank, defending the Postal
Service pricing, said the rates ``benefit the American householder
and smaller businesses who don't qualify for the volume discounts
offered to major corporations by these international couriers.''
   The companies filing the suit are DHL Airways Inc.,
Dworkin-Cosell Interair Courier Services Inc., Federal Express
Corp., Intertrade Courier International Inc., TNT Skypak Inc. and
UPS Air Forwarding Inc. Two industry associations _ Air Courier
Conference of America and International Express Carriers Conference
_ also participated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
