<FIRST>u f AM-Warner-Sony 1stLd-Writethru   10-13 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warner-Sony, 1st Ld-Writethru,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warner Bros. Sues Sony for $1 Billion For Recruiting Two Execs for
Columbia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, Guber and ... to DELETE ``Rain Man' which
was made for UA; SUBS 9th graf, ``We became ... to include first name of
Sony spokesman Farrow; SUBS 15th graf, Among other ... to DELETE ``Gorillas
in the Mist'' which was made for Universal.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Bros. said Friday it filed suit seeking
$1 billion in damages from Sony Corp. and others over Sony's
courtship of film producers Peter Guber and Jon Peters to run
Columbia Pictures Entertainment Inc.
   Guber and Peters, who produced the megahit ``Batman'' and other
films for Warner, have been trying to get out of a recently signed
five-year exclusive agreement to make films for Warner Bros.
   In a suit filed in Superior Court in Los Angeles, Warner accused
Sony of inducing the two executives to breach their agreement so
they could take top jobs at Columbia.
   Late Friday, Sony's U.S. arm, Sony USA Inc.; Guber and Peters
and their company announced they had jointly filed a lawsuit
against Warner Bros. in connection with Sony's proposed acquisition
of Guber-Peters Entertainment Co.
   The statement failed to say where the suit was filed, and a
spokesman was unavailable to elaborate on it.
   Sony, the Japanese electronics and recorded music giant,
announced Sept. 27 that it had agreed to buy Columbia for about
$3.4 billion.
   A tender offer for Columbia's shares is to expire Nov. 6, but
Sony said it intends to name Guber and Peters co-chairmen of the
company once it is acquired. In addition, Sony also has begun a
tender offer to buy their production company, Guber-Peters
Entertainment, for $200 million.
   Earlier this week, Sony's U.S. arm, Sony USA Inc., said it has
waived a condition in its agreement to buy Guber-Peters
Entertainment that would have allowed it o terminate the agreement
if the executives were unable to obtain waivers from their
contracts with Warner.
   ``We became satisfied that the contracts represented no
impediment to the acquisition,'' Sony spokesman Jason Farrow said
Friday.
   In addition to $1 billion in damages, the Warner suit seeks
punitive damages and an injunction preventing Guber and Peters from
breaching their commitments to Warner.
   Steven J. Ross, co-chairman and co-chief executive of Warner
Bros.' parent Time-Warner Inc. said, ``We regret that Sony has
attempted to enter the U.S. motion picture industry by illegally
and willfully raiding key talent under exclusive contract to a
competitor.
   ``This conduct cannot, must not and will not be condoned,'' he
said.
   Also named as defendants in the Warner suit are Sony USA, Guber,
Peters, their company and two Sony executives, Walter Yetnikoff and
Michael Schulhof.
   Calls placed to spokesmen for Guber, Peters, Yetnikoff and
Schulhof and the company were not returned or went unanswered.
   Among other movies that Guber and Peters were involved with for
Warner have been ``The Color Purple'' and ``The Witches of
Eastwick.''
   Warner executives say the two men are involved in about 50
projects for Warner, including sequels to ``Batman'' and movie
adaptations of the books ``Bonfire of the Vanities'' and ``A Bright
Shining Lie.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891013-0190 </DOCNO>
