<SECOND>BC-Business Highlights,0906</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A failing airline buyout knocked the stock
market off its record-setting pace with a sudden dive that erased
more than 190 points from the Dow Jones industrial average and
conjured memories of the 1987 crash.
   Nearly $200 billion was wiped out from the paper value of stocks
as more than 250 million shares changed hands on Friday.
   Over 100 million shares were traded in the last hour following
an announcement that the employee-led, highly leveraged buyout of
United Airlines parent UAL Corp. had come unglued.
   The widely watched Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks
plunged 190.58 points to 2,569.26, the biggest point drop since the
crash of 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Junk bond prices plunged as financing problems
for a major airline buyout widened fears over a possible collapse
of the slumping $200 billion market of the high-yield securities.
   News that bidders had failed to raise financing for the planned
$6.75 billion buyout of UAL Corp. also spread panic Friday that
billions of dollars in other planned debt-financed deals would have
to be scrapped.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock-index futures trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange was halted twice as tumbling stock prices
triggered ``circuit breakers'' designed to prevent a rapid,
computer-driven collapse.
   The action Friday was the first time the market had fallen far
enough to trigger 30-minute halts in trading since the circuit
breakers were installed a year after the stock market's October
1987 collapse.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot-management group attempting to buy UAL
Corp. said it could not get financing for its $6.75 billion deal.
   The group issued a statement Friday that banks managing the
financing for the proposed $300 a share acquisition of the company
indicated they had not received sufficient commitments to complete
the buyout at that price.
   But the group _ which also includes British Airways PLC _ stated
it expected to revise the proposal and continue its attempts to buy
the airline.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharp rise in energy costs helped trigger a
rebound in wholesale price inflation in September, wiping out three
rare monthly declines this summer, the government said.
   The 0.9 percent increase Friday in the Labor Department's
Producer Price Index, measuring inflation one stop short of the
retail level, represented a return to the high inflation rates
experienced in the first five months of the year.
   In another economic report, the Commerce Department said retail
sales rose a stronger-than-expected 0.5 percent last month, the
seventh consecutive rise.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plunge in General Motors Corp. car and light
truck sales led an 11.9 percent decline in early-October vehicle
sales by domestic automakers compared with last year, the companies
said.
   The eight major companies making vehicles in North America said
Friday their cars and light trucks sold at an average rate of
30,734 a day during the Oct. 1-10 period this year, compared with
34,867 during the same time last year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economic growth in 1990 will slump to
its slowest pace in eight years with an outright recession a
distinct threat unless the Federal Reserve lowers interest rates,
the nation's top business executives forecast.
   The Business Council, composed of the chief executives of 100 of
the country's largest corporations, said Friday the economy began
to lose steam this summer. They predicted the sluggish period would
last through much of next year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CARBO, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole set up the
first face-to-face meeting between Pittston Coal Group Inc. and the
United Mine Workers since a bitter strike began six months ago.
   Mrs. Dole said Pittston Chairman Paul Douglas and UMW President
Richard Trumka agreed to meet with her Saturday in her Washington
office. It would mark the first time any company and union
officials have met directly since 1,695 miners in Virginia, West
Virginia and Kentucky went on strike April 5 against Pittston Coal
Group Inc.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young &amp; Rubicam, one of the nation's
largest advertising agencies, pleaded innocent to charges it paid
nearly $1 million in bribes to Jamaican officials for the island's
lucrative tourism campaign.
   Two of the company's executives and a former executive also
pleaded innocent Friday in U.S. District Court Friday.
   Young &amp; Rubicam faces up to $7.5 million in fines if it is
convicted. Young &amp; Rubicam still holds the Jamaica account, which
won praise for its theme ``Come Back to Jamaica,'' and has
vigorously denied any wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The biggest selloff since the crash of 1987 rocked the stock
market Friday, driving prices into a free-fall decline following
news that a big buyout deal for UAL Corp. had fallen through. The
Dow Jones average of 30 industrials plunged 190.58 points, or 6.91
percent, to 2,569.26.
   Currency dealers pounded down the dollar in hectic selling
incited by the stock plunge.
   Bond prices rocketed higher in heavy trading afternoon as
investors fled the panicky stock market.
   Tumbling stock prices triggered temporary trading halts for
stock-index futures on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, in a drop
that mirrored a near-record selloff on Wall Street; orange juice
futures plunged; and crude oil futures jumped higher.
