<DOCNO> AP891013-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-89 2337EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Market-Scene 1stLd-Writethru   10-13 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Market-Scene, 1st Ld-Writethru,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Traders Dazed, Worried After Big Drop</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, `Almost exactly... to CORRECT date to Oct.
16; PICKS UP 7th graf pvs, `Some predicted...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Market-Drop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH J. HARPAZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The plunge in stock prices left Wall Street
workers dazed, grim and debating whether another crash is coming
Monday.
   One man stood on a street corner across from the New York Stock
Exchange Friday, shook his head and said to a friend, ``I'm trying
to figure out whether I got my head handed to me.''
   Some financial workers went to drown their sorrows at Houlihan's
bar, around the corner from the exchange.
   One trader put down his beer, spread his hands two feet apart
and said: ``I've got a hole in my underwear this big.''
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks plunged 190.58
points Friday. Nearly $200 billion was wiped out from the paper
value of stocks as more than 250 million shares changed hands.
   Almost exactly two years ago, on Friday, Oct. 16, 1987, the Dow
Jones average dropped 108 points. That Monday _ Black Monday, Oct.
19, 1987 _ it plummeted 508 points.
   Some predicted a similar crash next week.
   ``There's going to be a huge selloff on Monday,'' said another
Houlihan's patron, John Durand, a bank stocks trader.
   ``I thought it was all over two years ago. But I never thought
it would happen again,'' said Anthony, a stock exchange floor
reporter who would not give his last name, as he left the building
after Friday's closing bell.
   ``I need a drink,'' he added.
   But stockbroker Bernard Klein was defiantly optimistic: ``This
is not going to be like Black Monday. The market is going to stick
on Monday, absolutely. What we had today was just panic selling.''
   Thomas Flanagan and Greg LaBorde, retail stockbrokers having an
after-work drink at the South Street Seaport near Wall Street, said
Friday's drop actually stirred up business.
   ``I got many, many buy orders at the close,'' LaBorde said. The
market drop creates bargains for investors who like to buy when
prices are low.
   LaBorde dismissed comparisons with the 1987 disaster.
   ``There were a lot more problems with the economy back then,''
he said.
   ``This time, it's nothing really,'' agreed Flanagan. ``It's just
an adjustment.''
   He added: ``We're bullish.''
   Options traders Larry Mendelson and Jeff Schure were not.
   Interviewed as they left their offices across the street from
the stock exchange, Mendelson said: ``Monday's going to be a scary
day. People have all weekend to think about this.''
   Schure added: ``Most people took hits today. One guy I know went
down for $150,000.''
   Many financial workers pointed to the failed leveraged buyout of
United Airlines parent UAL Corp. as the trigger for the plunge in
Friday's prices.
   But another patron of the South Street Seaport, Al, a bond traer
who would not give his last name, said he thought the UAL deal was
merely a symptom of a deeper illness.
   ``The country is not in the euphoric financial state everyone
says it is,'' he said. ``We've got a huge deficit and the thrift
industry is falling apart.
   ``The stock market is like a house of cards,'' he added. ``I see
more of this happening on Monday.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
